WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:02.410
- [Narrator] The British royal family we know today

00:00:02.810 --> 00:00:06.560
are just one generation amongst a remarkable monarchy

00:00:06.560 --> 00:00:09.290
spanning over 1,000 years.

00:00:09.290 --> 00:00:12.710
But how did an ancestry that once ruled the lands

00:00:12.710 --> 00:00:14.660
eventually forfeit power?

00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:17.750
With over a millennium of bloody succession wars,

00:00:17.750 --> 00:00:19.880
global conquests, betrayals,

00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:22.580
and grand stone buildings still standing tall,

00:00:22.580 --> 00:00:26.270
all the royal history has been documented and preserved.

00:00:26.270 --> 00:00:28.130
With countless kings and queens,

00:00:28.130 --> 00:00:30.020
each with their own stories,

00:00:30.020 --> 00:00:33.875
this is The Entire History of the British Monarchy.

00:00:33.875 --> 00:00:36.950
(ethereal music)

00:00:36.950 --> 00:00:39.410
Our story doesn't begin with the Scots

00:00:39.410 --> 00:00:41.330
or with the English for that matter,

00:00:41.330 --> 00:00:44.600
but with a Saxon prince named Egbert III.

00:00:44.600 --> 00:00:48.620
At the time of Egbert III's birth in 771 AD,

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:50.360
England did not exist.

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:53.210
Instead, the British Isles looked like this,

00:00:53.210 --> 00:00:55.430
a patchwork of warring kingdoms

00:00:55.430 --> 00:00:58.790
made up of Angles, Saxons, Jutes, and Britains,

00:00:58.790 --> 00:00:59.990
all fighting one another

00:00:59.990 --> 00:01:02.900
for control and influence over the dominion.

00:01:02.900 --> 00:01:04.970
Born to Ealhmund, King of Kent

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:07.550
and grandson of Eafa, King of Wessex,

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:08.990
the young prince Egbert

00:01:08.990 --> 00:01:12.200
had strong claims to both territories.

00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:14.357
His father died when Egbert was 10,

00:01:14.357 --> 00:01:17.420
and a bloody scramble for the crown ensued.

00:01:17.420 --> 00:01:19.040
It eventually came to rest

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:21.590
on the head of Beorhtric of Mercia.

00:01:21.590 --> 00:01:26.150
A young Egbert challenged Beorhtric's rule and lost.

00:01:26.150 --> 00:01:29.240
Forced to take refuge in the nearby court of Mercia

00:01:29.240 --> 00:01:32.210
and eventually sent into exile in Francia,

00:01:32.210 --> 00:01:34.760
Egbert was forced to abide his time.

00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:37.220
Learning from the French courts of Charlemagne

00:01:37.220 --> 00:01:38.540
and gaining experience

00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:40.760
as a military leader on the continent,

00:01:40.760 --> 00:01:42.320
Egbert grew into a king

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:45.710
who was about to change the course of English history.

00:01:45.710 --> 00:01:48.860
In 800 AD after the death of Beorhtric,

00:01:48.860 --> 00:01:50.480
Egbert crossed the channel,

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:52.460
returning to the land of his father,

00:01:52.460 --> 00:01:54.920
and made his claim to the throne of Wessex.

00:01:54.920 --> 00:01:57.620
Despite overwhelming support in both Europe

00:01:57.620 --> 00:01:59.600
and within the Wessex nobility,

00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:02.600
Egbert's ascension was by no means easy.

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:05.300
Threats from nearby kingdoms were constant.

00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:07.010
And after losing his brother-in-law

00:02:07.010 --> 00:02:11.090
on the day of his ascension to an invading army of Mercians,

00:02:11.090 --> 00:02:15.980
Egbert was finally crowned King of Wessex in 802 AD.

00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:19.670
Immediately, he set about consolidating his power.

00:02:19.670 --> 00:02:23.150
He took control of the kingdoms of Kent, Essex, Sussex,

00:02:23.150 --> 00:02:27.350
and Cornwall, as well as large swathes of Wales.

00:02:27.350 --> 00:02:30.410
Even the kingdom of Northumbria eventually submitted

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:34.122
to the crown of Wessex, placing all Anglo-Saxon kingdoms

00:02:34.122 --> 00:02:37.400
in Britain under the direct and indirect rule

00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:39.260
of Egbert of Wessex.

00:02:39.260 --> 00:02:41.480
Well, almost all.

00:02:41.480 --> 00:02:45.260
His old enemy, the kingdom of Mercia, was a different story.

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:46.640
The two sides had been locked

00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:49.610
in a constant state of warfare for centuries,

00:02:49.610 --> 00:02:52.070
with each kingdom trading territory and blood

00:02:52.070 --> 00:02:53.540
as the years wore on.

00:02:53.540 --> 00:02:56.420
King Egbert of Wessex would see brief success

00:02:56.420 --> 00:03:00.290
driving the king of Mercia wheel off out of his lands,

00:03:00.290 --> 00:03:01.760
but he was unable to hold them

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:04.460
and wheel off returned only a year later.

00:03:04.460 --> 00:03:07.340
Despite this though, the Anglo-Saxon chronicles

00:03:07.340 --> 00:03:09.350
remember Egbert favorably.

00:03:09.350 --> 00:03:13.190
For his role in uniting the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms of Britain,

00:03:13.190 --> 00:03:16.310
they bestowed unto him the title of Bretwalda,

00:03:16.310 --> 00:03:18.920
or Wide-Ruler of Britain.

00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:21.470
And while he was never able to fully conquer

00:03:21.470 --> 00:03:22.850
the Mercian crown,

00:03:22.850 --> 00:03:26.000
his rule changed the landscape of Britain forever.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.580
Egbert of Wessex set in motion a policy

00:03:28.580 --> 00:03:30.560
of consolidation and expansion

00:03:30.560 --> 00:03:33.110
that his offspring would continue to enforce

00:03:33.110 --> 00:03:35.270
for the next 200 years,

00:03:35.270 --> 00:03:38.030
eventually leading to the unification of Britain

00:03:38.030 --> 00:03:39.860
and the birth of England.

00:03:39.860 --> 00:03:43.126
But there's still a lot of miss before we get there.

00:03:43.126 --> 00:03:45.626
(light music)

00:03:49.160 --> 00:03:52.580
King Egbert of Wessex died in 839 AD

00:03:52.580 --> 00:03:55.550
and was succeeded by his eldest son, Aethelwulf,

00:03:55.550 --> 00:03:58.730
who soon faced a new threat, the Danes.

00:03:58.730 --> 00:04:00.260
Adorned in animal skins

00:04:00.260 --> 00:04:02.450
and brandishing axes stained with blood,

00:04:02.450 --> 00:04:04.853
the Danish invasion officially began an 842 AD.

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:08.011
While Aethelwulf was victorious

00:04:08.011 --> 00:04:11.090
at the Battle of Aclea in 851 AD,

00:04:11.090 --> 00:04:13.580
driving the Danes back into the seas,

00:04:13.580 --> 00:04:15.800
he knew that this was just the beginning.

00:04:15.800 --> 00:04:18.980
The new threat worried the kingdoms of Britain so much

00:04:18.980 --> 00:04:20.840
that it forced Mercia and Wessex

00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:23.390
into an uneasy alliance with one another,

00:04:23.390 --> 00:04:27.353
putting an end to an almost 300 year conflict.

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:31.520
(suspenseful music)

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:34.580
Aethelwulf was succeeded by his son, Aethelbald,

00:04:34.580 --> 00:04:36.980
whose reign was short and unpopular,

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:38.990
especially amongst the clergy.

00:04:38.990 --> 00:04:41.390
This was mainly because of the new king's decision

00:04:41.390 --> 00:04:43.460
to marry his father's widow,

00:04:43.460 --> 00:04:47.240
something that even at this time was considered weird.

00:04:47.240 --> 00:04:51.050
After just four years of rule, Aethelbald died,

00:04:51.050 --> 00:04:52.400
passing the crown of Wessex

00:04:52.400 --> 00:04:55.340
onto his younger brother, Aethelberht.

00:04:55.340 --> 00:04:57.840
(light music)

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:03.410
Like his father before him, Aethelberht too was threatened

00:05:03.410 --> 00:05:05.600
by foreign invaders from the North.

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:07.670
Viking raids along the coast

00:05:07.670 --> 00:05:11.600
led by Ragnar Lodbrok and his son Ivar the Boneless,

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:14.270
had been growing in violence in frequency,

00:05:14.270 --> 00:05:16.370
with Viking forces even sacking

00:05:16.370 --> 00:05:20.720
the Wessex capital of Winchester in 865 AD.

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:24.380
Aethelberht rallied his troops and drove the Vikings back,

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:27.170
but died of unknown causes that autumn,

00:05:27.170 --> 00:05:30.053
leaving the throne to his younger brother, Aethelred I,

00:05:30.950 --> 00:05:32.840
who was about to inherit an island

00:05:32.840 --> 00:05:35.481
on the verge of a major upheaval.

00:05:35.481 --> 00:05:38.314
(uplifting music)

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:44.300
The same year of Aethelred's ascension, 867 AD,

00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:47.180
the Vikings captured and settled the town of York,

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:50.180
establishing the first major Danish foothold

00:05:50.180 --> 00:05:51.500
on English soil.

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:53.240
Aethelred had no choice

00:05:53.240 --> 00:05:56.630
but to meet the great heathen army in battle.

00:05:56.630 --> 00:05:58.820
Together with his younger brother Alfred,

00:05:58.820 --> 00:05:59.930
they gathered an army

00:05:59.930 --> 00:06:02.690
and marched out to defeat their invaders.

00:06:02.690 --> 00:06:05.420
The cautious King Aethelred was defeated

00:06:05.420 --> 00:06:08.660
at the Battle of Reading in 871 AD,

00:06:08.660 --> 00:06:10.520
but was saved by his younger brother

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:13.400
at the Battle of Ashdown the same year.

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:17.000
Impatient, as only the young are, Alfred took his army

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:18.890
while King Aethelred prayed

00:06:18.890 --> 00:06:21.590
and met the Danes in open battle.

00:06:21.590 --> 00:06:23.480
He pushed the Viking hoard back

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:25.700
and bought his brother's kingdom some time,

00:06:25.700 --> 00:06:27.080
but the Danes rallied

00:06:27.080 --> 00:06:29.450
and struck the armies of Wessex again,

00:06:29.450 --> 00:06:32.690
securing victories at the battles of Basing and Merton.

00:06:32.690 --> 00:06:34.610
Aethelred died from his wounds,

00:06:34.610 --> 00:06:37.250
leaving the throne to his younger brother Alfred,

00:06:37.250 --> 00:06:40.973
who now inherited a kingdom on the brink of collapse.

00:06:42.470 --> 00:06:45.220
(dramatic music)

00:06:46.310 --> 00:06:49.220
In 874 AD, the great heathen army

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:51.170
marched on the kingdom of Mercia,

00:06:51.170 --> 00:06:53.180
defeating Burgred of Mercia

00:06:53.180 --> 00:06:55.790
and forcing the king into exile.

00:06:55.790 --> 00:06:57.410
With Mercia defeated,

00:06:57.410 --> 00:06:59.510
all that stood between the northern invaders

00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:02.270
and total control of England was Alfred

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:04.010
and the kingdom of Wessex.

00:07:04.010 --> 00:07:07.310
As Danish forces closed in all around him,

00:07:07.310 --> 00:07:08.570
Alfred was pushed back

00:07:08.570 --> 00:07:11.420
and forced into a remote marsh in Somerset.

00:07:11.420 --> 00:07:15.350
He'd been betrayed by his allies who now chose to negotiate

00:07:15.350 --> 00:07:17.360
with the invaders rather than fight.

00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:20.600
Total Danish control of Britain looked imminent,

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:23.330
but the young king had not given up hope.

00:07:23.330 --> 00:07:24.710
He emerged from the marsh

00:07:24.710 --> 00:07:27.290
and surprised the Danish army in Edington,

00:07:27.290 --> 00:07:29.180
chasing the Danish king Guthrum

00:07:29.180 --> 00:07:30.980
back to his base in Chippenham

00:07:30.980 --> 00:07:33.590
and forcing the Danes into a siege.

00:07:33.590 --> 00:07:35.450
Guthrum held out for two weeks

00:07:35.450 --> 00:07:37.790
before he surrendered to Alfred's forces,

00:07:37.790 --> 00:07:40.010
and Alfred was victorious.

00:07:40.010 --> 00:07:41.360
The terms were simple.

00:07:41.360 --> 00:07:46.360
Guthrum was to leave Wessex and receive a Christian baptism.

00:07:46.940 --> 00:07:48.620
The Danish king obliged,

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:51.650
and after his baptism was solemnized at Wedmore,

00:07:51.650 --> 00:07:53.510
he retreated to East Anglia,

00:07:53.510 --> 00:07:56.060
leaving Alfred to consolidate his gains.

00:07:56.060 --> 00:08:00.260
Victorious, Alfred took on a new name, Alfred the Great.

00:08:00.260 --> 00:08:02.120
With the Viking threat tamed,

00:08:02.120 --> 00:08:05.600
Alfred set about transforming Anglo-Saxon society

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:06.560
for the better.

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:09.440
He established fortified towns throughout his kingdom,

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:12.770
built schools, and encouraged the acquisition of knowledge.

00:08:12.770 --> 00:08:15.410
There's even an unsubstantiated myth

00:08:15.410 --> 00:08:17.960
that he founded Oxford University.

00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:20.300
But perhaps his most important policy

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:22.820
was the establishment of Dane Law.

00:08:22.820 --> 00:08:24.830
England was to be divided.

00:08:24.830 --> 00:08:27.440
The south and east belonged to the Saxons,

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:29.180
and Saxon law applied.

00:08:29.180 --> 00:08:31.550
While the north and west belonged to the Danes,

00:08:31.550 --> 00:08:34.070
and thus were subject to Dane Law.

00:08:34.070 --> 00:08:37.370
This divide is still seen culturally, politically,

00:08:37.370 --> 00:08:40.280
and financially in Britain today.

00:08:40.280 --> 00:08:44.510
Alfred brought Anglo-Saxon England into a golden age.

00:08:44.510 --> 00:08:46.340
He tamed the Danish threat

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:49.010
and kickstarted a new age of Saxon rule

00:08:49.010 --> 00:08:52.793
that permanently changed the landscape of Britain forever.

00:08:54.496 --> 00:08:57.380
(suspenseful music)

00:08:57.380 --> 00:08:58.850
Alfred the Great was succeeded

00:08:58.850 --> 00:09:02.750
by his son, Edward the Elder, in 899 AD.

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:05.240
Edward was in many ways like his father,

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:09.080
learned, pious, and a keen military tactician.

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:11.360
His reign focused on two things,

00:09:11.360 --> 00:09:13.700
improving the administration of his lands

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:17.120
and increased expansion both north and south.

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:20.210
He was able to capture the Viking capital of York,

00:09:20.210 --> 00:09:21.650
but only held it for a year

00:09:21.650 --> 00:09:23.660
before he was forced to abandon it.

00:09:23.660 --> 00:09:26.990
He also successfully defeated the Viking presence

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:30.020
in southern England, and now either directly

00:09:30.020 --> 00:09:33.590
or indirectly ruled over all the old kingdoms,

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:37.040
barring Northumbria, which was still under Viking control.

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:41.300
Edward the Elder died in 924 AD from wounds he received

00:09:41.300 --> 00:09:44.330
while quashing a Mercian rebellion in Chester,

00:09:44.330 --> 00:09:47.435
and passed his crown onto his son Athelstan.

00:09:47.435 --> 00:09:49.935
(light music)

00:09:52.370 --> 00:09:54.860
After consolidating his power at home,

00:09:54.860 --> 00:09:56.870
Athelstan set his sights north

00:09:56.870 --> 00:09:59.090
and did what his father could not.

00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:01.520
He conquered the kingdom of Northumbria

00:10:01.520 --> 00:10:04.430
and took control of the Viking capital of York,

00:10:04.430 --> 00:10:07.580
conquering the last Viking territory on the island

00:10:07.580 --> 00:10:10.040
and pushing the Danes into Scotland.

00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:13.220
He continued his campaign into the Scottish territories,

00:10:13.220 --> 00:10:15.547
and after heavy losses on both sides,

00:10:15.547 --> 00:10:18.950
he emerged victorious at the Battle of Brunanburh,

00:10:18.950 --> 00:10:22.910
forcing the Scottish king to pledge overlordship to him.

00:10:22.910 --> 00:10:25.130
This made him the first true ruler

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:28.340
over all the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms in Britain,

00:10:28.340 --> 00:10:31.460
with his control extending from the shores of Cornwall

00:10:31.460 --> 00:10:33.440
up to the highlands of Scotland.

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:35.450
By uniting the Anglo-Saxons,

00:10:35.450 --> 00:10:37.940
Athelstan formed the Kingdom of England,

00:10:37.940 --> 00:10:41.690
and as thus remembered as the first real English king.

00:10:41.690 --> 00:10:44.810
With the realm now firmly under his control,

00:10:44.810 --> 00:10:47.150
King Athelstan continued the policies

00:10:47.150 --> 00:10:50.420
and reforms of his grandfather, Alfred the Great.

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:52.010
He centralized government,

00:10:52.010 --> 00:10:54.800
brought about massive legal reform in the realm,

00:10:54.800 --> 00:10:57.440
and concerned himself with European politics

00:10:57.440 --> 00:11:00.350
in a way his predecessors seldom had.

00:11:00.350 --> 00:11:03.620
He died in 939 AD, passing the throne

00:11:03.620 --> 00:11:06.773
onto his half brother, Edmund the Magnificent.

00:11:08.182 --> 00:11:11.060
(gentle music)

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:14.090
Edmund's reign would be almost entirely focused

00:11:14.090 --> 00:11:16.760
on keeping his half brother's kingdom together.

00:11:16.760 --> 00:11:19.430
He faced continuous threats from the Danish

00:11:19.430 --> 00:11:21.530
who had now settled north of the border.

00:11:21.530 --> 00:11:23.390
Shortly after Edmund's ascension,

00:11:23.390 --> 00:11:26.360
they revolted against the new king, retaking York

00:11:26.360 --> 00:11:29.330
and mounting destructive raids on the Midlands.

00:11:29.330 --> 00:11:30.980
But like his predecessor,

00:11:30.980 --> 00:11:34.160
Edmund the Magnificent wasn't to be messed with.

00:11:34.160 --> 00:11:36.470
Leading his army north, he briefly stopped

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:39.230
to quash a Welsh rebellion that had been brewing

00:11:39.230 --> 00:11:41.570
since before Athelstan's death.

00:11:41.570 --> 00:11:44.690
He then defeated the Danes at the siege of Leicester

00:11:44.690 --> 00:11:46.730
and sent his armies into Scotland,

00:11:46.730 --> 00:11:49.400
seeking revenge against the king of Strathclyde

00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:51.560
for his decision to decide with a Danish

00:11:51.560 --> 00:11:53.510
during the recapturing of York.

00:11:53.510 --> 00:11:55.640
He'd opposed the king of Strathclyde

00:11:55.640 --> 00:11:59.360
and installed Malcolm I of Scotland on the condition

00:11:59.360 --> 00:12:02.600
that Edmund would have overlordship of the territory.

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:06.350
This gave Edmund control directly and indirectly

00:12:06.350 --> 00:12:09.290
of the entire island of Great Britain.

00:12:09.290 --> 00:12:11.240
But for all his successes,

00:12:11.240 --> 00:12:14.805
Edmund the Magnificent could not escape a violent death.

00:12:14.805 --> 00:12:19.340
In 946 AD while attending a Saint Augustine's Mass

00:12:19.340 --> 00:12:21.710
in Gloucestershire, Edmund was attacked

00:12:21.710 --> 00:12:24.170
and killed by a thief named Leofa

00:12:24.170 --> 00:12:27.350
who the king had previously banished for his crimes.

00:12:27.350 --> 00:12:30.710
Edmund the Magnificent was buried at Glastonbury Abbey

00:12:30.710 --> 00:12:34.013
and the realms scrambled to find his successor.

00:12:35.519 --> 00:12:38.480
(light music)

00:12:38.480 --> 00:12:41.270
Since Edmund's two sons were too young to rule,

00:12:41.270 --> 00:12:44.690
the burden of the crown fell to Edmund's brother, Eadred,

00:12:44.690 --> 00:12:47.180
who reigned for nine years before succumbing

00:12:47.180 --> 00:12:51.530
to an unknown intestinal illness in 955 AD.

00:12:51.530 --> 00:12:54.800
Edmund's eldest son Eadwig was now 15

00:12:54.800 --> 00:12:56.690
and took the crown as his own.

00:12:56.690 --> 00:12:59.030
He decided to split the realm between himself

00:12:59.030 --> 00:13:00.650
and his younger brother Edgar,

00:13:00.650 --> 00:13:03.260
ruling everything south of the river Thames,

00:13:03.260 --> 00:13:05.000
while Edgar ruled the North.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.450
King Eadwig's reign was short, with the young king dying

00:13:08.450 --> 00:13:11.150
just four years after his coronation.

00:13:11.150 --> 00:13:13.640
He passed the Kingdom of England in its entirety

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:18.640
to his younger brother, Edgar the Peaceful in 959 AD.

00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:21.470
His reign was, as the name might suggest,

00:13:21.470 --> 00:13:24.890
considered a peaceful golden age where England was free

00:13:24.890 --> 00:13:28.010
from external attacks and internal disorder.

00:13:28.010 --> 00:13:31.220
He introduced a standardized coinage and was at the helm

00:13:31.220 --> 00:13:33.890
of the English Benedictine religious reforms

00:13:33.890 --> 00:13:37.910
that swept across the realm, but this peace did not last.

00:13:37.910 --> 00:13:41.570
His death in 975 AD thrust England back

00:13:41.570 --> 00:13:44.693
into a period of conflict and uncertainty.

00:13:46.308 --> 00:13:48.808
(light music)

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:53.420
The throne was disrupted by Edgar's two remaining sons,

00:13:53.420 --> 00:13:56.660
Edward the Martyr and Aethelred the Unready.

00:13:56.660 --> 00:14:00.260
Edward successfully took the throne in 975 AD,

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:03.740
but was murdered just four years later in circumstances

00:14:03.740 --> 00:14:05.810
not totally clear to us today.

00:14:05.810 --> 00:14:08.480
His younger brother Aethelred soon took charge

00:14:08.480 --> 00:14:10.940
at just 12 years old.

00:14:10.940 --> 00:14:14.480
Before the young king had even a hair on his chin,

00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:17.450
an old enemy reared from far in the north.

00:14:17.450 --> 00:14:19.130
The Danes had returned

00:14:19.130 --> 00:14:22.100
and set about raiding English territories again.

00:14:22.100 --> 00:14:25.160
With every year, the threat grew more serious,

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:26.570
and soon the English king

00:14:26.570 --> 00:14:29.240
could not afford to ignore them any longer.

00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:31.490
He gathered his armies and march north,

00:14:31.490 --> 00:14:34.580
but was eventually defeated at the Battle of Maldon.

00:14:34.580 --> 00:14:38.390
Seeking a compromise, King Aethelred II was forced

00:14:38.390 --> 00:14:40.130
to pay off the Danish king

00:14:40.130 --> 00:14:43.460
and leave them to settle in the kingdom of Northumbria,

00:14:43.460 --> 00:14:46.790
but as it turns out, the king was not content

00:14:46.790 --> 00:14:48.890
to just let the invaders be.

00:14:48.890 --> 00:14:50.750
A decade after his defeat,

00:14:50.750 --> 00:14:54.770
he ordered the infamous St. Brice's Day massacre,

00:14:54.770 --> 00:14:57.500
a brutal slaughtering of a Danish settlement

00:14:57.500 --> 00:15:00.860
which had dire consequences to not only his rule,

00:15:00.860 --> 00:15:04.040
but his entire family's place in history.

00:15:04.040 --> 00:15:06.050
Hearing of the attack on his people,

00:15:06.050 --> 00:15:09.680
King Sweyn Forkbeard of Denmark sailed to England,

00:15:09.680 --> 00:15:13.530
forcing Aethelred to flee to Normandy in 1013 AD.

00:15:13.530 --> 00:15:17.780
Sweyn Forkbeard ruled over England for just four weeks

00:15:17.780 --> 00:15:20.810
before his sudden and mysterious death.

00:15:20.810 --> 00:15:22.370
Seizing the opportunity,

00:15:22.370 --> 00:15:26.150
Aethelred returned and quickly retook control of the crown.

00:15:26.150 --> 00:15:28.640
Despite the brief Danish interruption,

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:30.680
Aethelred's 37 year reign

00:15:30.680 --> 00:15:33.920
was the longest of any Anglo-Saxon king,

00:15:33.920 --> 00:15:37.040
and it would become the last period of royal stability

00:15:37.040 --> 00:15:41.988
until the 12th century almost 100 years later.

00:15:41.988 --> 00:15:44.571
(bright music)

00:15:45.950 --> 00:15:49.607
King Aethelred the Unready died in 1016 AD,

00:15:49.607 --> 00:15:53.330
and the crown was passed onto his son, Edmund Ironside,

00:15:53.330 --> 00:15:55.610
who, like so many of those before him,

00:15:55.610 --> 00:15:58.880
was now forced to clean up the mess his father had made.

00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:00.800
You see, unbeknownst to Edmund,

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:04.190
the Danish King Sweyn had a son, Canute the Great,

00:16:04.190 --> 00:16:06.470
who had been amassing an army in Denmark

00:16:06.470 --> 00:16:08.660
in preparing it to sail to England.

00:16:08.660 --> 00:16:11.120
Just weeks after the death of his father

00:16:11.120 --> 00:16:14.300
and with the coronation wine barely out of his system,

00:16:14.300 --> 00:16:18.320
Edmund was forced to meet Canute and the Danes in battle.

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:20.240
He was unsuccessful.

00:16:20.240 --> 00:16:22.970
With Edmund wounded, the two reached an agreement.

00:16:22.970 --> 00:16:25.790
Edmund Ironside was to rule Wessex,

00:16:25.790 --> 00:16:29.030
while Canute could have the rest of the country.

00:16:29.030 --> 00:16:30.950
This was October 30th.

00:16:30.950 --> 00:16:33.680
By November 18th, Edmund was dead

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:37.580
and Canute assumed kingship over the entire realm.

00:16:37.580 --> 00:16:41.930
After 214 years of hegemony, the House of Wessex

00:16:41.930 --> 00:16:45.170
had officially lost its control over England,

00:16:45.170 --> 00:16:50.090
ruling uninterrupted since Egbert III in 802 AD.

00:16:50.090 --> 00:16:52.784
1016 would prove to be the dawn of a new age

00:16:52.784 --> 00:16:56.731
on the British Isles, the Age of Danes.

00:16:56.731 --> 00:16:59.314
(bright music)

00:17:00.890 --> 00:17:03.890
After centuries of Danish activity on the island,

00:17:03.890 --> 00:17:06.920
a Danish king now sat on the English throne.

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:10.430
Canute the Great was crowned in 1016 AD

00:17:10.430 --> 00:17:13.580
and wasted no time proving he was an astute leader

00:17:13.580 --> 00:17:15.170
and capable king.

00:17:15.170 --> 00:17:17.450
He understood that to rule the English

00:17:17.450 --> 00:17:18.980
he would need their help.

00:17:18.980 --> 00:17:21.800
He appointed English councilors and clergymen,

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:23.960
choosing to uphold the traditional customs

00:17:23.960 --> 00:17:26.090
and values of the land he'd inherited

00:17:26.090 --> 00:17:27.920
rather than to suppress them.

00:17:27.920 --> 00:17:30.470
He married the widow of Aethelred the Unready

00:17:30.470 --> 00:17:33.230
and allied himself closely to the church,

00:17:33.230 --> 00:17:38.230
all of which helped Canute cement his legitimacy in 1017 AD.

00:17:38.270 --> 00:17:41.120
In 1018, he was crowned king of Denmark

00:17:41.120 --> 00:17:44.870
and later conquered Sweden, uniting the three kingdoms

00:17:44.870 --> 00:17:47.360
to create the North Sea Alliance.

00:17:47.360 --> 00:17:50.870
Medieval historians look back on Canute's reign favorably.

00:17:50.870 --> 00:17:53.180
His presence brought stability to England

00:17:53.180 --> 00:17:54.860
and allowed the realm to flourish

00:17:54.860 --> 00:17:58.340
now that the threat of Viking raiders had been eliminated.

00:17:58.340 --> 00:18:00.590
He died in 1035 AD,

00:18:00.590 --> 00:18:04.013
and the crown was to be given to his son, Harold Harefoot.

00:18:05.682 --> 00:18:08.840
(ethereal music)

00:18:08.840 --> 00:18:11.570
Harold did not bend the first choice for succession,

00:18:11.570 --> 00:18:14.600
but with his older brother Hardicnut stuck in Norway

00:18:14.600 --> 00:18:18.080
dealing with a Swedish rebellion, therefore, it was decided

00:18:18.080 --> 00:18:20.690
that Harold would be appointed king instead.

00:18:20.690 --> 00:18:22.820
This was not a popular decision

00:18:22.820 --> 00:18:24.620
and many in the realm opposed it,

00:18:24.620 --> 00:18:27.440
most notably Godwin the Earl of Wessex

00:18:27.440 --> 00:18:30.260
and Emma of Normandy, Harold's stepmother

00:18:30.260 --> 00:18:32.660
and the widow of Aethelred the Unready.

00:18:32.660 --> 00:18:35.390
She'd had two other sons while with Aethelred,

00:18:35.390 --> 00:18:37.580
both of whom had been exiled to Normandy

00:18:37.580 --> 00:18:39.560
after the Danish conquest.

00:18:39.560 --> 00:18:41.750
But now with Hardicnut absent

00:18:41.750 --> 00:18:44.810
and Harold struggling to consolidate his power,

00:18:44.810 --> 00:18:47.060
she called on them to return to England

00:18:47.060 --> 00:18:49.730
and take back their father's throne.

00:18:49.730 --> 00:18:52.100
Alfred the Noble and Edward the Confessor

00:18:52.100 --> 00:18:54.770
sailed across the channel with a large army

00:18:54.770 --> 00:18:57.470
and sought support from the House of Wessex.

00:18:57.470 --> 00:19:00.230
But Godwin, who'd initially opposed Harold's claim

00:19:00.230 --> 00:19:03.020
to the throne, betrayed the young princes

00:19:03.020 --> 00:19:04.670
and seized Alfred the Noble

00:19:04.670 --> 00:19:07.913
with the aim of delivering him to Harold Harefoot.

00:19:08.780 --> 00:19:10.280
Fearing he would be next,

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:12.890
Edward the Confessor fled back to Normandy,

00:19:12.890 --> 00:19:15.680
this time taking his mother with him to safety.

00:19:15.680 --> 00:19:19.040
During his captivity, Alfred the Noble was blinded

00:19:19.040 --> 00:19:23.090
and eventually succumbed to his wounds in 1036 AD.

00:19:23.090 --> 00:19:25.760
Harold would rule for just four more years

00:19:25.760 --> 00:19:28.146
before dying in 1040.

00:19:28.146 --> 00:19:30.646
(light music)

00:19:31.910 --> 00:19:33.980
Hearing of his half brother's passing,

00:19:33.980 --> 00:19:36.290
Hardicnut returned from Scandinavia

00:19:36.290 --> 00:19:39.890
and crowned himself king of England that same year.

00:19:39.890 --> 00:19:42.830
But like his brother, his reign too would be short,

00:19:42.830 --> 00:19:47.060
and he died in 1042 AD from an unknown illness.

00:19:47.060 --> 00:19:50.210
He had no sons, and during the last years of his life,

00:19:50.210 --> 00:19:53.330
perhaps encouraged by his mother, Emma of Normandy,

00:19:53.330 --> 00:19:55.760
he called this half brother Edward the Confessor

00:19:55.760 --> 00:19:59.240
back from exile and named him as his heir.

00:19:59.240 --> 00:20:02.780
King Hardicnut's passing would mark the last time a Dane sat

00:20:02.780 --> 00:20:04.163
on the English throne.

00:20:05.618 --> 00:20:08.720
(bright music)

00:20:08.720 --> 00:20:10.520
With Edward now on the throne,

00:20:10.520 --> 00:20:14.090
England was once again ruled by an Anglo-Saxon king,

00:20:14.090 --> 00:20:17.870
except Edward was only really Anglo-Saxon by blood.

00:20:17.870 --> 00:20:21.770
He'd spent 25 years of his life in exile in Normandy,

00:20:21.770 --> 00:20:26.000
and as a result, had an extremely Norman outlook on things.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:29.360
He appointed Norman councilors and Norman church leaders

00:20:29.360 --> 00:20:33.140
and opted to speak French as opposed to old English.

00:20:33.140 --> 00:20:36.920
He is best remembered as the founder of Westminster Abbey,

00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:40.730
still a major landmark in use in London today.

00:20:40.730 --> 00:20:44.450
As his life drew to an end and with no sons to succeed him,

00:20:44.450 --> 00:20:46.760
Edward was expected to choose an heir.

00:20:46.760 --> 00:20:50.330
He was left with two options, Harold Godwinson,

00:20:50.330 --> 00:20:54.560
a prominent earl of Wessex, and William, Duke of Normandy.

00:20:54.560 --> 00:20:57.170
Choosing Harold made more political sense.

00:20:57.170 --> 00:21:00.560
He was Anglo-Saxon and came from a prominent family

00:21:00.560 --> 00:21:03.770
with ties to both the court of King Edward the Confessor

00:21:03.770 --> 00:21:06.710
and the former Danish king, Canute the Great.

00:21:06.710 --> 00:21:09.350
Meanwhile, William had been an aide to Edward

00:21:09.350 --> 00:21:11.300
during his exile in Normandy

00:21:11.300 --> 00:21:14.240
and was related to the Anglo-Saxon king

00:21:14.240 --> 00:21:17.150
through Emma of Normandy, who was his aunt.

00:21:17.150 --> 00:21:20.570
The issues that arose from Edward the Confessor's succession

00:21:20.570 --> 00:21:23.450
was that it wasn't clear what the king had wanted.

00:21:23.450 --> 00:21:26.360
There are rumors that he'd promised the throne to William,

00:21:26.360 --> 00:21:28.490
but those claims are unsupported.

00:21:28.490 --> 00:21:31.111
In 1065 AD, Edward the Confessor

00:21:31.111 --> 00:21:33.500
slipped suddenly into a coma,

00:21:33.500 --> 00:21:37.460
never clarifying who was to take over the English crown.

00:21:37.460 --> 00:21:41.150
Edward died on the 5th of January, 1066.

00:21:41.150 --> 00:21:44.090
A day later, Harold was crowned king of England

00:21:44.090 --> 00:21:46.550
at the newly built Westminster Abbey.

00:21:46.550 --> 00:21:49.070
Upon hearing the news of Harold's ascension,

00:21:49.070 --> 00:21:51.260
William of Normandy was outraged

00:21:51.260 --> 00:21:53.750
and began preparing to invade the island.

00:21:53.750 --> 00:21:56.510
What followed was a brief period of warfare

00:21:56.510 --> 00:21:59.213
that was about to shape England forever.

00:22:00.665 --> 00:22:03.770
(energetic music)

00:22:03.770 --> 00:22:07.430
King Harold found himself in an unfavorable position.

00:22:07.430 --> 00:22:09.500
He knew of William's invasion force

00:22:09.500 --> 00:22:11.720
and gathered his armies along the coast,

00:22:11.720 --> 00:22:14.180
expecting the Norman duke to set sail soon

00:22:14.180 --> 00:22:15.710
after he had been crowned.

00:22:15.710 --> 00:22:16.940
But William didn't.

00:22:16.940 --> 00:22:19.640
Bad weather made the channel too rough to sail across,

00:22:19.640 --> 00:22:22.040
and William was forced to postpone his invasion

00:22:22.040 --> 00:22:23.570
by several months.

00:22:23.570 --> 00:22:26.630
Back in England and with provisions starting to run out,

00:22:26.630 --> 00:22:30.560
Harold was forced to disband his army and return to London.

00:22:30.560 --> 00:22:34.670
That same day on the 8th of September, 1066,

00:22:34.670 --> 00:22:38.870
a new threat appeared, only this time far up north.

00:22:38.870 --> 00:22:43.100
Harold Hardrada, King of Norway, had arrived in Northumbria,

00:22:43.100 --> 00:22:44.870
and defeated the English earls

00:22:44.870 --> 00:22:47.510
in charge of protecting the northern kingdoms.

00:22:47.510 --> 00:22:49.670
Harold had no choice but to react.

00:22:49.670 --> 00:22:51.530
He hastily regrouped his army

00:22:51.530 --> 00:22:55.460
and began a forced march north of nearly 400 kilometers

00:22:55.460 --> 00:22:57.470
to meet the Viking invaders.

00:22:57.470 --> 00:22:59.990
It took four days for King Harold and his men

00:22:59.990 --> 00:23:03.980
to reach modern day Yorkshire, but on the 25th of September,

00:23:03.980 --> 00:23:06.380
they faced off against the Norwegian army

00:23:06.380 --> 00:23:08.360
at the Battle of Stamford Bridge.

00:23:08.360 --> 00:23:10.100
Just outside the city of York,

00:23:10.100 --> 00:23:13.490
the English army clashed with the Norse invaders.

00:23:13.490 --> 00:23:17.240
Hardrada was killed and Harold emerged victorious,

00:23:17.240 --> 00:23:20.120
stopping the invasion dead in its tracks.

00:23:20.120 --> 00:23:22.190
But Harold had little time to rest.

00:23:22.190 --> 00:23:25.460
Just two days after his victory at Stamford Bridge,

00:23:25.460 --> 00:23:28.340
word reached the king that the Norman invasion fleet

00:23:28.340 --> 00:23:30.980
had finally set sail for England.

00:23:30.980 --> 00:23:32.840
He gathered what many he had left

00:23:32.840 --> 00:23:36.380
and began the 400 kilometer march back

00:23:36.380 --> 00:23:37.970
to the English capital.

00:23:37.970 --> 00:23:39.800
Meanwhile, William of Normandy

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:44.690
and around 7,000 men landed at Pevensey Bay in East Sussex

00:23:44.690 --> 00:23:46.100
and quickly took control

00:23:46.100 --> 00:23:48.800
of the old Roman fortifications nearby.

00:23:48.800 --> 00:23:51.440
It took King Harold and his army a week

00:23:51.440 --> 00:23:53.630
to reach the southern English coast,

00:23:53.630 --> 00:23:56.060
and Harold hoped his speech would catch William

00:23:56.060 --> 00:23:58.190
and his men by surprise.

00:23:58.190 --> 00:24:01.490
But Norman scouts had spotted Harald's army moving down

00:24:01.490 --> 00:24:04.220
and warned William of the king's arrival.

00:24:04.220 --> 00:24:08.360
On October 14th, 1066, a date forever etched

00:24:08.360 --> 00:24:12.770
in the annals of British history, the two armies clashed.

00:24:12.770 --> 00:24:16.520
The battle began at 9:00 AM and lasted the entire day.

00:24:16.520 --> 00:24:19.310
The English shield walls initially stood strong,

00:24:19.310 --> 00:24:21.920
surprising the Norman duke and forcing him back,

00:24:21.920 --> 00:24:24.080
but William had come prepared.

00:24:24.080 --> 00:24:26.360
While Harold had only foot soldiers,

00:24:26.360 --> 00:24:28.850
the Norman duke had brought with him cavalry

00:24:28.850 --> 00:24:31.670
and archers to supplement his main force.

00:24:31.670 --> 00:24:33.740
The Norman army feigned a retreat,

00:24:33.740 --> 00:24:36.770
which prompted the English troops to rush forward.

00:24:36.770 --> 00:24:38.540
This allowed the Norman cavalryman

00:24:38.540 --> 00:24:41.420
to route the disorganized English foot soldiers

00:24:41.420 --> 00:24:43.640
and slaughter them where they stood.

00:24:43.640 --> 00:24:47.270
Harold, the last Anglo-Saxon king of England,

00:24:47.270 --> 00:24:50.600
was killed by an arrow which struck him in the eye.

00:24:50.600 --> 00:24:52.970
Harold's mother reportedly begged William

00:24:52.970 --> 00:24:56.960
for her son's body back, offering to pay his weight in gold

00:24:56.960 --> 00:24:59.690
for custody of her son's corpse.

00:24:59.690 --> 00:25:02.090
But William refused.

00:25:02.090 --> 00:25:04.790
Legend has it he threw the body into the ocean,

00:25:04.790 --> 00:25:07.040
allowing the waves of the English Channel

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:10.970
to swallow the Saxon king, never to be seen again.

00:25:10.970 --> 00:25:13.640
William of Normandy was victorious.

00:25:13.640 --> 00:25:14.960
He marched on London,

00:25:14.960 --> 00:25:16.880
burning his way through southern England

00:25:16.880 --> 00:25:20.630
and forcing lords to swear fealty to him as he went.

00:25:20.630 --> 00:25:23.780
He was crowned on Christmas Day, 1066,

00:25:23.780 --> 00:25:26.930
marking the beginning of the Norman age of England.

00:25:26.930 --> 00:25:28.880
His ascension to the English throne

00:25:28.880 --> 00:25:32.843
earned the Norman duke a new name, William the Conqueror.

00:25:34.338 --> 00:25:37.520
(suspenseful music)

00:25:37.520 --> 00:25:39.290
As king by conquest,

00:25:39.290 --> 00:25:41.960
William now faced the unenviable challenge

00:25:41.960 --> 00:25:43.880
of consolidating his power.

00:25:43.880 --> 00:25:46.520
He brutally punished those who had stood against him

00:25:46.520 --> 00:25:50.300
by confiscating their lands, removing their royal titles

00:25:50.300 --> 00:25:54.020
and executing anyone he deemed a threat to his rule.

00:25:54.020 --> 00:25:56.840
Families that had remained neutral during the invasion

00:25:56.840 --> 00:25:59.900
or were quick to pledge their support to William after it

00:25:59.900 --> 00:26:02.810
were rewarded and allowed to continue operating

00:26:02.810 --> 00:26:04.220
as they had before.

00:26:04.220 --> 00:26:07.940
Some were even allowed to marry into the new royal family.

00:26:07.940 --> 00:26:09.260
But a change in leadership

00:26:09.260 --> 00:26:11.330
was not all William brought with him.

00:26:11.330 --> 00:26:14.450
One of his most enduring policies was the construction

00:26:14.450 --> 00:26:17.450
of motte-and-bailey castles throughout his kingdom.

00:26:17.450 --> 00:26:20.480
Initially made from wood and later rebuilt with stone,

00:26:20.480 --> 00:26:23.450
these fortifications became the landmark feature

00:26:23.450 --> 00:26:25.310
of William's rule in England.

00:26:25.310 --> 00:26:27.560
From Pevensey where he first landed

00:26:27.560 --> 00:26:30.470
to as far north as modern day Newcastle,

00:26:30.470 --> 00:26:33.230
these buildings were a sign of William's strength

00:26:33.230 --> 00:26:35.150
and influence over the land.

00:26:35.150 --> 00:26:37.880
Historians estimate that around 500

00:26:37.880 --> 00:26:39.290
of these castles were built

00:26:39.290 --> 00:26:42.950
within the first 20 years of Norman rule alone,

00:26:42.950 --> 00:26:45.890
and they gave William and those loyal to him a position

00:26:45.890 --> 00:26:47.600
from which to defend themselves

00:26:47.600 --> 00:26:52.070
against revolts and usurpers, of which there were many.

00:26:52.070 --> 00:26:55.550
Williams's first test came when his former ally Eustace,

00:26:55.550 --> 00:26:58.280
the Count of Boulogne, rebelled at Dover.

00:26:58.280 --> 00:27:00.680
Unhappy with his spoils of the conquest,

00:27:00.680 --> 00:27:03.140
he rallied local troops against the king

00:27:03.140 --> 00:27:05.540
and attempted to take Dover Castle,

00:27:05.540 --> 00:27:09.110
but he failed and was forced to return the land he had won.

00:27:09.110 --> 00:27:11.210
Next, the king was faced with a number

00:27:11.210 --> 00:27:13.670
of English rebellions further inland.

00:27:13.670 --> 00:27:17.390
There was Eadric the Wild in Wessex, as well as Gytha,

00:27:17.390 --> 00:27:19.280
mother of Harold Godwinson,

00:27:19.280 --> 00:27:21.830
organizing revolts as south as Exeter.

00:27:21.830 --> 00:27:24.440
William dealt with those rebellions swiftly

00:27:24.440 --> 00:27:26.990
and with relatively little bloodshed.

00:27:26.990 --> 00:27:31.010
But in 1069 AD, the north rose up in revolt

00:27:31.010 --> 00:27:33.620
and William responded in what would later be known

00:27:33.620 --> 00:27:35.780
as the Harrying of the North.

00:27:35.780 --> 00:27:39.650
It was a put down so brutal that it left the areas of York

00:27:39.650 --> 00:27:43.880
and Durham underpopulated for centuries after,

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:45.920
but his show of force had done its job.

00:27:45.920 --> 00:27:48.650
England was now firmly in his control.

00:27:48.650 --> 00:27:51.140
With this stability, the king felt confident enough

00:27:51.140 --> 00:27:52.517
to travel between England

00:27:52.517 --> 00:27:55.100
and the continent with increasing frequency.

00:27:55.100 --> 00:27:58.220
After 1072, he gave up making the journey

00:27:58.220 --> 00:28:00.590
and spent the majority of his time in Normandy,

00:28:00.590 --> 00:28:01.910
leaving England to be ruled

00:28:01.910 --> 00:28:04.370
by his half-brother Odo of Bayeux

00:28:04.370 --> 00:28:07.070
and his wife Matilda of Flanders.

00:28:07.070 --> 00:28:10.730
It was during this time that the first ever national census

00:28:10.730 --> 00:28:12.320
was conducted in England.

00:28:12.320 --> 00:28:14.840
The dramatically named Doomsday Book

00:28:14.840 --> 00:28:18.830
was in effect a royal survey of all the lands in England

00:28:18.830 --> 00:28:21.890
simply for administrative and tax purposes.

00:28:21.890 --> 00:28:24.920
Its name derives from the Christian Day of Judgment.

00:28:24.920 --> 00:28:27.290
And the aim of the project was to streamline

00:28:27.290 --> 00:28:29.570
and regulate tax collection in the realm.

00:28:29.570 --> 00:28:32.900
Its historical relevance cannot be understated,

00:28:32.900 --> 00:28:35.960
as it gave historians an incredibly detailed look

00:28:35.960 --> 00:28:39.110
into what life was like at the time of the Norman Invasion,

00:28:39.110 --> 00:28:40.430
and it currently lives

00:28:40.430 --> 00:28:42.890
in the National Archives at Kew in London.

00:28:42.890 --> 00:28:44.870
A year after the book was completed,

00:28:44.870 --> 00:28:47.780
on the 9th of September, 1087 AD,

00:28:47.780 --> 00:28:50.330
William the Conqueror died of dysentery

00:28:50.330 --> 00:28:52.670
while on expedition in France.

00:28:52.670 --> 00:28:54.680
As was the custom of the time,

00:28:54.680 --> 00:28:58.280
he divided his properties between his three living sons.

00:28:58.280 --> 00:29:01.220
Robert got Normandy, William got England,

00:29:01.220 --> 00:29:03.713
and Henry, Henry got money.

00:29:05.305 --> 00:29:08.270
(foreboding music)

00:29:08.270 --> 00:29:09.740
While the new king William

00:29:09.740 --> 00:29:12.590
may have inherited his father's lands and name,

00:29:12.590 --> 00:29:15.680
he had unfortunately inherited little else.

00:29:15.680 --> 00:29:18.410
Crowned king a month after his father's death,

00:29:18.410 --> 00:29:21.440
he quickly established himself as an unpopular,

00:29:21.440 --> 00:29:23.840
greedy, and self-centered ruler.

00:29:23.840 --> 00:29:25.610
He was a poor administrator

00:29:25.610 --> 00:29:28.760
who frequently angered the church and provoked his nobility

00:29:28.760 --> 00:29:32.720
with an unpredictable temperament and unyielding attitude.

00:29:32.720 --> 00:29:36.950
It's perhaps no surprise then that after 13 years of rule,

00:29:36.950 --> 00:29:41.540
King William II met his end during a hunting accident.

00:29:41.540 --> 00:29:43.880
The details of which aren't totally clear,

00:29:43.880 --> 00:29:45.890
but it is reported that William stepped

00:29:45.890 --> 00:29:50.120
in front of a stray arrow, dying of his wounds on the spot.

00:29:50.120 --> 00:29:53.030
The man who shot the arrow, William Tirel,

00:29:53.030 --> 00:29:55.673
fled after giving his account of the ordeal.

00:29:56.764 --> 00:29:59.840
(light music)

00:29:59.840 --> 00:30:03.200
With King William II dead, the throne was to be passed

00:30:03.200 --> 00:30:06.530
onto his older brother, Robert, Duke of Normandy,

00:30:06.530 --> 00:30:10.430
but Henry, the youngest of the three, had other ideas.

00:30:10.430 --> 00:30:12.200
With Robert busy on the continent

00:30:12.200 --> 00:30:14.090
ruling his Duke of Normandy,

00:30:14.090 --> 00:30:17.030
Henry took control of the royal treasury in London

00:30:17.030 --> 00:30:21.290
and proclaimed himself king of England in 1100 AD.

00:30:21.290 --> 00:30:23.960
Robert did eventually challenge his younger brother

00:30:23.960 --> 00:30:27.050
for the English throne, but King Henry was victorious

00:30:27.050 --> 00:30:30.620
at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106.

00:30:30.620 --> 00:30:33.320
Defeated, Robert was stripped of his dukedom

00:30:33.320 --> 00:30:36.080
and would spend the rest of his life in prison.

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:38.750
Thankfully for England, Henry I turned out

00:30:38.750 --> 00:30:42.200
to be a much better ruler than his brother before him.

00:30:42.200 --> 00:30:44.930
He successfully expanded royal administration

00:30:44.930 --> 00:30:48.590
throughout the realm and further solidified the rule of law.

00:30:48.590 --> 00:30:50.600
He set up the Court of the Exchequer

00:30:50.600 --> 00:30:53.750
to directly handle all financial matters,

00:30:53.750 --> 00:30:56.120
something which greatly improved the processes

00:30:56.120 --> 00:30:59.090
of collecting taxes and granting charters.

00:30:59.090 --> 00:31:03.710
He ruled for 35 long, peaceful and prosperous years

00:31:03.710 --> 00:31:05.540
during a time of great social

00:31:05.540 --> 00:31:07.790
and political change on the island.

00:31:07.790 --> 00:31:09.200
Many of the administrators

00:31:09.200 --> 00:31:11.900
King Henry had appointed were new men,

00:31:11.900 --> 00:31:15.260
obscure, untitled subjects who had risen through the ranks

00:31:15.260 --> 00:31:17.780
through sheer brilliance and ability

00:31:17.780 --> 00:31:20.150
and not simply because of their names.

00:31:20.150 --> 00:31:23.570
But tragedy struck Henry during his twilight years.

00:31:23.570 --> 00:31:26.720
His son and eventual heir to the English throne,

00:31:26.720 --> 00:31:30.410
William Adelin, died in the wreck of the White Ship

00:31:30.410 --> 00:31:32.240
while returning from France.

00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:34.580
The widower Henry was forced to remarry

00:31:34.580 --> 00:31:36.680
in the hopes of having another son.

00:31:36.680 --> 00:31:40.100
When it became clear Henry would not bear another son,

00:31:40.100 --> 00:31:42.530
he decided to name his daughter Matilda

00:31:42.530 --> 00:31:44.720
as his successor to the throne.

00:31:44.720 --> 00:31:47.030
This was an unprecedented move,

00:31:47.030 --> 00:31:49.700
and while many barons publicly swore fealty

00:31:49.700 --> 00:31:53.960
to the future empress, privately they had other ideas.

00:31:53.960 --> 00:31:57.440
King Henry I died in 1135 AD

00:31:57.440 --> 00:32:00.680
believing that he had solved the issue of succession.

00:32:00.680 --> 00:32:03.500
Immediately, however, the barons of England

00:32:03.500 --> 00:32:05.480
abandoned the dead king's wishes

00:32:05.480 --> 00:32:08.870
in favor of a different claimant, Henry's nephew,

00:32:08.870 --> 00:32:10.250
Stephen of Blois.

00:32:10.250 --> 00:32:12.800
You see, the English nobility weren't keen

00:32:12.800 --> 00:32:15.560
on the idea of a woman ruling the country.

00:32:15.560 --> 00:32:17.300
English society believed a woman

00:32:17.300 --> 00:32:20.480
simply couldn't rule as effectively as a man.

00:32:20.480 --> 00:32:23.660
Patriarchal biases aside, Stephen of Blois

00:32:23.660 --> 00:32:26.390
was a well-known and well-liked figure

00:32:26.390 --> 00:32:29.000
within the Anglo-Saxon upper class.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:31.790
He was respected, well-mannered, decisive,

00:32:31.790 --> 00:32:33.890
and best of all, wealthy,

00:32:33.890 --> 00:32:36.290
traits that made him an attractive prospect

00:32:36.290 --> 00:32:37.940
to put on the English throne.

00:32:37.940 --> 00:32:40.850
Matilda meanwhile was stubborn, arrogant,

00:32:40.850 --> 00:32:43.730
and because she had been married off at a young age

00:32:43.730 --> 00:32:45.560
to the holy Roman emperor

00:32:45.560 --> 00:32:48.350
and therefore spent her life away from England,

00:32:48.350 --> 00:32:51.140
she was considered by many a foreigner.

00:32:51.140 --> 00:32:53.780
What followed was a period of English history

00:32:53.780 --> 00:32:57.571
that later came to be known as the anarchy.

00:32:57.571 --> 00:33:00.590
(foreboding music)

00:33:00.590 --> 00:33:02.300
The news of King Henry's death

00:33:02.300 --> 00:33:05.630
reached Stephen of Blois first, and he crossed the channel

00:33:05.630 --> 00:33:09.050
and crown himself king in 1135 AD,

00:33:09.050 --> 00:33:11.870
arguing that the stability of the land took precedence

00:33:11.870 --> 00:33:13.670
over any earlier commitments

00:33:13.670 --> 00:33:16.280
to support Matilda as Henry's heir.

00:33:16.280 --> 00:33:19.520
Matilda, who now was married to the Count of Anjou,

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:20.810
was still in Europe

00:33:20.810 --> 00:33:23.900
and news of her father's passing was slow to reach her.

00:33:23.900 --> 00:33:27.500
As a result, King Stephen enjoyed an early period of ruling

00:33:27.500 --> 00:33:30.110
that was free of turmoil and challenge.

00:33:30.110 --> 00:33:33.500
When news reached Matilda of Stephen's usurpation,

00:33:33.500 --> 00:33:35.270
she was furious.

00:33:35.270 --> 00:33:37.910
In 1139, she crossed the channel

00:33:37.910 --> 00:33:40.100
and traveled to the court of her half-brother,

00:33:40.100 --> 00:33:42.080
Robert, the Earl of Gloucester,

00:33:42.080 --> 00:33:44.870
seeking his support against the usurper king.

00:33:44.870 --> 00:33:46.670
Robert obliged.

00:33:46.670 --> 00:33:49.820
Trouble began in 1141 when the king's forces

00:33:49.820 --> 00:33:52.520
met Robert's army at the Battle of Lincoln.

00:33:52.520 --> 00:33:54.680
King Stephen is said to have fought bravely

00:33:54.680 --> 00:33:57.290
but was overwhelmed by Robert's men.

00:33:57.290 --> 00:34:00.590
The captured king was then taken to speak with Matilda.

00:34:00.590 --> 00:34:03.890
She immediately imprisoned Stephen at Bristol Castle

00:34:03.890 --> 00:34:08.330
and set out for London with one aim in mind, her coronation,

00:34:08.330 --> 00:34:11.360
but her attempts at becoming queen were soon halted.

00:34:11.360 --> 00:34:14.210
She faced bitter opposition from the crowds

00:34:14.210 --> 00:34:15.830
that had gathered in the capital.

00:34:15.830 --> 00:34:19.730
These were not soldiers, but ordinary citizens.

00:34:19.730 --> 00:34:22.880
Forced to retreat, her half brother Robert was captured

00:34:22.880 --> 00:34:24.620
during the route of Winchester,

00:34:24.620 --> 00:34:26.960
and only by releasing King Stephen

00:34:26.960 --> 00:34:30.620
did Empress Matilda secure her half brother's safety.

00:34:30.620 --> 00:34:34.550
With Stephen free once again, the fighting continued.

00:34:34.550 --> 00:34:38.342
Empress Matilda was herself captured at the town of Devizes,

00:34:38.342 --> 00:34:41.090
but managed to slip away from the king's men

00:34:41.090 --> 00:34:43.730
by pretending to be a corpse on a cart.

00:34:43.730 --> 00:34:47.540
She was again captured and this time held at Oxford Castle,

00:34:47.540 --> 00:34:50.630
but Matilda mounted another daring escape,

00:34:50.630 --> 00:34:53.600
lowering herself from the castle walls on a rope

00:34:53.600 --> 00:34:55.040
during a snowstorm.

00:34:55.040 --> 00:34:57.920
Wearing white so as the camouflage herself,

00:34:57.920 --> 00:35:00.650
the empress traverse the bitter cold

00:35:00.650 --> 00:35:03.710
and made her way to the town of Wallingford by night,

00:35:03.710 --> 00:35:05.600
making sure to avoid detection

00:35:05.600 --> 00:35:09.470
from hastily formed search parties that hoped to find her.

00:35:09.470 --> 00:35:11.407
The war soon turned into a stalemate

00:35:11.407 --> 00:35:13.550
as neither side could claim

00:35:13.550 --> 00:35:15.590
they controlled much of anything.

00:35:15.590 --> 00:35:19.340
In 1153, Matilda's son, Henry, landed in England

00:35:19.340 --> 00:35:22.730
and began building his own alliances with power barons

00:35:22.730 --> 00:35:25.340
to support his mother's claim to the throne.

00:35:25.340 --> 00:35:28.160
But Empress Matilda had grown tired of the fighting

00:35:28.160 --> 00:35:30.320
and by now had retreated to Normandy,

00:35:30.320 --> 00:35:33.020
passing her claim solely onto her son.

00:35:33.020 --> 00:35:35.000
King Stephen was in a similar position

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:37.880
with his rule undermined by the constant fighting,

00:35:37.880 --> 00:35:40.670
so he agreed to the Treaty of Westminster.

00:35:40.670 --> 00:35:43.910
It stated that King Stephen would remain king for life,

00:35:43.910 --> 00:35:45.890
and then Henry, the lawful heir,

00:35:45.890 --> 00:35:49.070
would succeed him as king of England upon his death.

00:35:49.070 --> 00:35:53.240
As it turns out, Stephen only lived for another year

00:35:53.240 --> 00:35:58.240
and died in 1154 AD, passing the English throne to Henry.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:01.280
From the ashes of the civil war,

00:36:01.280 --> 00:36:03.980
England was reborn under a new family,

00:36:03.980 --> 00:36:06.950
one that would eventually rule over the island

00:36:06.950 --> 00:36:09.530
for almost half a millennia,

00:36:09.530 --> 00:36:12.375
introducing the Plantagenets.

00:36:12.375 --> 00:36:15.208
(uplifting music)

00:36:16.820 --> 00:36:19.250
Henry II was crowned king of England

00:36:19.250 --> 00:36:22.940
on the 19th of December, 1154 AD,

00:36:22.940 --> 00:36:25.850
and immediately set about fixing his kingdom.

00:36:25.850 --> 00:36:29.150
18 years of civil war had taken its toll,

00:36:29.150 --> 00:36:31.460
and the realm his grandfather had ruled over

00:36:31.460 --> 00:36:35.420
less than a lifetime ago was now unrecognizable.

00:36:35.420 --> 00:36:37.700
The treasury was virtually empty,

00:36:37.700 --> 00:36:40.400
royal administration was almost non-existent,

00:36:40.400 --> 00:36:43.730
and local lords had slowly wrestled power away

00:36:43.730 --> 00:36:47.000
from the crown, weakening its influence in the realm.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:51.140
Henry began by restoring the power of royal administrations,

00:36:51.140 --> 00:36:54.920
as well as reestablishing English hegemony over Wales.

00:36:54.920 --> 00:36:57.200
He raised unlicensed castles

00:36:57.200 --> 00:36:59.990
that had sprung up during the anarchy,

00:36:59.990 --> 00:37:01.760
and reclaimed many of the rights

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:03.530
and powers the crown had lost

00:37:03.530 --> 00:37:05.660
during the reign of King Stephen.

00:37:05.660 --> 00:37:09.560
Next, Henry focused on restoring the crown's finances.

00:37:09.560 --> 00:37:11.300
The war had disrupted almost

00:37:11.300 --> 00:37:13.970
all the king's traditional sources of income,

00:37:13.970 --> 00:37:16.580
and as a result, Henry inherited a kingdom

00:37:16.580 --> 00:37:21.260
that had lost an estimated 46% of its funding.

00:37:21.260 --> 00:37:23.690
Faced with an administrative nightmare,

00:37:23.690 --> 00:37:25.070
the king needed help.

00:37:25.070 --> 00:37:27.740
He was soon introduced to a cleric from London

00:37:27.740 --> 00:37:29.030
who had earned a reputation

00:37:29.030 --> 00:37:31.610
as an astute and capable administrator.

00:37:31.610 --> 00:37:33.710
His name was Thomas Becket.

00:37:33.710 --> 00:37:36.950
Ruthlessly efficient and brilliant at this post,

00:37:36.950 --> 00:37:40.700
Becket was appointed lord chancellor in 1155,

00:37:40.700 --> 00:37:42.350
giving him direct control

00:37:42.350 --> 00:37:44.420
over the king's sources of revenue.

00:37:44.420 --> 00:37:46.850
Becket was successful at his new post,

00:37:46.850 --> 00:37:50.240
and King Henry had a lot of admiration for the chancellor.

00:37:50.240 --> 00:37:53.439
As a new man, Becket championed the idea

00:37:53.439 --> 00:37:56.030
set forward by Henry's grandfather,

00:37:56.030 --> 00:37:59.360
that of promotion through ability and not title,

00:37:59.360 --> 00:38:03.680
and even beyond this, the two men quickly became friends.

00:38:03.680 --> 00:38:05.660
The king even sent his son Henry

00:38:05.660 --> 00:38:08.420
to live in the Becket household as a young boy,

00:38:08.420 --> 00:38:11.990
highlighting just how close the two families really were.

00:38:11.990 --> 00:38:14.810
So when the archbishop of Canterbury died,

00:38:14.810 --> 00:38:17.360
Henry saw a golden opportunity.

00:38:17.360 --> 00:38:20.510
Wanting to reassert his rights over the church in England,

00:38:20.510 --> 00:38:22.880
which had been growing increasingly powerful

00:38:22.880 --> 00:38:25.370
in recent years, King Henry II

00:38:25.370 --> 00:38:27.950
encouraged a reluctant Thomas Becket

00:38:27.950 --> 00:38:30.980
to take up the position of archbishop.

00:38:30.980 --> 00:38:32.960
It was a win-win for Henry.

00:38:32.960 --> 00:38:35.150
Becket was a powerful chancellor,

00:38:35.150 --> 00:38:37.040
and his new position as archbishop

00:38:37.040 --> 00:38:38.870
would weaken him politically,

00:38:38.870 --> 00:38:40.850
meaning Becket would have to rely more

00:38:40.850 --> 00:38:42.710
on King Henry for support.

00:38:42.710 --> 00:38:44.900
Moreover, Henry assumed his old friend

00:38:44.900 --> 00:38:47.390
would act in the crown's best interest,

00:38:47.390 --> 00:38:49.430
weakening the church's growing influence

00:38:49.430 --> 00:38:52.700
over the Kingdom of England, but he was wrong.

00:38:52.700 --> 00:38:57.020
Almost immediately after his ordination in 1162 AD,

00:38:57.020 --> 00:38:58.880
Thomas Becket changed.

00:38:58.880 --> 00:39:01.340
He abandoned his links to the royal family

00:39:01.340 --> 00:39:05.480
and fashion himself as a new protector of religious rights.

00:39:05.480 --> 00:39:09.020
Henry's plan had backfired enormously.

00:39:09.020 --> 00:39:11.000
Their friendship did little to stop them

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:13.610
from clashing on a number of issues,

00:39:13.610 --> 00:39:15.830
mainly the question of the supremacy

00:39:15.830 --> 00:39:17.990
of ecclesiastical courts.

00:39:17.990 --> 00:39:20.120
Put simply, during Henry's reign,

00:39:20.120 --> 00:39:22.040
clergy members could only be tried

00:39:22.040 --> 00:39:24.320
for their crimes in church courts.

00:39:24.320 --> 00:39:27.080
The king didn't like this, as it made the crown appear weak

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:29.300
and subservient, implying that the church

00:39:29.300 --> 00:39:32.022
and its clergy were above royal ordinance.

00:39:32.022 --> 00:39:34.610
Add to this the fact that a huge portion

00:39:34.610 --> 00:39:38.090
of England's administrative body was made up of clergymen,

00:39:38.090 --> 00:39:42.080
and Henry was anxious to wrestle power back from the church.

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:44.270
He argued that criminalist clerks

00:39:44.270 --> 00:39:46.850
should be tried in royal courts instead.

00:39:46.850 --> 00:39:48.290
Becket disagreed.

00:39:48.290 --> 00:39:52.880
This enraged King Henry II who was known for having a wild

00:39:52.880 --> 00:39:54.710
and unpredictable temperament.

00:39:54.710 --> 00:39:58.400
Fearing for his life, Archbishop Becket fled to France,

00:39:58.400 --> 00:40:00.710
where the pope was forced to intervene,

00:40:00.710 --> 00:40:04.610
mediating a fragile peace between the old friends.

00:40:04.610 --> 00:40:07.940
Upon his return, Becket immediately angered Henry

00:40:07.940 --> 00:40:11.420
by excommunicating the bishops who had supported the king

00:40:11.420 --> 00:40:13.640
during the archbishop's exile.

00:40:13.640 --> 00:40:17.030
Henry flew into another rage, and four nights,

00:40:17.030 --> 00:40:19.370
perhaps hoping to curry favor from the king,

00:40:19.370 --> 00:40:22.130
rode to Canterbury and killed Becket

00:40:22.130 --> 00:40:25.100
on the steps of his altar where he stood.

00:40:25.100 --> 00:40:27.140
It was a shocking move

00:40:27.140 --> 00:40:30.140
and one that Henry came to deeply regret.

00:40:30.140 --> 00:40:31.520
Filled with remorse,

00:40:31.520 --> 00:40:33.920
King Henry walked to Canterbury Cathedral

00:40:33.920 --> 00:40:35.960
in sackcloth and ashes,

00:40:35.960 --> 00:40:39.110
allowing himself to be whipped by the monks there.

00:40:39.110 --> 00:40:40.520
Becket was martyred

00:40:40.520 --> 00:40:43.670
and the power of the church grew as a consequence.

00:40:43.670 --> 00:40:45.890
Henry's own demise would eventually come

00:40:45.890 --> 00:40:48.200
at the hands of his three sons.

00:40:48.200 --> 00:40:51.650
In 1173, the heir to the English throne,

00:40:51.650 --> 00:40:54.680
young Henry rebelled against his father.

00:40:54.680 --> 00:40:57.230
Joined by his two brothers, Richard and Geoffrey,

00:40:57.230 --> 00:41:01.520
as well as several European states, the Great Revolt began,

00:41:01.520 --> 00:41:05.450
and King Henry II was forced to meet the rebels in battle.

00:41:05.450 --> 00:41:06.830
The revolt was only stopped

00:41:06.830 --> 00:41:09.890
thanks to Henry's talented local commanders,

00:41:09.890 --> 00:41:13.100
many of whom were new men appointed for their loyalty

00:41:13.100 --> 00:41:14.870
and administrative skill.

00:41:14.870 --> 00:41:17.390
Young Henry and Geoffrey led another revolt

00:41:17.390 --> 00:41:21.860
a decade later in 1183, but they were, again, unsuccessful

00:41:21.860 --> 00:41:24.080
and died a few years after.

00:41:24.080 --> 00:41:26.300
Philip II, King of France,

00:41:26.300 --> 00:41:28.910
swayed a neutral Richard to his side,

00:41:28.910 --> 00:41:31.220
and together they led one last revolt

00:41:31.220 --> 00:41:33.830
against King Henry II of England.

00:41:33.830 --> 00:41:35.480
With his army defeated,

00:41:35.480 --> 00:41:38.000
the king retreated to his castle in Anjou

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:42.530
where he died from a bleeding ulcer shortly after in 1189.

00:41:42.530 --> 00:41:44.930
Having forced his father off the throne,

00:41:44.930 --> 00:41:47.273
Richard prepped himself to take over.

00:41:48.247 --> 00:41:51.290
(gentle music)

00:41:51.290 --> 00:41:54.560
Richard I was crowned king at Westminster Abbey

00:41:54.560 --> 00:41:57.380
on the 3rd of September, 1198.

00:41:57.380 --> 00:41:59.360
Fondly remembered an English history

00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:01.670
as Richard the Lionheart for his bravery

00:42:01.670 --> 00:42:04.850
and skill in battle, Richard's rule is unique,

00:42:04.850 --> 00:42:06.830
as he spent the majority of it abroad

00:42:06.830 --> 00:42:10.880
fighting in what would later be known as the Third Crusades.

00:42:10.880 --> 00:42:14.330
In fact, King Richard spent just 10 months in England

00:42:14.330 --> 00:42:17.929
before leaving to join Philip II of France on his crusade

00:42:17.929 --> 00:42:21.440
to liberate Jerusalem from Muslim invaders.

00:42:21.440 --> 00:42:25.410
Richard proved himself to be a brilliant military strategist

00:42:25.410 --> 00:42:27.890
and he fought cruelly and decisively

00:42:27.890 --> 00:42:30.590
as he led his army deep into the Lavant.

00:42:30.590 --> 00:42:33.440
His rivalry with Muslim commander Saladin

00:42:33.440 --> 00:42:35.750
became the stuff of a legend,

00:42:35.750 --> 00:42:38.090
and the crusaders were able to recapture

00:42:38.090 --> 00:42:41.240
a sizable portion of their territory back.

00:42:41.240 --> 00:42:44.750
But as a result, England quickly became an afterthought

00:42:44.750 --> 00:42:45.860
to King Richard.

00:42:45.860 --> 00:42:48.800
He used the realm mainly to finance his wars

00:42:48.800 --> 00:42:49.970
in the Middle East.

00:42:49.970 --> 00:42:52.310
After failing to retake Jerusalem,

00:42:52.310 --> 00:42:55.760
King Richard was captured by Leopold of Austria,

00:42:55.760 --> 00:42:59.810
a personal enemy of the English king, and held for ransom.

00:42:59.810 --> 00:43:02.600
John, the youngest of Henry II's children

00:43:02.600 --> 00:43:03.950
and brother of Richard,

00:43:03.950 --> 00:43:06.500
had been left an administrative charge of the realm.

00:43:06.500 --> 00:43:09.110
When news reached him of his brother's capture,

00:43:09.110 --> 00:43:13.130
he was hesitant to pay the 60,000 pound ransom.

00:43:13.130 --> 00:43:15.560
With help from the archbishop of Canterbury

00:43:15.560 --> 00:43:17.960
and his mother, Eleanor of Aquitaine,

00:43:17.960 --> 00:43:21.980
King Richard's ransom was paid and he was free once more.

00:43:21.980 --> 00:43:25.910
But Richard the Lionheart died as he lived, fighting.

00:43:25.910 --> 00:43:28.580
Struck by a crossbow bolt in France,

00:43:28.580 --> 00:43:30.950
the wound quickly turned gangrenous,

00:43:30.950 --> 00:43:34.100
and it was apparent to all that the king wouldn't make it.

00:43:34.100 --> 00:43:36.770
Richard reportedly asked to have the crossbow man

00:43:36.770 --> 00:43:38.506
brought before him and was surprised

00:43:38.506 --> 00:43:41.300
when a boy was thrown at his feet.

00:43:41.300 --> 00:43:42.800
The child said King Richard

00:43:42.800 --> 00:43:44.510
had killed his father and brother

00:43:44.510 --> 00:43:47.870
and that he had intended to kill Richard in revenge.

00:43:47.870 --> 00:43:52.160
He expected to be executed, but in one final act of mercy,

00:43:52.160 --> 00:43:55.047
Richard the Lionheart forgave him saying,

00:43:55.047 --> 00:43:59.240
"Live on, and by my bounty, behold the light of day."

00:43:59.240 --> 00:44:03.950
Richard died in his mother's arms on the 6th of April, 1199.

00:44:03.950 --> 00:44:06.957
Chroniclers of this time said this of the king's death,

00:44:06.957 --> 00:44:09.827
"The lion by the ant was slain."

00:44:11.267 --> 00:44:14.300
(light music)

00:44:14.300 --> 00:44:16.070
With his brother now dead,

00:44:16.070 --> 00:44:19.970
John was crowned king of England in 1199 AD.

00:44:19.970 --> 00:44:21.950
Like his older brother before him,

00:44:21.950 --> 00:44:23.900
John too was given a nickname,

00:44:23.900 --> 00:44:26.180
although one far less romantic.

00:44:26.180 --> 00:44:29.870
He was called John Lackland or lack-of-land,

00:44:29.870 --> 00:44:33.021
as he was not expected to inherit any significant lands

00:44:33.021 --> 00:44:35.360
upon his father's death.

00:44:35.360 --> 00:44:36.920
But as fate would have it,

00:44:36.920 --> 00:44:40.190
as the youngest of Henry II's four sons,

00:44:40.190 --> 00:44:41.690
John had not been involved

00:44:41.690 --> 00:44:43.880
in any of the wars against his father

00:44:43.880 --> 00:44:47.330
and had therefore been given lands in Ireland and France

00:44:47.330 --> 00:44:49.340
as a thank you for his loyalty.

00:44:49.340 --> 00:44:51.740
Unfortunately, though, this was about as good

00:44:51.740 --> 00:44:53.510
as it got for King John.

00:44:53.510 --> 00:44:57.200
While Richard the Lionheart was an absent but popular king,

00:44:57.200 --> 00:44:59.060
John was the complete opposite.

00:44:59.060 --> 00:45:02.150
He was a poor administrator, a greedy statesman,

00:45:02.150 --> 00:45:05.510
and a terrible fighter whose over-involvement in ruling

00:45:05.510 --> 00:45:08.870
led to a sharp decline in the power of the English crown.

00:45:08.870 --> 00:45:12.950
In 1204, he lost all his family's lands on the continent,

00:45:12.950 --> 00:45:16.340
severing the aristocracy of Normandy from England

00:45:16.340 --> 00:45:17.450
for the first time

00:45:17.450 --> 00:45:21.580
since William the Conqueror's ascension in 1066.

00:45:21.580 --> 00:45:26.580
He was briefly excommunicated in 1209 by Pope Innocent III

00:45:26.630 --> 00:45:28.670
after an argument with his clergy,

00:45:28.670 --> 00:45:31.100
and was becoming increasingly unpopular

00:45:31.100 --> 00:45:32.450
with the barons of England

00:45:32.450 --> 00:45:35.270
for his poor leadership and decision-making.

00:45:35.270 --> 00:45:38.480
After failing to recapture his territories of Normandy,

00:45:38.480 --> 00:45:41.090
King John was forced to return to England

00:45:41.090 --> 00:45:44.630
and face a powerful rebellion from his barons.

00:45:44.630 --> 00:45:47.570
Unhappy with the king's new fiscal policies

00:45:47.570 --> 00:45:50.930
and demanding that their righteous nobility be respected,

00:45:50.930 --> 00:45:54.170
they forced the king in signing the great document

00:45:54.170 --> 00:45:57.830
or the Magna Carta in 1215 AD.

00:45:57.830 --> 00:46:00.560
The English crown changed forever that day,

00:46:00.560 --> 00:46:04.010
as the king agreed to be bound by common law and tradition,

00:46:04.010 --> 00:46:05.840
especially where it affected the rights

00:46:05.840 --> 00:46:07.790
and privileges of the nobility.

00:46:07.790 --> 00:46:11.330
It essentially put the crown directly under the rule of law,

00:46:11.330 --> 00:46:13.130
as opposed to the other way around

00:46:13.130 --> 00:46:15.740
as it had been since England was founded.

00:46:15.740 --> 00:46:20.180
Its impact was astronomical, although not immediate.

00:46:20.180 --> 00:46:22.460
While it was nothing more than a power grab

00:46:22.460 --> 00:46:24.080
by the barons of England,

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:26.240
it eventually went on to form the basis

00:46:26.240 --> 00:46:28.190
of the English constitution,

00:46:28.190 --> 00:46:31.490
and included several clauses that were later interpreted

00:46:31.490 --> 00:46:34.160
as definitions of democratic freedom

00:46:34.160 --> 00:46:37.160
and the rights of an individual under common law.

00:46:37.160 --> 00:46:39.950
King John had hoped that by signing the Magna Carta,

00:46:39.950 --> 00:46:41.360
he could appease his nobility

00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:44.060
and stop a war from breaking out in the kingdom.

00:46:44.060 --> 00:46:46.460
But once again, he was wrong.

00:46:46.460 --> 00:46:48.950
Still unhappy with King John's rule,

00:46:48.950 --> 00:46:53.030
the First Barons' War ignited in England in 1215.

00:46:53.030 --> 00:46:55.730
But despite backing from the King of France,

00:46:55.730 --> 00:46:57.680
the English barons were unable

00:46:57.680 --> 00:47:01.790
to score any decisive victories over King John and his men,

00:47:01.790 --> 00:47:04.100
and the war quickly became a stalemate.

00:47:04.100 --> 00:47:07.340
While on campaign, King John died of dysentery

00:47:07.340 --> 00:47:10.460
he'd contracted while overindulging on peaches,

00:47:10.460 --> 00:47:12.590
a fitting death perhaps.

00:47:12.590 --> 00:47:16.100
As a result, the throne was passed onto his son, Henry,

00:47:16.100 --> 00:47:19.190
who now had the unpleasant task of finishing

00:47:19.190 --> 00:47:21.246
what his father had started.

00:47:21.246 --> 00:47:24.770
(uplifting music)

00:47:24.770 --> 00:47:26.990
At just nine years of age,

00:47:26.990 --> 00:47:31.480
Henry III was crowned king of England on October 28th, 1216.

00:47:32.420 --> 00:47:34.640
Inheriting a kingdom on fire,

00:47:34.640 --> 00:47:36.980
the new King Henry was faced with a challenge

00:47:36.980 --> 00:47:39.170
of ending the First Barons' War.

00:47:39.170 --> 00:47:41.780
The king's army was led by William Marshal,

00:47:41.780 --> 00:47:43.580
1st Earl of Pembrokeshire

00:47:43.580 --> 00:47:46.670
and servant to five English rulers before him.

00:47:46.670 --> 00:47:48.500
He was a brilliant commander

00:47:48.500 --> 00:47:50.840
and successfully defeated the baron army

00:47:50.840 --> 00:47:52.520
at the Battle of Lincoln

00:47:52.520 --> 00:47:55.430
and the Battle of Sandwich that same year.

00:47:55.430 --> 00:47:56.840
With the barons defeated,

00:47:56.840 --> 00:47:59.540
they now had to answer to their new king.

00:47:59.540 --> 00:48:01.400
Henry showed great diplomacy

00:48:01.400 --> 00:48:05.030
and maturity by promising to abide by the Magna Carta,

00:48:05.030 --> 00:48:07.010
agreeing to limit his royal power

00:48:07.010 --> 00:48:09.050
and protect the rights of the nobility.

00:48:09.050 --> 00:48:12.290
With the rebellion quashed, Henry now turned his attention

00:48:12.290 --> 00:48:13.790
to repairing his kingdom.

00:48:13.790 --> 00:48:16.790
With the help of able statesmen and administrators,

00:48:16.790 --> 00:48:18.950
the next few years of King Henry's reign

00:48:18.950 --> 00:48:21.170
focused on regaining royal control

00:48:21.170 --> 00:48:22.970
that had been lost during the war.

00:48:22.970 --> 00:48:26.270
In 1230 AD, he had secured his power,

00:48:26.270 --> 00:48:28.190
and now well into adulthood,

00:48:28.190 --> 00:48:31.040
he said his sights on his father's greatest shame,

00:48:31.040 --> 00:48:33.560
their provinces in France.

00:48:33.560 --> 00:48:35.960
The English crown had never fully recovered

00:48:35.960 --> 00:48:38.600
from losing its grip on the edge of an empire,

00:48:38.600 --> 00:48:41.300
and King Henry III sought to fix that.

00:48:41.300 --> 00:48:43.190
He prepared an invasion fleet,

00:48:43.190 --> 00:48:45.860
planning to take the territories by force,

00:48:45.860 --> 00:48:48.050
and reestablish English control

00:48:48.050 --> 00:48:50.630
over land he deemed his birthright,

00:48:50.630 --> 00:48:53.240
but the invasion was a disaster.

00:48:53.240 --> 00:48:56.120
Perhaps on the advice of the first earl of Kent

00:48:56.120 --> 00:48:58.820
who had been ruling the realm on behalf of the young king

00:48:58.820 --> 00:49:00.620
while he was still coming of age,

00:49:00.620 --> 00:49:03.560
Henry avoided meeting the French in open battle

00:49:03.560 --> 00:49:06.830
and instead marched his troops across the countryside,

00:49:06.830 --> 00:49:10.490
forcing local barons and lords to pay homage to him.

00:49:10.490 --> 00:49:14.510
Some did, some didn't, and it was a pointless venture

00:49:14.510 --> 00:49:15.800
that didn't really mean much

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:17.870
for English control in the region.

00:49:17.870 --> 00:49:20.930
Eventually, Henry was forced to return to England

00:49:20.930 --> 00:49:22.580
having achieved nothing.

00:49:22.580 --> 00:49:25.100
As soon as Henry and his troops left France,

00:49:25.100 --> 00:49:27.560
those barons who had pledged themselves to him

00:49:27.560 --> 00:49:30.080
went right back to supporting the French king.

00:49:30.080 --> 00:49:32.960
The invasion had been a costly fiasco

00:49:32.960 --> 00:49:36.560
that made Henry extremely unpopular amongst his nobility.

00:49:36.560 --> 00:49:38.450
Hubert, 1st Earl of Kent,

00:49:38.450 --> 00:49:41.030
had now fallen out of favor with the king,

00:49:41.030 --> 00:49:44.210
and upon their return to England, Henry dismissed him,

00:49:44.210 --> 00:49:48.050
eventually imprisoning Hubert in the Tower of London,

00:49:48.050 --> 00:49:51.530
and the man chosen to replace him was no better.

00:49:51.530 --> 00:49:54.980
Peter des Roches took over as the king's justiciar

00:49:54.980 --> 00:49:57.650
and immediately set about reversing the policies

00:49:57.650 --> 00:49:59.060
of his predecessor.

00:49:59.060 --> 00:50:01.580
He stripped his enemies of land and wealth,

00:50:01.580 --> 00:50:03.740
circumventing the royal courts,

00:50:03.740 --> 00:50:06.020
and angering the nobility who believed

00:50:06.020 --> 00:50:09.140
that their rights were being infringed upon once again.

00:50:09.140 --> 00:50:11.510
Richard Marshal, the son of William Marshal,

00:50:11.510 --> 00:50:14.540
who had led the royal army in the First Barons' War,

00:50:14.540 --> 00:50:16.340
began to amass troops,

00:50:16.340 --> 00:50:19.940
only this time in support of the English barons.

00:50:19.940 --> 00:50:22.430
They argued that the king had again failed

00:50:22.430 --> 00:50:25.760
to protect their rights as outlined in the Magna Carta,

00:50:25.760 --> 00:50:28.760
and thus a new civil war broke out.

00:50:28.760 --> 00:50:31.280
Unable to gain a clear military advantage

00:50:31.280 --> 00:50:34.520
against the rebels and with tension in France growing,

00:50:34.520 --> 00:50:36.530
King Henry had no choice.

00:50:36.530 --> 00:50:39.440
He agreed to the dismissal of Peter des Roches

00:50:39.440 --> 00:50:42.230
and submitted fully to the rebels' demands.

00:50:42.230 --> 00:50:44.240
King Henry had learned his lesson.

00:50:44.240 --> 00:50:47.880
Never again was England ruled through senior ministers,

00:50:47.880 --> 00:50:51.770
and the king now chose to administer the realm personally.

00:50:51.770 --> 00:50:54.020
The only problem was that Henry

00:50:54.020 --> 00:50:56.150
was not a good administrator.

00:50:56.150 --> 00:50:59.690
He filled the church with absentee Italian appointees

00:50:59.690 --> 00:51:03.170
and much of the civil offices with French bureaucrats,

00:51:03.170 --> 00:51:05.906
actions which unsurprisingly angered the nobility

00:51:05.906 --> 00:51:07.940
of England once more.

00:51:07.940 --> 00:51:10.850
This led to the barons to once again take action

00:51:10.850 --> 00:51:11.683
against the king.

00:51:11.683 --> 00:51:15.320
He was forced into signing the provisions of Oxford,

00:51:15.320 --> 00:51:17.840
a document which gave barons the legal right

00:51:17.840 --> 00:51:20.360
to veto the king's decisions.

00:51:20.360 --> 00:51:22.100
Although initially supportive,

00:51:22.100 --> 00:51:24.590
King Henry tried to back out of the deal,

00:51:24.590 --> 00:51:28.040
which led to the third civil war of his reign.

00:51:28.040 --> 00:51:31.190
Led by Simon de Montfort, Henry's brother-in-law,

00:51:31.190 --> 00:51:34.040
the rebel army successfully captured King Henry

00:51:34.040 --> 00:51:36.950
at the Battle of Lewis in 1265.

00:51:36.950 --> 00:51:38.990
With the king now at his mercy,

00:51:38.990 --> 00:51:42.380
Simon called the first English parliament into action.

00:51:42.380 --> 00:51:45.110
From the French word for talk or parle,

00:51:45.110 --> 00:51:47.600
he summoned two knights from each shire

00:51:47.600 --> 00:51:50.660
and two burgesses from each borough for a discussion.

00:51:50.660 --> 00:51:53.480
The men talked and created a new system of government

00:51:53.480 --> 00:51:57.140
on the island that is still in use in England today.

00:51:57.140 --> 00:52:00.230
King Henry's eldest son, Edward Longshanks,

00:52:00.230 --> 00:52:02.120
so named for his lanky build,

00:52:02.120 --> 00:52:04.310
had been captured alongside his father

00:52:04.310 --> 00:52:06.530
at the Battle of Lewis.

00:52:06.530 --> 00:52:09.440
Shortly after the first parliamentary discussion,

00:52:09.440 --> 00:52:12.530
Edward escaped, and within a few short months,

00:52:12.530 --> 00:52:17.480
he had defeated Simon at the Battle of Evesham in 1265.

00:52:17.480 --> 00:52:20.450
The Second Barons' War ended shortly after,

00:52:20.450 --> 00:52:23.270
and Edward Longshanks left England with his father,

00:52:23.270 --> 00:52:26.300
King Henry, once again on the English throne.

00:52:26.300 --> 00:52:29.990
In 1275, King Henry III announced his intention

00:52:29.990 --> 00:52:32.660
to embark on the crusades alongside his son,

00:52:32.660 --> 00:52:35.510
but died just a few months later.

00:52:35.510 --> 00:52:37.610
Edward was recalled from the continent

00:52:37.610 --> 00:52:40.819
and slowly made his way back to the English shores.

00:52:40.819 --> 00:52:43.402
(gentle music)

00:52:45.020 --> 00:52:47.660
Landing on the island in 1274,

00:52:47.660 --> 00:52:50.540
Edward Longshanks was crowned at Westminster Abbey

00:52:50.540 --> 00:52:52.940
shortly after becoming king of England,

00:52:52.940 --> 00:52:55.130
inheriting an island that had suffered

00:52:55.130 --> 00:52:59.870
through three major insurrections in the last 56 years.

00:52:59.870 --> 00:53:02.840
King Edward I had his work cut out for him.

00:53:02.840 --> 00:53:06.260
He immediately set about reforming royal administration

00:53:06.260 --> 00:53:10.010
and reinforcing common law, writing a series of statutes

00:53:10.010 --> 00:53:13.430
that regulated criminal and property law in the realm.

00:53:13.430 --> 00:53:16.190
Edward had also learned from his father's mistakes

00:53:16.190 --> 00:53:19.490
and was more supportive of the demands of his nobility.

00:53:19.490 --> 00:53:22.910
He regularly convened with knights and townspeople alike

00:53:22.910 --> 00:53:24.410
on matters that affected them

00:53:24.410 --> 00:53:28.160
and quickly proved to be an able and just ruler.

00:53:28.160 --> 00:53:31.940
But despite his focus on repairing England domestically,

00:53:31.940 --> 00:53:33.579
King Edward could not help

00:53:33.579 --> 00:53:36.500
but be drawn into foreign conflicts.

00:53:36.500 --> 00:53:38.540
The first was a revolt in Wales

00:53:38.540 --> 00:53:42.110
led by a Welsh chief named Llywelyn in 1282.

00:53:42.110 --> 00:53:44.720
Here the royal army came face-to-face

00:53:44.720 --> 00:53:48.140
with the brutal efficiency of the Welsh longbowman,

00:53:48.140 --> 00:53:50.510
and despite taking heavy losses,

00:53:50.510 --> 00:53:52.340
they subdued the rebel threat.

00:53:52.340 --> 00:53:55.460
In an attempt to exert more control over the region,

00:53:55.460 --> 00:53:57.860
King Edward constructed a series of castles

00:53:57.860 --> 00:53:59.420
in the Welsh territory

00:53:59.420 --> 00:54:02.000
and increased royal presence in the region.

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:05.720
His son, Edward, was born in Wales in 1284

00:54:05.720 --> 00:54:08.239
and was soon after named Prince of Wales,

00:54:08.239 --> 00:54:10.910
a title that the heir to the English throne

00:54:10.910 --> 00:54:13.370
still wears to this day.

00:54:13.370 --> 00:54:17.870
In 1291, another foreign conflict called his attention,

00:54:17.870 --> 00:54:20.000
this time at the northern border.

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:22.760
Asked to arbitrate between three rival claimants

00:54:22.760 --> 00:54:26.660
to the Scottish throne, Edward chose to crown John Balliol.

00:54:26.660 --> 00:54:29.060
The only problem was that John Balliol

00:54:29.060 --> 00:54:32.480
had previously paid homage to the English king,

00:54:32.480 --> 00:54:36.590
thus ruining any impartiality Edward was supposed to have.

00:54:36.590 --> 00:54:38.660
This angered the lords of Scotland,

00:54:38.660 --> 00:54:41.750
who in turn allied themselves with France,

00:54:41.750 --> 00:54:45.080
leaving England threatened on all sides.

00:54:45.080 --> 00:54:47.540
King Edward then retaliated.

00:54:47.540 --> 00:54:50.210
Claiming feudal suzerainty over Scotland,

00:54:50.210 --> 00:54:52.670
he marched his army north and invaded,

00:54:52.670 --> 00:54:55.250
defeating Balliol in 1296

00:54:55.250 --> 00:54:58.280
and taking the Scottish crown for himself.

00:54:58.280 --> 00:55:00.440
He also took the Stone of Scone,

00:55:00.440 --> 00:55:02.720
an important relic of Scottish nobility

00:55:02.720 --> 00:55:05.510
where all Scottish kings were crowned upon.

00:55:05.510 --> 00:55:08.840
The stone is still used to crown British monarchs today

00:55:08.840 --> 00:55:11.870
and currently resides at Westminster Abbey in London.

00:55:11.870 --> 00:55:13.790
For his actions in Scotland,

00:55:13.790 --> 00:55:16.130
King Edward earned himself a new nickname.

00:55:16.130 --> 00:55:20.930
Edward Longshanks had become Edward the Hammer of Scots.

00:55:20.930 --> 00:55:23.270
Back in England, Edward was overseeing

00:55:23.270 --> 00:55:26.480
a rapidly transforming English government.

00:55:26.480 --> 00:55:28.550
He encouraged petitions to parliament,

00:55:28.550 --> 00:55:30.650
with council sitting much more frequently

00:55:30.650 --> 00:55:32.060
than they had previously,

00:55:32.060 --> 00:55:34.459
and he continued to clarify the responsibilities

00:55:34.459 --> 00:55:36.290
of the different courts.

00:55:36.290 --> 00:55:38.300
Criminal and crown cases were handled

00:55:38.300 --> 00:55:40.130
by the Court of King's Bench.

00:55:40.130 --> 00:55:43.250
The Court of the Exchequer dealt with the royal finance,

00:55:43.250 --> 00:55:44.630
and the Court of Common Plea

00:55:44.630 --> 00:55:48.290
handled more of the day-to-day cases between subjects.

00:55:48.290 --> 00:55:52.820
From these roots, a new profession sprouted, lawyers.

00:55:52.820 --> 00:55:55.370
Needing to keep his new courts running smoothly,

00:55:55.370 --> 00:55:58.370
he took the profession of law away from the clergy

00:55:58.370 --> 00:56:01.670
and formed a new social class of educated young men

00:56:01.670 --> 00:56:03.740
whose job was to learn the law

00:56:03.740 --> 00:56:06.320
away from the influence of the church.

00:56:06.320 --> 00:56:09.590
This led to the establishment of the Inns of Court,

00:56:09.590 --> 00:56:13.010
grade mansions where students and barristers lived together.

00:56:13.010 --> 00:56:16.160
The barristers taught the students English common law,

00:56:16.160 --> 00:56:18.530
along with necessary social skills,

00:56:18.530 --> 00:56:20.420
such as music and dancing.

00:56:20.420 --> 00:56:23.300
These Inns of Court also set the precedent

00:56:23.300 --> 00:56:26.090
for other collegiate systems around the country.

00:56:26.090 --> 00:56:27.800
It was during King Edwards reign

00:56:27.800 --> 00:56:29.870
that the academic system we know today

00:56:29.870 --> 00:56:32.660
as Oxford University was founded,

00:56:32.660 --> 00:56:35.090
building on the earlier schools established

00:56:35.090 --> 00:56:38.810
by Alfred the Great over 200 years before.

00:56:38.810 --> 00:56:42.470
King Edward I first died of dysentery in 1307

00:56:42.470 --> 00:56:44.480
while fighting the Scottish up north.

00:56:44.480 --> 00:56:46.640
There is a rumor that on his deathbed,

00:56:46.640 --> 00:56:49.760
Edward wished for his bones to be taken with the army

00:56:49.760 --> 00:56:52.610
while they continued their fight into Scotland.

00:56:52.610 --> 00:56:55.310
Another rumor claims that Edward wished for his heart

00:56:55.310 --> 00:56:57.560
to accompany the next crusaders

00:56:57.560 --> 00:57:00.290
as they marched into the holy land once more.

00:57:00.290 --> 00:57:02.690
Regardless, what these stories show

00:57:02.690 --> 00:57:06.980
is that Edward very much considered himself a warrior king.

00:57:06.980 --> 00:57:10.520
While he was a successful military commander,

00:57:10.520 --> 00:57:12.680
it was his administrative actions

00:57:12.680 --> 00:57:16.250
that had the biggest impact on England as a whole.

00:57:16.250 --> 00:57:17.690
The introduction of lawyers

00:57:17.690 --> 00:57:20.150
mingled with the burgeoning merchant class

00:57:20.150 --> 00:57:22.490
to form a proto middle class,

00:57:22.490 --> 00:57:24.530
where before there had been none,

00:57:24.530 --> 00:57:26.030
parliament was strengthened

00:57:26.030 --> 00:57:28.400
and legitimized during his reign.

00:57:28.400 --> 00:57:31.100
And despite his war-like tendencies,

00:57:31.100 --> 00:57:34.190
King Edward's reign was peaceful and prosperous

00:57:34.190 --> 00:57:35.723
for the average Englishman.

00:57:37.375 --> 00:57:40.520
(light music)

00:57:40.520 --> 00:57:43.790
King Edward I was succeeded by his son, Edward II,

00:57:43.790 --> 00:57:48.020
who was crowned in 1307 at Westminster Abbey.

00:57:48.020 --> 00:57:50.120
While his father had immediately launched

00:57:50.120 --> 00:57:52.340
into fixing the realm he had inherited,

00:57:52.340 --> 00:57:54.620
Edward II had no need to.

00:57:54.620 --> 00:57:56.900
His father's kingdom was flourishing,

00:57:56.900 --> 00:57:59.120
bolstered by great social changes

00:57:59.120 --> 00:58:01.220
and the newly inherited Scottish crown.

00:58:01.220 --> 00:58:03.980
It was a stable territory that was emerging

00:58:03.980 --> 00:58:08.030
as one of the most powerful kingdoms in all of Europe.

00:58:08.030 --> 00:58:10.550
But despite its power and prestige,

00:58:10.550 --> 00:58:12.200
the new king Edward appeared

00:58:12.200 --> 00:58:14.900
to almost resent the English crown

00:58:14.900 --> 00:58:16.820
that now rested on his head.

00:58:16.820 --> 00:58:19.580
He grew bored of his royal responsibilities

00:58:19.580 --> 00:58:21.170
and quickly turned his attention

00:58:21.170 --> 00:58:24.050
towards other pursuits, young men.

00:58:24.050 --> 00:58:25.836
The first of these deep infatuations

00:58:25.836 --> 00:58:29.750
the king would come to have was with Piers Gaveston.

00:58:29.750 --> 00:58:32.840
Gaveston was arrogant and well aware of his position

00:58:32.840 --> 00:58:34.190
as the king's favorite,

00:58:34.190 --> 00:58:36.590
abusing his power and coming to blows

00:58:36.590 --> 00:58:39.290
with many of the other barons of England.

00:58:39.290 --> 00:58:41.360
He was a close companion to the king,

00:58:41.360 --> 00:58:43.190
accompanying him everywhere,

00:58:43.190 --> 00:58:45.920
but this wasn't well received by everyone.

00:58:45.920 --> 00:58:49.850
Soon, Gaveston's behavior angered the French royal family,

00:58:49.850 --> 00:58:53.420
to whom Edward II had married into through his wife,

00:58:53.420 --> 00:58:55.220
Isabella of France.

00:58:55.220 --> 00:58:57.890
With pressure mounting from both his nobility

00:58:57.890 --> 00:58:59.510
and the French crown,

00:58:59.510 --> 00:59:04.070
King Edward II was forced to exile Piers Gaveston,

00:59:04.070 --> 00:59:05.720
but this didn't last long.

00:59:05.720 --> 00:59:08.690
By 1307, Gaveston was back in England

00:59:08.690 --> 00:59:11.390
and once again at the king's side.

00:59:11.390 --> 00:59:14.030
Parliament met in 1308 with the king

00:59:14.030 --> 00:59:16.730
eager to discuss potential government reform,

00:59:16.730 --> 00:59:18.740
but the barons were unwilling to proceed

00:59:18.740 --> 00:59:21.680
until the issue of Gaveston had been dealt with.

00:59:21.680 --> 00:59:23.660
The king was initially dismissive

00:59:23.660 --> 00:59:26.480
and a violent outcome seemed inevitable.

00:59:26.480 --> 00:59:28.700
But after the archbishop of Canterbury

00:59:28.700 --> 00:59:31.520
threatened to have Gaveston excommunicated,

00:59:31.520 --> 00:59:33.740
Edward miraculously yielded.

00:59:33.740 --> 00:59:36.380
Gaveston was to be sent to Aquitaine,

00:59:36.380 --> 00:59:38.720
away from England for good.

00:59:38.720 --> 00:59:42.260
Unsurprisingly, though, this did not last.

00:59:42.260 --> 00:59:45.020
The king once again recalled Gaveston,

00:59:45.020 --> 00:59:48.560
angering the barons and sparking an insurrection.

00:59:48.560 --> 00:59:50.330
After a period of cat and mouse

00:59:50.330 --> 00:59:53.180
between the king and the armies of his nobility,

00:59:53.180 --> 00:59:56.630
Gaveston was eventually captured at Scarborough Castle

00:59:56.630 --> 00:59:59.960
and taken to Warwick where he was tried as a traitor.

00:59:59.960 --> 01:00:02.420
Gaveston was beheaded on the authority

01:00:02.420 --> 01:00:04.190
of the earl of Lancaster.

01:00:04.190 --> 01:00:07.610
The king was reportedly inconsolable.

01:00:07.610 --> 01:00:10.310
Still reeling from the death of his friend,

01:00:10.310 --> 01:00:12.500
Edward was decisively defeated

01:00:12.500 --> 01:00:16.040
at the Battle of Bannockburn by Robert the Bruce,

01:00:16.040 --> 01:00:19.220
and after just 18 years of English rule,

01:00:19.220 --> 01:00:23.900
Scotland gained its independence once more in 1314.

01:00:23.900 --> 01:00:26.570
However, the king tempered his foreign losses

01:00:26.570 --> 01:00:29.300
with a new favorite, Hugh Le Despenser.

01:00:29.300 --> 01:00:31.070
Like with Gaveston before,

01:00:31.070 --> 01:00:34.400
Despenser and his family grew increasingly powerful

01:00:34.400 --> 01:00:36.470
as King Edward's favorites,

01:00:36.470 --> 01:00:38.930
but the barons of England had had enough.

01:00:38.930 --> 01:00:41.030
A fresh civil war broke out,

01:00:41.030 --> 01:00:44.000
which saw an army led by the Earl of Lancaster,

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:47.420
Gaveston's killer, face off against the crown

01:00:47.420 --> 01:00:49.280
and her royal forces.

01:00:49.280 --> 01:00:51.620
After five years of bloodshed,

01:00:51.620 --> 01:00:54.920
King Edward II emerged victorious.

01:00:54.920 --> 01:00:58.280
The Earl of Lancaster got a taste of his own medicine

01:00:58.280 --> 01:01:02.807
and was beheaded at Pontefract Castle in 1326.

01:01:02.807 --> 01:01:05.690
The Despenser clan, whose power had been growing

01:01:05.690 --> 01:01:07.130
even before the war,

01:01:07.130 --> 01:01:10.460
now saw their influence skyrocket across England.

01:01:10.460 --> 01:01:11.990
With the barons defeated,

01:01:11.990 --> 01:01:14.870
Isabella was once again forced to step in.

01:01:14.870 --> 01:01:16.910
With backing from the French crown,

01:01:16.910 --> 01:01:18.560
Queen Isabella raised an army

01:01:18.560 --> 01:01:20.600
and marched against her husband.

01:01:20.600 --> 01:01:23.660
Aided by her longtime lover, Roger Mortimer,

01:01:23.660 --> 01:01:26.540
the king defeated King Edward and his army,

01:01:26.540 --> 01:01:28.490
captured Hugh Le Despenser,

01:01:28.490 --> 01:01:31.160
and tried the young chamberlain with treason.

01:01:31.160 --> 01:01:36.160
Despenser was, unsurprisingly, found guilty and hung, drawn,

01:01:36.170 --> 01:01:39.200
and courted for his crimes.

01:01:39.200 --> 01:01:42.260
Fearing that her husband would once again undermine her,

01:01:42.260 --> 01:01:46.820
Queen Isabella forced King Edward II to abdicate his throne.

01:01:46.820 --> 01:01:48.590
It was decided that their son,

01:01:48.590 --> 01:01:51.629
Edward III, would take over in his place.

01:01:51.629 --> 01:01:54.462
(energetic music)

01:01:56.660 --> 01:01:59.061
He was only 15 when the English crown

01:01:59.061 --> 01:02:01.790
came to rest on his head, but the young king

01:02:01.790 --> 01:02:05.150
already had a big mess ahead of him to clean up.

01:02:05.150 --> 01:02:08.060
His father's unorthodox style of governance

01:02:08.060 --> 01:02:11.690
had left England in a financially precarious position,

01:02:11.690 --> 01:02:14.630
and the crown's influence had been steadily undermined

01:02:14.630 --> 01:02:17.390
by the barons who administered the lands.

01:02:17.390 --> 01:02:20.120
But before he could set about fixing his kingdom,

01:02:20.120 --> 01:02:22.340
he would have to wait to come of age.

01:02:22.340 --> 01:02:24.650
In the meantime, his mother Isabella

01:02:24.650 --> 01:02:28.520
and Roger Mortimer ruled as regents in his place.

01:02:28.520 --> 01:02:31.370
However, King Edward hated this.

01:02:31.370 --> 01:02:33.650
Mortimer held all the power,

01:02:33.650 --> 01:02:36.050
and Edward grew resentful of his mother,

01:02:36.050 --> 01:02:39.560
who always sided with her lover on courtly matters.

01:02:39.560 --> 01:02:43.700
In 1330, on the eve of his 18th birthday,

01:02:43.700 --> 01:02:47.480
King Edward III rebelled against his regents,

01:02:47.480 --> 01:02:49.790
having his mother's lover hanged

01:02:49.790 --> 01:02:52.940
and taking full control over the English crown.

01:02:52.940 --> 01:02:55.520
With power now firmly his,

01:02:55.520 --> 01:02:58.490
Edward did what most medieval kings do.

01:02:58.490 --> 01:03:00.200
He waged war.

01:03:00.200 --> 01:03:01.280
Turning his attention

01:03:01.280 --> 01:03:04.010
to the newly independent Kingdom of Scotland,

01:03:04.010 --> 01:03:06.710
he mounted a successful campaign against them,

01:03:06.710 --> 01:03:10.400
crushing their army and retaking land his father had lost.

01:03:10.400 --> 01:03:12.770
But these gains were hard to hold onto,

01:03:12.770 --> 01:03:14.630
and soon a new conflict

01:03:14.630 --> 01:03:17.330
would demand all of King Edward's attention.

01:03:17.330 --> 01:03:21.170
In 1337, King Philip VI of France

01:03:21.170 --> 01:03:24.410
confiscated the English king's Duchy of Aquitaine,

01:03:24.410 --> 01:03:27.590
a move that greatly angered Edward.

01:03:27.590 --> 01:03:29.840
Instead of seeking a peaceful resolution

01:03:29.840 --> 01:03:32.420
like his father had, King Edward responded

01:03:32.420 --> 01:03:35.900
by laying claim to the French throne.

01:03:35.900 --> 01:03:39.224
He didn't know it, but this would be the start of a long

01:03:39.224 --> 01:03:42.860
and bloody conflict that would come to claim the lives

01:03:42.860 --> 01:03:47.860
of millions, outliving him and his grandsons.

01:03:47.871 --> 01:03:50.704
(uplifting music)

01:03:52.310 --> 01:03:55.340
As the grandson of Philip IV of France,

01:03:55.340 --> 01:03:58.730
Edward did technically have a claim to the French throne,

01:03:58.730 --> 01:04:01.010
but because of the newly set precedent

01:04:01.010 --> 01:04:02.600
of agnatic succession,

01:04:02.600 --> 01:04:05.960
which only gave the male heirs a claim to succession,

01:04:05.960 --> 01:04:07.460
Edward's link through his mother

01:04:07.460 --> 01:04:09.830
was rejected by the French courts.

01:04:09.830 --> 01:04:13.430
Regardless, King Edward III was ready to fight.

01:04:13.430 --> 01:04:15.290
After some initial setbacks,

01:04:15.290 --> 01:04:18.110
the first phase of the war went well for England.

01:04:18.110 --> 01:04:20.600
Their success at Crecy and Poitiers

01:04:20.600 --> 01:04:23.900
led to the highly favorable treaty of Bretigny,

01:04:23.900 --> 01:04:27.380
which saw England make territorial gains on the continent,

01:04:27.380 --> 01:04:29.750
but forced Edward to renounce his claim

01:04:29.750 --> 01:04:31.040
to the French throne.

01:04:31.040 --> 01:04:33.260
This was by no means a peace treaty

01:04:33.260 --> 01:04:36.350
and fighting quickly resumed between the two kingdoms,

01:04:36.350 --> 01:04:37.953
but by this point, either side

01:04:37.953 --> 01:04:41.420
had other greater problems to deal with.

01:04:41.420 --> 01:04:44.570
All of Europe, in fact, was reeling as a result

01:04:44.570 --> 01:04:49.016
of the single most deadly event in human history.

01:04:49.016 --> 01:04:51.980
(bright music)

01:04:51.980 --> 01:04:56.360
In 1348, the Black Death had arrived in England.

01:04:56.360 --> 01:04:58.880
Plus-filled tumors, bile, and blood,

01:04:58.880 --> 01:05:00.860
the streets of London were littered

01:05:00.860 --> 01:05:03.530
with the rotting corpses of the dead.

01:05:03.530 --> 01:05:06.440
Believed by many to be a curse from God Himself,

01:05:06.440 --> 01:05:09.830
the bubonic plague claimed anywhere between 1/3

01:05:09.830 --> 01:05:14.630
to half of the population of Europe in just five years.

01:05:14.630 --> 01:05:16.190
King Edward was fortunate enough

01:05:16.190 --> 01:05:18.230
to avoid contact with the disease,

01:05:18.230 --> 01:05:19.550
which spread in the cramped

01:05:19.550 --> 01:05:23.120
and overcrowded living conditions of England's major cities

01:05:23.120 --> 01:05:26.630
and decimated the normal population.

01:05:26.630 --> 01:05:29.300
The plague did more to accelerate social change

01:05:29.300 --> 01:05:32.840
than any singular event in English history before it.

01:05:32.840 --> 01:05:36.800
The unimaginably high death toll led to a labor shortage

01:05:36.800 --> 01:05:39.560
that severely impacted the English economy.

01:05:39.560 --> 01:05:41.690
With fewer hands to work the fields,

01:05:41.690 --> 01:05:44.780
many landowners were forced to enclose their lands,

01:05:44.780 --> 01:05:47.900
switching from traditional labor intensive crop farming

01:05:47.900 --> 01:05:51.860
to the comparatively less labor intensive, sheep herding.

01:05:51.860 --> 01:05:54.860
Raising sheep required 1/5 of the manpower,

01:05:54.860 --> 01:05:56.510
and feudal lords allowed peasants

01:05:56.510 --> 01:05:58.640
who had previously been tied to their land

01:05:58.640 --> 01:06:02.570
in a style of serfdom to purchase their freedom and leave.

01:06:02.570 --> 01:06:05.960
A new class emerged, free laborers.

01:06:05.960 --> 01:06:08.540
People who had been previously bound to an area

01:06:08.540 --> 01:06:11.930
for generations were now free to move about

01:06:11.930 --> 01:06:13.790
and many settled in the large cities

01:06:13.790 --> 01:06:16.370
that had been devastated by the plague.

01:06:16.370 --> 01:06:18.920
This switch to sheep herding and wool farming

01:06:18.920 --> 01:06:21.260
would also transform the English economy

01:06:21.260 --> 01:06:24.410
in the coming years, but more on that later.

01:06:24.410 --> 01:06:26.600
As a result, by the end of his reign,

01:06:26.600 --> 01:06:30.710
King Edward III's kingdom looked almost unrecognizable.

01:06:30.710 --> 01:06:32.060
He had transformed England

01:06:32.060 --> 01:06:35.750
into one of the most formidable military powers in Europe,

01:06:35.750 --> 01:06:38.690
further developed legislation and the role of government,

01:06:38.690 --> 01:06:41.180
and completely revamped the economy,

01:06:41.180 --> 01:06:42.616
ushering in a golden age

01:06:42.616 --> 01:06:45.170
as England recovered from the Black Death.

01:06:45.170 --> 01:06:47.570
His 50 years on the English throne

01:06:47.570 --> 01:06:49.610
made him the longest ruling king

01:06:49.610 --> 01:06:51.710
the English throne had ever seen,

01:06:51.710 --> 01:06:54.020
but those final years were dominated

01:06:54.020 --> 01:06:55.910
by sickness and ill health.

01:06:55.910 --> 01:06:59.480
He died on the 21st of June, 1377,

01:06:59.480 --> 01:07:02.750
having outlived his own son, the Black Prince.

01:07:02.750 --> 01:07:04.370
The crown was instead passed on

01:07:04.370 --> 01:07:06.593
to Edward's grandson, Richard II.

01:07:08.361 --> 01:07:11.480
(bright music)

01:07:11.480 --> 01:07:13.130
Richard was a young king,

01:07:13.130 --> 01:07:16.010
first wearing the crown at just 10 years of age,

01:07:16.010 --> 01:07:18.350
which meant like his grandfather before him,

01:07:18.350 --> 01:07:20.900
he was forced to rely on the regency of others

01:07:20.900 --> 01:07:22.130
while he came of age.

01:07:22.130 --> 01:07:25.970
John of Gaunt was the first virtual ruler to take over.

01:07:25.970 --> 01:07:28.460
He had stepped in during King Edward's final years

01:07:28.460 --> 01:07:31.520
when sickness and age kept the king bound bed

01:07:31.520 --> 01:07:32.600
and continued to rule

01:07:32.600 --> 01:07:35.810
after King Richard's coronation in 1337.

01:07:35.810 --> 01:07:37.640
There was just one problem.

01:07:37.640 --> 01:07:40.760
Edward's long reign had by no means been easy,

01:07:40.760 --> 01:07:44.330
and by now, the cracks that had started to form previously

01:07:44.330 --> 01:07:47.570
were on the verge of entirely breaking apart.

01:07:47.570 --> 01:07:50.030
You see, the English treasury had been stretched

01:07:50.030 --> 01:07:52.730
to its limits, as it struggled to keep financing

01:07:52.730 --> 01:07:55.040
the ongoing Hundred Years' War.

01:07:55.040 --> 01:07:57.470
France was larger and wealthier than England

01:07:57.470 --> 01:08:00.500
and so had no problem pouring vast amounts of money

01:08:00.500 --> 01:08:02.090
behind their armies.

01:08:02.090 --> 01:08:05.930
Specifically during this time, there was a very real fear

01:08:05.930 --> 01:08:08.000
of a French invasion on the island,

01:08:08.000 --> 01:08:11.300
and the English army was in no position to challenge it.

01:08:11.300 --> 01:08:14.270
So John of Gaunt introduced a new poll tax

01:08:14.270 --> 01:08:17.450
that required every person over the age of 15

01:08:17.450 --> 01:08:20.960
to pay one shilling towards the war effort on the continent.

01:08:20.960 --> 01:08:23.450
This was not an insignificant amount of money

01:08:23.450 --> 01:08:24.830
for people at the time,

01:08:24.830 --> 01:08:28.250
and the peasantry strongly opposed the new tax.

01:08:28.250 --> 01:08:32.060
With the post-plague economic boom now firmly over,

01:08:32.060 --> 01:08:34.130
peasants had returned to low paying work

01:08:34.130 --> 01:08:36.320
in an effort to keep food on the table.

01:08:36.320 --> 01:08:38.660
Alongside this, landowners in England

01:08:38.660 --> 01:08:41.090
had been trying to reintroduce servility

01:08:41.090 --> 01:08:43.190
and serfdom back to the land,

01:08:43.190 --> 01:08:46.550
and all these factors combined to form one major event

01:08:46.550 --> 01:08:49.973
that threatened King Richard's rule immensely.

01:08:51.252 --> 01:08:54.530
(dramatic music)

01:08:54.530 --> 01:08:56.660
Led by the Priest John Ball,

01:08:56.660 --> 01:09:00.230
a mob of 100,000 people marched on London

01:09:00.230 --> 01:09:03.020
demanding the new poll tax be abolished,

01:09:03.020 --> 01:09:06.410
a major uprising known as the Peasants' Revolt.

01:09:06.410 --> 01:09:08.120
The crowd was unruly,

01:09:08.120 --> 01:09:10.610
and within hours of their arrival in the capital,

01:09:10.610 --> 01:09:13.010
a destructive rampage broke out.

01:09:13.010 --> 01:09:15.830
The protestors burnt down the Savoy Palace,

01:09:15.830 --> 01:09:17.360
home of John of Gaunt,

01:09:17.360 --> 01:09:20.840
and even murdered the archbishop of Canterbury.

01:09:20.840 --> 01:09:22.490
Faced with a little choice,

01:09:22.490 --> 01:09:25.100
King Richard II and the lord mayor of London

01:09:25.100 --> 01:09:27.230
met with the demonstrators in a field

01:09:27.230 --> 01:09:30.470
just outside the city to discuss their terms.

01:09:30.470 --> 01:09:33.260
The conversation began amicably enough,

01:09:33.260 --> 01:09:36.950
but one of the other leaders, Wat Tyler, grew abusive

01:09:36.950 --> 01:09:40.400
and demanded more than the king and mayor would concede.

01:09:40.400 --> 01:09:43.850
Offended, the lord mayor of London drew his sword

01:09:43.850 --> 01:09:46.190
and killed Tyler on the spot.

01:09:46.190 --> 01:09:48.740
Fearing that the crowd would turn violent again,

01:09:48.740 --> 01:09:52.220
the young king made an extraordinarily brave move.

01:09:52.220 --> 01:09:53.780
Standing before the crowd,

01:09:53.780 --> 01:09:56.180
he shouted to the peasants to follow him.

01:09:56.180 --> 01:09:58.910
Leading them away from their leader's dead body,

01:09:58.910 --> 01:10:01.130
he promised that he would enact the reforms

01:10:01.130 --> 01:10:04.880
they had insisted on and successfully disperse the crowd.

01:10:04.880 --> 01:10:08.030
These were, however, hollow promises.

01:10:08.030 --> 01:10:10.910
Immediately after the protesters had returned home,

01:10:10.910 --> 01:10:12.770
the king's council of advisors

01:10:12.770 --> 01:10:15.860
revoked any concessions made by their ruler

01:10:15.860 --> 01:10:18.920
and swiftly set about crushing the rebels.

01:10:18.920 --> 01:10:21.320
The leaders of the Peasants' Revolt were tried

01:10:21.320 --> 01:10:24.200
and hanged as traitors for their crimes.

01:10:24.200 --> 01:10:26.930
The king never forgot the actions of his council,

01:10:26.930 --> 01:10:30.140
and this episode ignited a deep sense of mistrust

01:10:30.140 --> 01:10:33.200
between himself and his advisors.

01:10:33.200 --> 01:10:35.690
As a result, his inner circle shrink

01:10:35.690 --> 01:10:38.090
until it only included three men,

01:10:38.090 --> 01:10:40.670
who in turn became extremely powerful

01:10:40.670 --> 01:10:42.590
due to their closeness to the king.

01:10:42.590 --> 01:10:45.710
The other nobles became resentful of this favoritism

01:10:45.710 --> 01:10:48.980
and feared that their power would soon diminish as a result.

01:10:48.980 --> 01:10:52.370
Banding together, a group of powerful lords united

01:10:52.370 --> 01:10:55.040
to form a group called the Lords Appellant.

01:10:55.040 --> 01:10:58.910
They seized control of the English government in 1387

01:10:58.910 --> 01:11:02.750
and demanded the king expel his inner circle from court.

01:11:02.750 --> 01:11:04.791
A period of instability followed

01:11:04.791 --> 01:11:08.360
and culminated in the king being forced to banish

01:11:08.360 --> 01:11:11.450
or execute those closest to him.

01:11:11.450 --> 01:11:14.750
For the next decade, the fragile peace held,

01:11:14.750 --> 01:11:16.880
and King Richard was slowly able

01:11:16.880 --> 01:11:18.980
to reestablish royal authority,

01:11:18.980 --> 01:11:21.683
and bring it away from the merciless parliament

01:11:21.683 --> 01:11:23.480
of the Lords Appellant.

01:11:23.480 --> 01:11:26.900
In 1397, the king had amassed enough support

01:11:26.900 --> 01:11:28.430
to get his revenge.

01:11:28.430 --> 01:11:29.870
In a period that historians

01:11:29.870 --> 01:11:32.420
would come to call a Richard's tyranny,

01:11:32.420 --> 01:11:34.190
the king captured, tried,

01:11:34.190 --> 01:11:37.880
and executed a number of the Appellant Lords.

01:11:37.880 --> 01:11:41.810
In 1398, Richard's tyranny went a step further,

01:11:41.810 --> 01:11:45.380
as he declared all acts of the merciless parliament

01:11:45.380 --> 01:11:47.330
to be null and void.

01:11:47.330 --> 01:11:50.090
He then delegated all parliamentary power

01:11:50.090 --> 01:11:53.300
to a committee of 12 lords and six commoners,

01:11:53.300 --> 01:11:55.700
each chosen by the king himself,

01:11:55.700 --> 01:11:58.580
effectively making Richard an absolute ruler

01:11:58.580 --> 01:12:01.220
who no longer needed parliament's support,

01:12:01.220 --> 01:12:02.720
but there still existed a threat

01:12:02.720 --> 01:12:05.870
to Richard's rule, House Lancaster.

01:12:05.870 --> 01:12:08.390
At its head sat John of Gaunt

01:12:08.390 --> 01:12:11.750
who represented the most powerful non-royal household

01:12:11.750 --> 01:12:12.680
on the island.

01:12:12.680 --> 01:12:16.460
King Richard had exiled John's son, Henry Bolingbroke,

01:12:16.460 --> 01:12:19.160
during his initial takeover a year before,

01:12:19.160 --> 01:12:22.010
but House Lancaster still stood in his way.

01:12:22.010 --> 01:12:25.160
Not only did they possess enormous wealth,

01:12:25.160 --> 01:12:26.990
but they were royal descendants.

01:12:26.990 --> 01:12:30.620
John, being King Edward III's youngest surviving son,

01:12:30.620 --> 01:12:33.980
as a result, it was the wish of many in the land

01:12:33.980 --> 01:12:37.400
that House Lancaster would succeed a childless Richard

01:12:37.400 --> 01:12:39.140
to the English throne.

01:12:39.140 --> 01:12:43.520
Lucky for Richard though, John of Gaunt died in 1399,

01:12:43.520 --> 01:12:46.520
giving the king time to secure his power.

01:12:46.520 --> 01:12:48.830
He had John's son, Henry Bolingbroke,

01:12:48.830 --> 01:12:52.546
who he'd exiled to France, disowned, confiscating his lands

01:12:52.546 --> 01:12:55.070
and effectively stripping Bolingbroke

01:12:55.070 --> 01:12:56.810
of his claim to the throne.

01:12:56.810 --> 01:12:58.850
Feeling as though he'd effectively dealt

01:12:58.850 --> 01:13:02.000
with the Lancastrian threat, Richard turned his attention

01:13:02.000 --> 01:13:05.120
to the growing Irish problem in the west.

01:13:05.120 --> 01:13:07.640
He amassed an army of 8,000 men

01:13:07.640 --> 01:13:10.310
and left England in May, 1399,

01:13:10.310 --> 01:13:14.360
landing in Dublin within the week, but just a month later,

01:13:14.360 --> 01:13:17.810
triple on the continent spilled over into England.

01:13:17.810 --> 01:13:22.550
Charles VI, King of France, had been deposed by Louis I,

01:13:22.550 --> 01:13:24.770
and the new French king saw a chance

01:13:24.770 --> 01:13:27.740
to gain the upper hand against his English foe.

01:13:27.740 --> 01:13:30.350
In a continuation of the Hundred Years' War,

01:13:30.350 --> 01:13:33.440
Louis allowed Henry Bolingbroke to return to England

01:13:33.440 --> 01:13:36.817
with a small force, where Henry soon gathered more support

01:13:36.817 --> 01:13:39.140
and made a claim to the throne.

01:13:39.140 --> 01:13:41.210
With Richard off fighting in Ireland,

01:13:41.210 --> 01:13:44.900
Henry's arrival was entirely unchallenged.

01:13:44.900 --> 01:13:45.890
He gathered an army

01:13:45.890 --> 01:13:48.920
and soon defeated King Richard II in battle.

01:13:48.920 --> 01:13:50.660
The king was then imprisoned

01:13:50.660 --> 01:13:54.230
and later died of starvation while in the Tower of London.

01:13:54.230 --> 01:13:57.230
While Henry's claim to the throne was weak,

01:13:57.230 --> 01:14:00.950
it was unopposed by both the people and parliament,

01:14:00.950 --> 01:14:04.220
and Henry Bolingbroke was crowned Henry IV

01:14:04.220 --> 01:14:07.463
on the 30th of September, 1399.

01:14:09.199 --> 01:14:11.990
(bright music)

01:14:11.990 --> 01:14:15.740
The reign of Henry IV was marked by a series of firsts.

01:14:15.740 --> 01:14:17.900
He is believed to be the first king

01:14:17.900 --> 01:14:20.930
since the Normans had invaded in 1066

01:14:20.930 --> 01:14:23.420
to address his people in English

01:14:23.420 --> 01:14:25.670
as opposed to Norman French.

01:14:25.670 --> 01:14:29.630
He also hosted a visit from Manuel II Palaiologos

01:14:29.630 --> 01:14:32.660
shortly after his coronation in 1400,

01:14:32.660 --> 01:14:36.200
making this the only time a Byzantine emperor

01:14:36.200 --> 01:14:38.000
ever visited England.

01:14:38.000 --> 01:14:40.700
In 1406, English pirates captured

01:14:40.700 --> 01:14:43.310
the future James I of Scotland.

01:14:43.310 --> 01:14:46.610
Then, aged 11, off the coast of Yorkshire,

01:14:46.610 --> 01:14:49.100
the young prince would remain Henry's prisoner

01:14:49.100 --> 01:14:50.630
for the rest of his reign.

01:14:50.630 --> 01:14:51.860
Aside from that, though,

01:14:51.860 --> 01:14:55.550
the reign of King Henry IV was largely uneventful.

01:14:55.550 --> 01:14:57.590
He was mainly forced to deal with plots

01:14:57.590 --> 01:15:00.200
and rebellions from abroad, as well as a number

01:15:00.200 --> 01:15:03.200
of domestic assassination attempts on his life.

01:15:03.200 --> 01:15:05.180
He put down a rebellion in Wales

01:15:05.180 --> 01:15:08.240
against Owain Glyndwr in 1400

01:15:08.240 --> 01:15:10.880
and was forced to deal with a series of rebellions

01:15:10.880 --> 01:15:15.350
led by Henry Percy, 1st Earl of Northumberland in the north.

01:15:15.350 --> 01:15:17.900
The Percy Rebellion, as it came to be known,

01:15:17.900 --> 01:15:21.380
ended at the Battle of Shrewsbury in 1403,

01:15:21.380 --> 01:15:24.470
where Henry's eldest son, Henry of Monmouth,

01:15:24.470 --> 01:15:27.637
showed great military prowess, leading his troops

01:15:27.637 --> 01:15:31.790
in a decisive victory against Percy's forces.

01:15:31.790 --> 01:15:34.250
During the battle, though, Henry of Monmouth

01:15:34.250 --> 01:15:38.510
was struck by an arrow to the face, but luckily survived.

01:15:38.510 --> 01:15:40.280
During the last years of his rule,

01:15:40.280 --> 01:15:42.800
the rebellions had become more frequent.

01:15:42.800 --> 01:15:45.380
A rumor soon took hold in London that Richard II

01:15:45.380 --> 01:15:49.100
who had died of starvation in the Tower of London

01:15:49.100 --> 01:15:51.350
was actually still alive.

01:15:51.350 --> 01:15:53.720
This was all in spite of Henry's best efforts

01:15:53.720 --> 01:15:56.570
to prove Richard had died while in captivity.

01:15:56.570 --> 01:15:59.420
King Henry had the body of Richard on display

01:15:59.420 --> 01:16:02.480
at St. Paul Cathedral shortly after his death

01:16:02.480 --> 01:16:04.700
in an effort to prove to his supporters

01:16:04.700 --> 01:16:07.370
that the old king had in fact died

01:16:07.370 --> 01:16:09.980
and that his death had not been violent.

01:16:09.980 --> 01:16:12.558
However, this didn't stop Scottish emissaries

01:16:12.558 --> 01:16:15.320
from traveling throughout the villages of England

01:16:15.320 --> 01:16:17.600
declaring that Richard was alive

01:16:17.600 --> 01:16:19.520
and residing at the Scottish court.

01:16:19.520 --> 01:16:23.030
Sir Elias Lyvet and his associate Thomas Clark

01:16:23.030 --> 01:16:25.310
searched for an appropriate lookalike

01:16:25.310 --> 01:16:29.240
and promised him Scottish aid to carry out the insurrection.

01:16:29.240 --> 01:16:32.150
Unsurprisingly, the rebellion came to nothing.

01:16:32.150 --> 01:16:33.440
Lyvet was released

01:16:33.440 --> 01:16:36.290
and Clark was thrown into the Tower of London.

01:16:36.290 --> 01:16:37.790
Towards the end of his life,

01:16:37.790 --> 01:16:41.510
Henry was taken by recurring bouts of serious ill health.

01:16:41.510 --> 01:16:43.670
Henry died in London at the Abbot's House

01:16:43.670 --> 01:16:46.610
of Westminster Abbey and the Jerusalem Chamber

01:16:46.610 --> 01:16:48.740
during a convocation of parliament.

01:16:48.740 --> 01:16:51.200
He was buried at Canterbury Cathedral

01:16:51.200 --> 01:16:53.690
adjacent to the shrine of Thomas Becket.

01:16:53.690 --> 01:16:55.940
The English throne in its entirety

01:16:55.940 --> 01:16:59.153
would go on to his son, Henry of Monmouth.

01:17:01.116 --> 01:17:04.040
(gloomy music)

01:17:04.040 --> 01:17:07.580
On April 9th, 1413, Henry of Monmouth

01:17:07.580 --> 01:17:10.850
was crowned Henry V at Westminster Abbey.

01:17:10.850 --> 01:17:12.500
On the day of his coronation,

01:17:12.500 --> 01:17:15.740
a terrible snowstorm blew over the crowds,

01:17:15.740 --> 01:17:18.290
but the king addressed as people despite it.

01:17:18.290 --> 01:17:21.020
Described as very tall with a slim build

01:17:21.020 --> 01:17:22.610
and a ruddy complexion,

01:17:22.610 --> 01:17:25.340
the young king had developed a taste for battle

01:17:25.340 --> 01:17:27.740
during his father's reign before him.

01:17:27.740 --> 01:17:30.170
He'd helped quash the Welsh rebellion

01:17:30.170 --> 01:17:33.230
and personally commanded the royal army to victory

01:17:33.230 --> 01:17:37.520
at the Battle of Shrewsbury at just 16 years of age.

01:17:37.520 --> 01:17:40.610
But Henry V had inherited many of the same problems

01:17:40.610 --> 01:17:42.290
his father had dealt with.

01:17:42.290 --> 01:17:45.710
The Lancastrian claim had its fair share of doubters,

01:17:45.710 --> 01:17:47.150
and the young king immediately

01:17:47.150 --> 01:17:49.700
set about securing his position on the throne.

01:17:49.700 --> 01:17:52.520
He wanted to rule a unified England

01:17:52.520 --> 01:17:54.980
and not deal with the constant threat of pretenders

01:17:54.980 --> 01:17:57.470
and usurpers like his father had.

01:17:57.470 --> 01:18:00.440
He allowed his past indifferences to be forgotten,

01:18:00.440 --> 01:18:03.710
honorably reinterring the late Richard II,

01:18:03.710 --> 01:18:05.870
giving Richard's son, Edmund Mortimer,

01:18:05.870 --> 01:18:09.230
a place on the council and gradually restoring titles

01:18:09.230 --> 01:18:10.430
in a states of those

01:18:10.430 --> 01:18:12.530
who had suffered under his father's reign.

01:18:12.530 --> 01:18:14.570
When he did face a serious threat,

01:18:14.570 --> 01:18:17.300
he proved a decisive decision maker.

01:18:17.300 --> 01:18:21.830
He ruthlessly put down the Lollard discontent in 1414

01:18:21.830 --> 01:18:24.620
and the Southampton Plot of 1415,

01:18:24.620 --> 01:18:27.080
which involved a number of earls and barons

01:18:27.080 --> 01:18:29.900
who supported Edmund Mortimer's claim to the throne,

01:18:29.900 --> 01:18:31.610
which was easily dealt with

01:18:31.610 --> 01:18:34.160
as had failed to gain much popular support.

01:18:34.160 --> 01:18:36.260
Mortimer himself remained loyal

01:18:36.260 --> 01:18:38.120
to the king throughout the plot.

01:18:38.120 --> 01:18:41.210
He promoted the use of the English language in government,

01:18:41.210 --> 01:18:42.650
keeping records in English

01:18:42.650 --> 01:18:45.320
and using English in his personal correspondence

01:18:45.320 --> 01:18:47.930
for the first time since the Norman Conquest

01:18:47.930 --> 01:18:50.450
350 years earlier.

01:18:50.450 --> 01:18:53.450
With his domestic situation now under control,

01:18:53.450 --> 01:18:55.760
Henry could turn his attention abroad.

01:18:55.760 --> 01:18:58.850
The Hundred Years' War was still ongoing,

01:18:58.850 --> 01:19:02.330
despite a brief period of inactivity from both sides.

01:19:02.330 --> 01:19:05.690
In 1415, King Henry V took an army

01:19:05.690 --> 01:19:07.970
and landed at Harfleur in Normandy,

01:19:07.970 --> 01:19:10.790
intent on regaining territory on the continent.

01:19:10.790 --> 01:19:12.200
After a brief siege,

01:19:12.200 --> 01:19:14.540
Henry and his men take the city of Harfleur,

01:19:14.540 --> 01:19:16.550
but it's a costly victory.

01:19:16.550 --> 01:19:19.100
It had taken Henry longer than he would've liked

01:19:19.100 --> 01:19:20.870
and his men had suffered.

01:19:20.870 --> 01:19:24.050
Having arrived in Normandy with 12,000 men,

01:19:24.050 --> 01:19:27.080
Henry's troops now numbered only 6,000

01:19:27.080 --> 01:19:30.350
due to desertion, starvation, and disease.

01:19:30.350 --> 01:19:32.300
Against the advice of his council,

01:19:32.300 --> 01:19:35.360
he ordered his men to march across the French countryside

01:19:35.360 --> 01:19:38.030
towards the English held port city of Calais

01:19:38.030 --> 01:19:40.520
where they could re-arm and return to England.

01:19:40.520 --> 01:19:42.650
Unable to cross the river Somme,

01:19:42.650 --> 01:19:45.770
Henry V was forced to make a detour inland

01:19:45.770 --> 01:19:48.470
where he was intercepted by French forces

01:19:48.470 --> 01:19:50.600
near the village of Agincourt.

01:19:50.600 --> 01:19:52.910
Henry's men were exhausted.

01:19:52.910 --> 01:19:55.340
The French army outnumbered them five to one,

01:19:55.340 --> 01:19:59.000
and many of the rank and file were suffering from dysentery.

01:19:59.000 --> 01:20:01.160
Regardless, Henry had little choice

01:20:01.160 --> 01:20:03.260
but to meet the French in battle.

01:20:03.260 --> 01:20:04.790
Heavy rain the night before

01:20:04.790 --> 01:20:07.490
had made the ground around them a marshy bog,

01:20:07.490 --> 01:20:09.850
and as the astute tactician that he was,

01:20:09.850 --> 01:20:12.800
he intended to use that to his advantage.

01:20:12.800 --> 01:20:15.590
At 11:00 AM, the French army attacked,

01:20:15.590 --> 01:20:19.730
mounting a cavalry charge straight at the main English line.

01:20:19.730 --> 01:20:21.470
Henry brought his archers forward

01:20:21.470 --> 01:20:23.720
and ordered them to unleash hell.

01:20:23.720 --> 01:20:26.660
With a 250 meter killing range,

01:20:26.660 --> 01:20:29.870
the English longbowman slaughtered the French cavalry

01:20:29.870 --> 01:20:31.940
who had been slowed down in the mud.

01:20:31.940 --> 01:20:33.740
Many were forced to dismount,

01:20:33.740 --> 01:20:36.560
and some drowned in the thick mud where they stood.

01:20:36.560 --> 01:20:39.260
By the time the cavalry reached the English line,

01:20:39.260 --> 01:20:40.610
Henry had ordered his archers

01:20:40.610 --> 01:20:43.640
to drive large, pointed stakes into the ground,

01:20:43.640 --> 01:20:45.830
a new tactic never before employed

01:20:45.830 --> 01:20:47.990
by the English against the French.

01:20:47.990 --> 01:20:51.830
The charge was rendered useless and a melee broke out.

01:20:51.830 --> 01:20:54.800
Eventually, the English archers abandoned their bows

01:20:54.800 --> 01:20:56.810
and took the fighting hand to hand.

01:20:56.810 --> 01:20:57.920
The tide of the battle

01:20:57.920 --> 01:21:00.350
quickly turned in favor of the English

01:21:00.350 --> 01:21:02.870
who hacked the French soldiers to death,

01:21:02.870 --> 01:21:04.850
many of whom who were stuck in the mud

01:21:04.850 --> 01:21:06.230
due to their heavy armor.

01:21:06.230 --> 01:21:09.170
Before long, Henry was victorious.

01:21:09.170 --> 01:21:12.050
His army marched in Calais unopposed.

01:21:12.050 --> 01:21:14.990
When he returned to England just a few months later,

01:21:14.990 --> 01:21:17.000
he received a hero's welcome.

01:21:17.000 --> 01:21:19.910
Crowds lined the streets, pageants took place,

01:21:19.910 --> 01:21:22.460
and choir sang in all the churches.

01:21:22.460 --> 01:21:25.220
It was a great moment of pride for England

01:21:25.220 --> 01:21:27.830
and proved to be the greatest English victory

01:21:27.830 --> 01:21:29.780
of the Hundred Years' War.

01:21:29.780 --> 01:21:31.490
From a practical standpoint,

01:21:31.490 --> 01:21:35.630
it greatly bolstered Henry V's claim to the French throne.

01:21:35.630 --> 01:21:38.930
It directly led to infighting within the French court,

01:21:38.930 --> 01:21:42.890
and by 1420, the Treaty of Troyes was signed,

01:21:42.890 --> 01:21:46.850
acknowledging Henry as regent and heir to the French throne.

01:21:46.850 --> 01:21:49.820
By now, Henry had regained control of Normandy,

01:21:49.820 --> 01:21:52.130
was allied with the Duchy of Burgundy,

01:21:52.130 --> 01:21:55.610
and had received support from King Sigismund of Hungary

01:21:55.610 --> 01:21:57.800
who signed the Treaty of Canterbury,

01:21:57.800 --> 01:22:00.800
acknowledging the English claim to the throne.

01:22:00.800 --> 01:22:02.360
Unification of the kingdoms

01:22:02.360 --> 01:22:05.870
of England and France seemed inevitable.

01:22:05.870 --> 01:22:09.830
It was Henry's intention that after unifying the two crowns

01:22:09.830 --> 01:22:11.840
he would embark on a crusade.

01:22:11.840 --> 01:22:16.310
However, he died just a few years later in 1422,

01:22:16.310 --> 01:22:19.043
passing the throne onto his son, Henry VI.

01:22:19.880 --> 01:22:22.190
While Henry V's reign was short,

01:22:22.190 --> 01:22:25.430
it transformed England into a powerful player

01:22:25.430 --> 01:22:27.350
in European politics

01:22:27.350 --> 01:22:30.860
and forged in her a new national identity.

01:22:30.860 --> 01:22:34.040
England once again had a land on the continent,

01:22:34.040 --> 01:22:37.910
and under King Henry, England reached its territorial peak

01:22:37.910 --> 01:22:39.690
in mainland Europe.

01:22:39.690 --> 01:22:43.520
(suspenseful music)

01:22:43.520 --> 01:22:46.100
Henry VI was crowned at Westminster Abbey

01:22:46.100 --> 01:22:49.100
on the 1st of September, 1422.

01:22:49.100 --> 01:22:51.470
Young kings were nothing new in the realm,

01:22:51.470 --> 01:22:55.160
but Henry VI broke every English record,

01:22:55.160 --> 01:22:58.730
ascending to the throne at just nine months old

01:22:58.730 --> 01:23:02.060
and becoming the youngest ever king of England.

01:23:02.060 --> 01:23:05.060
Still breastfeeding, the burden of administration

01:23:05.060 --> 01:23:08.120
quickly fell to regents who ruled England together.

01:23:08.120 --> 01:23:11.000
Just a few months after his coronation in England,

01:23:11.000 --> 01:23:13.730
the baby King Henry traveled to France

01:23:13.730 --> 01:23:17.000
and was crowned king of France at Notre-Dame Cathedral

01:23:17.000 --> 01:23:19.100
in accordance with the Treaty of Troyes

01:23:19.100 --> 01:23:22.190
his father had signed just a few years earlier.

01:23:22.190 --> 01:23:25.820
This made King Henry VI the only English king

01:23:25.820 --> 01:23:30.350
to also be crowned king of France in French territory.

01:23:30.350 --> 01:23:32.090
While he waited to come of age,

01:23:32.090 --> 01:23:35.330
Henry's mother, Catherine, remarried to Owen Tudor

01:23:35.330 --> 01:23:38.390
and had two sons, Edmund and Jasper.

01:23:38.390 --> 01:23:41.480
Henry gave his half-brothers earldoms in Normandy,

01:23:41.480 --> 01:23:44.510
and their influence would later have a huge impact

01:23:44.510 --> 01:23:45.740
on English history.

01:23:45.740 --> 01:23:47.720
By the time he reached 16,

01:23:47.720 --> 01:23:51.110
Henry had resumed full authoritative control over England.

01:23:51.110 --> 01:23:53.810
However, it came at a bad time.

01:23:53.810 --> 01:23:56.300
It was the beginning of the Great Slump,

01:23:56.300 --> 01:23:58.070
a period of economic decline

01:23:58.070 --> 01:24:00.560
that would last for the next 50 years

01:24:00.560 --> 01:24:03.050
and weaken the crown's power in the realm.

01:24:03.050 --> 01:24:05.030
Things were only further complicated

01:24:05.030 --> 01:24:07.760
by the king's problematic personality.

01:24:07.760 --> 01:24:09.770
Described as shy, passive,

01:24:09.770 --> 01:24:12.710
and utterly opposed to conflict and violence,

01:24:12.710 --> 01:24:15.380
Henry VI was nothing like his father,

01:24:15.380 --> 01:24:17.780
and these traits were undesirable of a king

01:24:17.780 --> 01:24:21.320
during the medieval times and made him appear weak in court.

01:24:21.320 --> 01:24:23.630
Had he been an able administrator,

01:24:23.630 --> 01:24:26.270
he might have salvaged some respect,

01:24:26.270 --> 01:24:29.090
but Henry would soon prove to be unreliable

01:24:29.090 --> 01:24:31.310
in a totally different way.

01:24:31.310 --> 01:24:35.180
The king was prone to debilitating bouts of madness

01:24:35.180 --> 01:24:37.700
that forced administrative decision making

01:24:37.700 --> 01:24:39.719
back into the hands of regents.

01:24:39.719 --> 01:24:43.970
This made England unstable and weakened royal authority.

01:24:43.970 --> 01:24:47.540
It wasn't long before England declined into anarchy

01:24:47.540 --> 01:24:50.480
and lawlessness, disaffected noble's sense

01:24:50.480 --> 01:24:53.660
that the crown was weak and capitalized on this.

01:24:53.660 --> 01:24:56.870
Quarreling with one another and amassing private armies

01:24:56.870 --> 01:24:58.790
to fight for local supremacy,

01:24:58.790 --> 01:25:01.340
the king would intermittently resume control,

01:25:01.340 --> 01:25:04.100
but with each bout of madness that afflicted him,

01:25:04.100 --> 01:25:06.500
his grip on the realm weakened.

01:25:06.500 --> 01:25:09.380
To make matters worse, the One Hundred Years' War

01:25:09.380 --> 01:25:12.500
that had now been raging for five generations

01:25:12.500 --> 01:25:16.190
would sputter to its end under Henry's watch.

01:25:16.190 --> 01:25:18.920
England had seen many successes and victories

01:25:18.920 --> 01:25:21.470
during its time, but by its conclusion,

01:25:21.470 --> 01:25:24.890
Henry had lost all of his father's lands in France,

01:25:24.890 --> 01:25:27.470
retaining only the port city of Calais,

01:25:27.470 --> 01:25:30.110
further adding to his image of a weak king.

01:25:30.110 --> 01:25:32.750
With his kingdom fracturing around him,

01:25:32.750 --> 01:25:35.060
it wasn't long before England broke out

01:25:35.060 --> 01:25:37.130
into civil war again.

01:25:37.130 --> 01:25:39.440
One of the more powerful noble houses

01:25:39.440 --> 01:25:41.690
had been slowly amassing support,

01:25:41.690 --> 01:25:44.990
while Henry struggled to keep a grip on his sanity.

01:25:44.990 --> 01:25:48.440
House York, who claimed descendancy from Edward III,

01:25:48.440 --> 01:25:52.100
the Plantagenet king who ruled before Henry Bolingbroke

01:25:52.100 --> 01:25:55.580
took the throne by force less than 100 years ago,

01:25:55.580 --> 01:25:58.850
was preparing to make its move on the English throne.

01:25:58.850 --> 01:26:02.210
In 1460, tensions finally erupted

01:26:02.210 --> 01:26:05.210
and the War of the Roses had begun.

01:26:05.210 --> 01:26:07.910
So named for the red rose of Lancaster

01:26:07.910 --> 01:26:09.530
and the white rose of York,

01:26:09.530 --> 01:26:11.780
the Yorkist rebels scoured a quick

01:26:11.780 --> 01:26:15.140
and early victory at the Battle of Northampton

01:26:15.140 --> 01:26:17.720
on the 10th of July, 1460,

01:26:17.720 --> 01:26:21.230
capturing King Henry and making him a Yorkist prisoner.

01:26:21.230 --> 01:26:23.630
The queen, however, was able to escape,

01:26:23.630 --> 01:26:25.850
traveling through Wales and into Scotland

01:26:25.850 --> 01:26:27.020
where she sought refuge

01:26:27.020 --> 01:26:30.650
in the court of the Scottish queen regent, Mary of Guelders.

01:26:30.650 --> 01:26:32.930
After amassing an army of her own,

01:26:32.930 --> 01:26:34.730
she marched back into England

01:26:34.730 --> 01:26:37.340
seeking to rescue her imprisoned husband.

01:26:37.340 --> 01:26:40.940
After defeating the Yorkist army at the Battle of Wakefield,

01:26:40.940 --> 01:26:43.790
she marched her army south to St. Albans

01:26:43.790 --> 01:26:45.740
where the king was being held.

01:26:45.740 --> 01:26:48.200
There she engaged with the Earl of Warwick,

01:26:48.200 --> 01:26:51.410
defeating him and freeing the king from captivity.

01:26:51.410 --> 01:26:54.740
Henry's mental state at this time was so fractured

01:26:54.740 --> 01:26:56.930
that reports state that the king laughed

01:26:56.930 --> 01:26:59.660
and sing as the battle raged around him.

01:26:59.660 --> 01:27:02.720
The Lancastrian victories were short-lived, however,

01:27:02.720 --> 01:27:04.850
as Edward of York rallied his troops

01:27:04.850 --> 01:27:09.290
and met the royal army at the Battle of Towton in 1461.

01:27:09.290 --> 01:27:11.210
Under a thick blanket of snow,

01:27:11.210 --> 01:27:13.910
the Battle of Towton became the bloodiest battle

01:27:13.910 --> 01:27:16.370
that ever took place on English soil

01:27:16.370 --> 01:27:19.730
and resulted in a decisive Yorkist victory.

01:27:19.730 --> 01:27:22.520
Edward deposed Henry VI from the throne

01:27:22.520 --> 01:27:25.760
and hastily crowned himself king of England.

01:27:25.760 --> 01:27:28.100
Despite this, though, the war would continue

01:27:28.100 --> 01:27:29.780
as Henry fled the battle

01:27:29.780 --> 01:27:32.480
and became a fugitive in his own kingdom.

01:27:32.480 --> 01:27:34.482
Henry VI was eventually betrayed

01:27:34.482 --> 01:27:37.190
by the black monk of Addington

01:27:37.190 --> 01:27:39.590
and captured by Yorkist forces.

01:27:39.590 --> 01:27:43.520
The new King Edward decided to spare the mad king's life,

01:27:43.520 --> 01:27:46.223
instead putting him in the Tower of London.

01:27:47.805 --> 01:27:50.930
(light music)

01:27:50.930 --> 01:27:52.850
Edward of York was crowned Edward IV

01:27:52.850 --> 01:27:56.210
on the 28th of June, 1461

01:27:56.210 --> 01:27:59.420
following his victories against the Lancastrian army.

01:27:59.420 --> 01:28:01.370
As a usurper, the new king

01:28:01.370 --> 01:28:04.760
desperately needed parliamentary support to back his claim,

01:28:04.760 --> 01:28:06.410
but many of the lords in England

01:28:06.410 --> 01:28:08.570
still supported the old King Henry

01:28:08.570 --> 01:28:11.180
and chose to stay neutral during the conflict.

01:28:11.180 --> 01:28:13.340
This forced Edward to rely heavily

01:28:13.340 --> 01:28:15.380
on a small group of noblemen,

01:28:15.380 --> 01:28:17.840
mainly Richard Neville, Earl of Warwick.

01:28:17.840 --> 01:28:20.240
This over-reliance would directly lead

01:28:20.240 --> 01:28:24.110
to King Edward IV losing his grip on the English crown.

01:28:24.110 --> 01:28:27.920
Warwick had advised the king to marry either Anne of France

01:28:27.920 --> 01:28:32.270
or Bona of Savoy to strengthen England's ties with France

01:28:32.270 --> 01:28:35.300
and effectively outmaneuver the Duchy of Burgundy,

01:28:35.300 --> 01:28:36.770
which had been growing in power

01:28:36.770 --> 01:28:39.860
and influence in Europe over the last decade.

01:28:39.860 --> 01:28:42.740
Edward, however, had other ideas.

01:28:42.740 --> 01:28:44.870
He married Elizabeth Woodville,

01:28:44.870 --> 01:28:48.500
a woman of considerably lower social class than the king

01:28:48.500 --> 01:28:50.240
and a widow, but someone

01:28:50.240 --> 01:28:54.410
who historians claim was enchanting nonetheless.

01:28:54.410 --> 01:28:58.670
This enraged Warwick who began to seek allies elsewhere.

01:28:58.670 --> 01:29:03.670
In 1467, King Edward dealt Warwick another humiliating blow,

01:29:03.950 --> 01:29:07.430
dismissing his brother from his position as lord chancellor.

01:29:07.430 --> 01:29:09.980
By now, though, Warwick had amassed enough support

01:29:09.980 --> 01:29:12.290
to challenge the unpopular king.

01:29:12.290 --> 01:29:14.210
He traveled to London with an army

01:29:14.210 --> 01:29:17.570
and intended to remove the evil councilors

01:29:17.570 --> 01:29:20.150
that had taken hold of the English government.

01:29:20.150 --> 01:29:22.370
With the king preoccupied in the north,

01:29:22.370 --> 01:29:25.940
Neville's army was easily able to defeat the royal troops

01:29:25.940 --> 01:29:29.090
at Edgecote Moor in 1469.

01:29:29.090 --> 01:29:31.490
The king's father-in-law, Richard Woodville,

01:29:31.490 --> 01:29:33.710
alongside his youngest son, Richard,

01:29:33.710 --> 01:29:36.950
were captured and executed at Kenilworth.

01:29:36.950 --> 01:29:39.110
However, it quickly became apparent

01:29:39.110 --> 01:29:42.530
that Warwick had little support in the capital, and Edward,

01:29:42.530 --> 01:29:45.620
who had been captured and imprisoned at Middleham Castle,

01:29:45.620 --> 01:29:48.590
was released and allowed to resume the throne.

01:29:48.590 --> 01:29:51.950
What followed was a period of tense stability.

01:29:51.950 --> 01:29:54.500
Warwick was ousted from Edward's courts

01:29:54.500 --> 01:29:56.420
and decided on traveling to France

01:29:56.420 --> 01:29:58.400
where he sought support from the continent

01:29:58.400 --> 01:30:01.130
and vowed to restore Henry VI,

01:30:01.130 --> 01:30:04.297
who was currently still alive in the Tower of London

01:30:04.297 --> 01:30:06.590
to the English throne.

01:30:06.590 --> 01:30:09.770
Yorkist rule had become increasingly unpopular,

01:30:09.770 --> 01:30:13.910
and Warwick was able to gather an army of 30,000 men

01:30:13.910 --> 01:30:15.800
in support of his cause.

01:30:15.800 --> 01:30:19.760
Landing back in England on the 9th of September, 1470,

01:30:19.760 --> 01:30:23.090
King Edward was a no match for Warwick's army,

01:30:23.090 --> 01:30:26.000
and he fled to Bruges to avoid capture.

01:30:26.000 --> 01:30:29.690
Warwick restored King Henry VI to the throne,

01:30:29.690 --> 01:30:31.880
but with this, the same problems

01:30:31.880 --> 01:30:35.270
that had plagued the mad king's reign simply returned,

01:30:35.270 --> 01:30:38.930
mental instability meant a lack of central leadership,

01:30:38.930 --> 01:30:42.170
and caused the nobility to fight amongst itself for power,

01:30:42.170 --> 01:30:44.240
like it had previously.

01:30:44.240 --> 01:30:46.580
Edward, meanwhile, returned to England

01:30:46.580 --> 01:30:49.550
aided by powerful Flemish merchants

01:30:49.550 --> 01:30:51.800
and immediately sought support in York.

01:30:51.800 --> 01:30:54.680
Marching through the realm, he slowly gathered an army

01:30:54.680 --> 01:30:56.780
and turned his attention to the capital.

01:30:56.780 --> 01:30:58.430
He entered London unopposed

01:30:58.430 --> 01:31:02.000
and imprisoned Henry VI once again.

01:31:02.000 --> 01:31:05.990
Warwick was killed at the Battle of Barnet in 1471,

01:31:05.990 --> 01:31:08.870
while a second Lancastrian army was defeated

01:31:08.870 --> 01:31:11.840
at the Battle of Tewkesbury only a month later.

01:31:11.840 --> 01:31:14.600
Henry's only son, Edward of Westminster,

01:31:14.600 --> 01:31:16.250
died on the battlefield,

01:31:16.250 --> 01:31:19.550
while Henry himself passed away less than a year later.

01:31:19.550 --> 01:31:22.250
With the old King and his heir dead,

01:31:22.250 --> 01:31:25.610
King Edward had hoped his throne would now be secure,

01:31:25.610 --> 01:31:28.910
but the realm was in disarray, plagued by instability

01:31:28.910 --> 01:31:31.760
and infighting after years of civil war.

01:31:31.760 --> 01:31:34.640
King Edward was able to maintain his grip on power,

01:31:34.640 --> 01:31:38.420
but toward the end of his reign, he became increasingly ill

01:31:38.420 --> 01:31:41.720
and died on the 9th of April, 1483.

01:31:41.720 --> 01:31:46.400
His son, Edward V, was to take over as King of England,

01:31:46.400 --> 01:31:48.260
but as Edward was only little,

01:31:48.260 --> 01:31:51.590
the king named his brother, Richard, Duke of Gloucester,

01:31:51.590 --> 01:31:55.460
as lord protector and regent while Edward came of age.

01:31:55.460 --> 01:31:57.530
But Edward would never be crowned

01:31:57.530 --> 01:32:00.830
and England would soon discover that the new lord protector

01:32:00.830 --> 01:32:04.643
had little intention of vacating his position on the throne.

01:32:06.068 --> 01:32:09.380
(foreboding music)

01:32:09.380 --> 01:32:12.260
Richard took over as lord protector of the realm

01:32:12.260 --> 01:32:16.010
immediately after the death of his brother, King Edward IV.

01:32:16.010 --> 01:32:18.590
Royal records do show that plans were made

01:32:18.590 --> 01:32:20.660
for Edward the V's coronation,

01:32:20.660 --> 01:32:23.180
but there is great debate amongst scholars

01:32:23.180 --> 01:32:25.610
as to how much of this was genuine

01:32:25.610 --> 01:32:28.850
or merely a show put on by the new lord protector

01:32:28.850 --> 01:32:31.550
to appease the old king's supporters.

01:32:31.550 --> 01:32:34.610
Richard's reputation as a ruthless power grabber

01:32:34.610 --> 01:32:36.320
initially stems from the speed

01:32:36.320 --> 01:32:38.990
with which he took control of the English crown.

01:32:38.990 --> 01:32:41.630
Shortly after his appointment as lord protector,

01:32:41.630 --> 01:32:45.500
he brutally put down a supposed plot against his life

01:32:45.500 --> 01:32:49.370
that involved the new king's uncles, Anthony Woodville.

01:32:49.370 --> 01:32:51.020
Upon the queen's request,

01:32:51.020 --> 01:32:54.170
Richard and Anthony Woodville were to meet at Northampton

01:32:54.170 --> 01:32:57.050
and accompany the young Edward down to the capital,

01:32:57.050 --> 01:32:58.280
providing him safety

01:32:58.280 --> 01:33:00.770
and legitimacy as he ascended the throne.

01:33:00.770 --> 01:33:02.390
But while the young king waited

01:33:02.390 --> 01:33:05.930
for the arrival of his uncles, Richard got to work.

01:33:05.930 --> 01:33:09.020
He had Anthony Woodville and his associates arrested

01:33:09.020 --> 01:33:11.420
and sent to Pontefract Castle,

01:33:11.420 --> 01:33:14.960
where the men were tried and executed for an alleged plot

01:33:14.960 --> 01:33:17.600
against the new lord protector's life.

01:33:17.600 --> 01:33:19.490
Richard quickly notified his nephew

01:33:19.490 --> 01:33:23.150
of the treasonous actions of his uncle and reassured the boy

01:33:23.150 --> 01:33:25.610
that they had been dealt with accordingly.

01:33:25.610 --> 01:33:27.620
He alone led Edward into London

01:33:27.620 --> 01:33:29.990
and transferred the boy to the royal apartments

01:33:29.990 --> 01:33:31.550
in the Tower of London,

01:33:31.550 --> 01:33:35.150
as was customary for any king awaiting his coronation,

01:33:35.150 --> 01:33:38.420
but Richard's plan was only just beginning.

01:33:38.420 --> 01:33:41.240
Upon hearing the news of her brother's demise,

01:33:41.240 --> 01:33:43.640
the dowager queen fled to the capital

01:33:43.640 --> 01:33:44.990
and sought support from those

01:33:44.990 --> 01:33:46.730
who had been loyal to her husband,

01:33:46.730 --> 01:33:49.070
but Richard had beaten her to it.

01:33:49.070 --> 01:33:50.810
He accused those close to the queen

01:33:50.810 --> 01:33:53.420
of being complicit in the plot against his life

01:33:53.420 --> 01:33:56.780
and had them executed within days of the trial,

01:33:56.780 --> 01:33:59.510
with the Woodville's power base in tatters.

01:33:59.510 --> 01:34:02.477
Richard had only one obstacle in between himself

01:34:02.477 --> 01:34:06.410
and the English throne, the princes in the tower.

01:34:06.410 --> 01:34:09.350
As luck would have it, the lord protector was informed

01:34:09.350 --> 01:34:11.450
by the bishop of Bath and Wells

01:34:11.450 --> 01:34:14.480
that King Edward IV's marriage to Elizabeth Woodville

01:34:14.480 --> 01:34:16.400
was in fact invalid

01:34:16.400 --> 01:34:18.650
due to King Edward still having been married

01:34:18.650 --> 01:34:22.400
to Eleanor Butler at the time of his union with Woodville.

01:34:22.400 --> 01:34:24.320
This meant that Edward and Richard,

01:34:24.320 --> 01:34:25.970
the princes in the tower,

01:34:25.970 --> 01:34:29.270
were illegitimate and could not rule.

01:34:29.270 --> 01:34:32.480
A sermon was preached on the steps of St. Paul's Cathedral

01:34:32.480 --> 01:34:34.700
on the day of the new king's coronation,

01:34:34.700 --> 01:34:37.850
declaring Edward V to be a bastard

01:34:37.850 --> 01:34:39.530
and asserting that Richard III

01:34:39.530 --> 01:34:42.620
was the rightful heir to the English throne.

01:34:42.620 --> 01:34:45.110
Shortly after this, the citizens of London

01:34:45.110 --> 01:34:48.260
and its nobility converged and drew up a petition

01:34:48.260 --> 01:34:52.310
asking Richard to assume direct control of the throne.

01:34:52.310 --> 01:34:56.240
On the 6th of July, 1483, Lord Protector Richard

01:34:56.240 --> 01:34:59.720
was crowned Richard III, King of England.

01:34:59.720 --> 01:35:01.520
Power was his.

01:35:01.520 --> 01:35:03.230
That same summer, the princes

01:35:03.230 --> 01:35:05.300
who had been quietly living in the Tower,

01:35:05.300 --> 01:35:06.920
silently disappeared.

01:35:06.920 --> 01:35:09.380
There are many theories as to what happened,

01:35:09.380 --> 01:35:11.840
from being murdered by Richard himself

01:35:11.840 --> 01:35:14.750
to fleeing to Europe under the cover of darkness,

01:35:14.750 --> 01:35:17.960
but the mystery of the Princes in the Tower still remains

01:35:17.960 --> 01:35:22.040
one of the greatest unsolved questions in English history.

01:35:22.040 --> 01:35:23.450
But despite the ease

01:35:23.450 --> 01:35:25.670
with which Richard had assumed the throne,

01:35:25.670 --> 01:35:28.760
his power base was still fragile, and it wasn't long

01:35:28.760 --> 01:35:31.790
before he was faced with his first major threat,

01:35:31.790 --> 01:35:33.980
the Buckingham Rebellion.

01:35:33.980 --> 01:35:35.559
Led by the earl of Buckingham

01:35:35.559 --> 01:35:37.880
and a number of disaffected nobility

01:35:37.880 --> 01:35:41.420
who had been fiercely loyal to the old King Edward IV,

01:35:41.420 --> 01:35:45.200
they quietly planned to overthrow the new King Richard.

01:35:45.200 --> 01:35:48.650
They saw the new regime for what it was, a power grab,

01:35:48.650 --> 01:35:50.330
and they saw to give the crown back

01:35:50.330 --> 01:35:54.290
to the young Prince Edward currently in the Tower of London.

01:35:54.290 --> 01:35:56.330
But when rumors of Prince Edward's death

01:35:56.330 --> 01:35:58.580
began to circulate throughout the realm,

01:35:58.580 --> 01:36:00.800
Buckingham had to change his plan.

01:36:00.800 --> 01:36:03.110
Luckily for him, there was another candidate

01:36:03.110 --> 01:36:07.640
ready and willing just to cross the channel, Henry Tudor.

01:36:07.640 --> 01:36:10.370
As the son of Lady Margaret Beaufort,

01:36:10.370 --> 01:36:13.070
herself a ascendant of King Edward III,

01:36:13.070 --> 01:36:15.800
Henry had a legal claim to the English throne,

01:36:15.800 --> 01:36:18.290
regardless of how weak it actually was.

01:36:18.290 --> 01:36:20.540
Buckingham gathered his troops in Wales,

01:36:20.540 --> 01:36:23.240
while Henry Tudor, who had been exiled to France,

01:36:23.240 --> 01:36:25.220
gathered an army on the continent.

01:36:25.220 --> 01:36:28.100
However, just like it had in 1066,

01:36:28.100 --> 01:36:30.710
bad weather once again played an important part

01:36:30.710 --> 01:36:32.060
in the fate of England.

01:36:32.060 --> 01:36:34.190
As Henry and his ships were delayed

01:36:34.190 --> 01:36:37.280
crossing the English Channel by a fierce storm,

01:36:37.280 --> 01:36:38.720
most of his fleet was forced

01:36:38.720 --> 01:36:41.750
to turn back to their ports in Normandy and Calais,

01:36:41.750 --> 01:36:43.220
while Henry himself anchored

01:36:43.220 --> 01:36:44.960
at Plymouth to wait out the gale.

01:36:44.960 --> 01:36:48.470
Buckingham's army was troubled by the same storm on land,

01:36:48.470 --> 01:36:51.680
and when Richard's troops arrived to face the rebel army,

01:36:51.680 --> 01:36:54.110
many of Buckingham's men deserted,

01:36:54.110 --> 01:36:56.000
leaving the earl to be captured,

01:36:56.000 --> 01:36:59.000
tried, and beheaded in Salisbury.

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:02.450
When Henry heard of Buckingham's fate, he fled to Paris,

01:37:02.450 --> 01:37:04.010
where the French regent supplied him

01:37:04.010 --> 01:37:08.990
with a fresh army with which to invade a year later in 1485.

01:37:08.990 --> 01:37:12.350
On the 22nd of August, the armies of Henry Tudor

01:37:12.350 --> 01:37:15.410
and King Richard III met at Bosworth Field

01:37:15.410 --> 01:37:17.240
near the city of Leicester.

01:37:17.240 --> 01:37:19.970
Accounts of the battle claim that the king's forces

01:37:19.970 --> 01:37:22.520
heavily outnumbered that of the Tudor rebel.

01:37:22.520 --> 01:37:25.970
But as Richard was about to discover, who he had with him

01:37:25.970 --> 01:37:28.430
was about to become far more important

01:37:28.430 --> 01:37:30.470
than how many he had with him.

01:37:30.470 --> 01:37:33.890
King Richard divided his army into three main units.

01:37:33.890 --> 01:37:36.530
One section would be led by the duke of Norfolk,

01:37:36.530 --> 01:37:38.840
the other by the earl of Northumberland,

01:37:38.840 --> 01:37:40.910
while Richard himself would take control

01:37:40.910 --> 01:37:42.500
of the bulk of the army.

01:37:42.500 --> 01:37:44.180
The battle began with King Richard

01:37:44.180 --> 01:37:47.060
attacking Henry Tudor's forces head on.

01:37:47.060 --> 01:37:48.860
The melee was brutal,

01:37:48.860 --> 01:37:51.530
and fierce, hand-to-hand combat broke out,

01:37:51.530 --> 01:37:53.600
but Henry's army was well-drilled

01:37:53.600 --> 01:37:55.640
and led by the earl of Oxford,

01:37:55.640 --> 01:37:58.940
an incredibly competent military strategist.

01:37:58.940 --> 01:38:01.190
Despite a numerical disadvantage,

01:38:01.190 --> 01:38:04.040
the earl was able to inflict serious casualties

01:38:04.040 --> 01:38:05.090
on the royal army,

01:38:05.090 --> 01:38:07.580
causing some of the duke of Norfolk's troops

01:38:07.580 --> 01:38:08.840
to flee the battle.

01:38:08.840 --> 01:38:12.020
It was at this moment that Richard turned to Northumberland

01:38:12.020 --> 01:38:15.143
and signaled for the earl to reinforce his lines,

01:38:15.143 --> 01:38:17.720
but Northumberland refused.

01:38:17.720 --> 01:38:20.030
Meanwhile on a hill overlooking the battle,

01:38:20.030 --> 01:38:23.570
Sir William Stanley, son of the earl of Stanley,

01:38:23.570 --> 01:38:24.980
had arrived with his army.

01:38:24.980 --> 01:38:27.710
He had been loyal to Richard in the Yorkist regime

01:38:27.710 --> 01:38:31.310
since the start of the War of Roses 30 years ago.

01:38:31.310 --> 01:38:34.310
Stanley had been present at the Battle of Tewkesbury

01:38:34.310 --> 01:38:36.500
when Edward IV took the throne,

01:38:36.500 --> 01:38:38.630
and Richard had even rewarded him

01:38:38.630 --> 01:38:42.080
after his ascension to power with land in North Wales.

01:38:42.080 --> 01:38:43.785
But this meant little to Stanley

01:38:43.785 --> 01:38:46.250
who held off on joining either side

01:38:46.250 --> 01:38:48.440
until a clear winner had emerged.

01:38:48.440 --> 01:38:51.230
With Northumberland refusing to come to his aid,

01:38:51.230 --> 01:38:54.590
Richard feared that he might lose control of his army soon.

01:38:54.590 --> 01:38:57.050
So he mounted a risky attack,

01:38:57.050 --> 01:38:59.840
intending to charge right into Henry's forces,

01:38:59.840 --> 01:39:02.240
and kill the young pretender himself,

01:39:02.240 --> 01:39:04.820
ending the battle and securing a victory.

01:39:04.820 --> 01:39:07.760
But seeing the king separated from his main army,

01:39:07.760 --> 01:39:09.020
Stanley made a decision

01:39:09.020 --> 01:39:12.170
that changed the course of English history.

01:39:12.170 --> 01:39:14.390
He joined on the side of Henry Tudor,

01:39:14.390 --> 01:39:16.850
surrounding King Richard and his men

01:39:16.850 --> 01:39:19.407
and removing the king from his horse.

01:39:19.407 --> 01:39:23.390
"My horse, my horse, a kingdom for my horse,"

01:39:23.390 --> 01:39:26.150
the king shouted as he fought bravely surrounded

01:39:26.150 --> 01:39:28.280
by swarms of his enemies.

01:39:28.280 --> 01:39:30.980
King Richard reportedly came with an a swords length

01:39:30.980 --> 01:39:34.070
of Henry Tudor before finally being overwhelmed

01:39:34.070 --> 01:39:35.720
by Stanley and his men.

01:39:35.720 --> 01:39:37.940
He was killed where he stood.

01:39:37.940 --> 01:39:40.430
The Battle of Bosworth Field was over

01:39:40.430 --> 01:39:43.460
and the reign of Richard III had ended.

01:39:43.460 --> 01:39:46.970
He would be the last English king to die in battle.

01:39:46.970 --> 01:39:48.710
Myth has it that the English crown

01:39:48.710 --> 01:39:51.410
was found propped up against a bush nearby.

01:39:51.410 --> 01:39:54.230
It was taken and placed on Henry Tudor's head

01:39:54.230 --> 01:39:56.570
right there on the battlefield.

01:39:56.570 --> 01:39:59.240
Richard's body was buried without ceremony

01:39:59.240 --> 01:40:01.220
in a nearby abbey in Leicester.

01:40:01.220 --> 01:40:04.940
His death marked the official end of the War of Roses,

01:40:04.940 --> 01:40:08.660
and Richard III became the last Plantagenet king

01:40:08.660 --> 01:40:10.313
to rule over the island.

01:40:12.143 --> 01:40:15.110
(light music)

01:40:15.110 --> 01:40:17.990
After over three decades of civil war,

01:40:17.990 --> 01:40:19.400
England had a new king.

01:40:19.400 --> 01:40:23.570
Henry Tudor was crowned Henry VII at Westminster Abbey

01:40:23.570 --> 01:40:27.140
on the 30th of October, 1485.

01:40:27.140 --> 01:40:28.790
His ascension marks the beginning

01:40:28.790 --> 01:40:31.730
of the early modern period of English history.

01:40:31.730 --> 01:40:33.650
As a king by right of conquest,

01:40:33.650 --> 01:40:35.450
Henry faced the difficult challenge

01:40:35.450 --> 01:40:37.100
of consolidating his power

01:40:37.100 --> 01:40:39.770
and securing his position on the throne.

01:40:39.770 --> 01:40:42.320
He did this by marrying Elizabeth of York,

01:40:42.320 --> 01:40:43.940
daughter of Edward IV,

01:40:43.940 --> 01:40:46.189
and uniting the warring houses of Lancaster

01:40:46.189 --> 01:40:50.480
and York together to form the new house, Tudor.

01:40:50.480 --> 01:40:52.940
He punished those loyal to the old king

01:40:52.940 --> 01:40:55.730
and rewarded any man who swore fealty to him,

01:40:55.730 --> 01:40:58.190
promising not to confiscate their lands

01:40:58.190 --> 01:41:00.260
or remove their royal titles.

01:41:00.260 --> 01:41:02.450
Many welcome the change in leadership

01:41:02.450 --> 01:41:05.210
and pledged their support to the Tudor king.

01:41:05.210 --> 01:41:08.090
Once his position as ruler was more secure,

01:41:08.090 --> 01:41:11.390
he turned his attention to repairing the kingdom he had won,

01:41:11.390 --> 01:41:14.810
and England was in serious need of repair.

01:41:14.810 --> 01:41:18.020
Decades of civil war and two years patience

01:41:18.020 --> 01:41:20.270
in the last three years had left the realm

01:41:20.270 --> 01:41:24.140
in serious administrative and financial disarray.

01:41:24.140 --> 01:41:26.180
But thankfully, King Henry proved

01:41:26.180 --> 01:41:27.860
to be the right man for the job.

01:41:27.860 --> 01:41:31.850
The new king believed in something called royal absolutism,

01:41:31.850 --> 01:41:33.950
essentially the divine right of kings

01:41:33.950 --> 01:41:35.570
to rule as they saw fit

01:41:35.570 --> 01:41:39.350
without having to answer to nobility, church, or parliament.

01:41:39.350 --> 01:41:42.650
This led Henry to take a much more hands-on approach

01:41:42.650 --> 01:41:44.720
to the everyday running of his kingdom.

01:41:44.720 --> 01:41:47.893
He was a stickler for details, and quickly proved himself

01:41:47.893 --> 01:41:51.680
to be a highly capable administrator and diplomat.

01:41:51.680 --> 01:41:54.234
Up first was the crown's finances.

01:41:54.234 --> 01:41:57.410
Civil wars are never great for the treasury,

01:41:57.410 --> 01:42:00.800
and after 30 years of fighting on top of the Great Slump

01:42:00.800 --> 01:42:03.680
that it only ended five years before his ascension,

01:42:03.680 --> 01:42:07.010
England's financial situation was in tatters.

01:42:07.010 --> 01:42:09.050
He revitalized the Exchequer

01:42:09.050 --> 01:42:11.030
and improved tax collection in the realm

01:42:11.030 --> 01:42:13.089
by keeping the same financial advisors

01:42:13.089 --> 01:42:14.960
throughout his entire reign.

01:42:14.960 --> 01:42:16.970
This gave the Office of the Exchequer

01:42:16.970 --> 01:42:19.070
a strong sense of stability

01:42:19.070 --> 01:42:21.620
and allowed the men to refine their processes.

01:42:21.620 --> 01:42:25.100
He was also far less extravagant than his predecessors,

01:42:25.100 --> 01:42:26.977
choosing to be fiscally responsible

01:42:26.977 --> 01:42:30.770
instead of spending lavishly on feasts and events.

01:42:30.770 --> 01:42:34.250
He introduced the Acts of Resumption in 1486,

01:42:34.250 --> 01:42:37.010
which gave him access to all the lands given away

01:42:37.010 --> 01:42:38.780
during the War of the Roses,

01:42:38.780 --> 01:42:41.750
and placed them directly under the crown's control,

01:42:41.750 --> 01:42:44.360
greatly improving his financial situation.

01:42:44.360 --> 01:42:47.120
But perhaps his greatest economic achievement

01:42:47.120 --> 01:42:51.530
was the Magnus Intercursus or the Great Agreement.

01:42:51.530 --> 01:42:54.350
As you might remember, a few generations ago,

01:42:54.350 --> 01:42:56.960
England had switched from majority crop farming

01:42:56.960 --> 01:42:58.070
to sheep tending.

01:42:58.070 --> 01:43:01.610
Now, centuries later, the English wool trade had exploded

01:43:01.610 --> 01:43:05.120
and become the island's main economic export into Europe.

01:43:05.120 --> 01:43:07.400
But that export was directly threatened

01:43:07.400 --> 01:43:10.580
when Margaret of Burgundy supported Perkin Warbeck,

01:43:10.580 --> 01:43:12.260
a pretender to the throne

01:43:12.260 --> 01:43:14.390
and one of the first major rebellions

01:43:14.390 --> 01:43:17.120
Henry was forced to deal with during his reign.

01:43:17.120 --> 01:43:19.730
The king enacted a trade embargo with Burgundy,

01:43:19.730 --> 01:43:21.410
cutting off their supply of wool

01:43:21.410 --> 01:43:24.170
and severely limiting the amount of English trade

01:43:24.170 --> 01:43:25.940
that was going into the continent.

01:43:25.940 --> 01:43:28.340
But wool was an important material.

01:43:28.340 --> 01:43:31.790
An English wool was prized from Paris to Rome,

01:43:31.790 --> 01:43:34.010
so it wasn't long before the two nations

01:43:34.010 --> 01:43:36.170
began talks of negotiation.

01:43:36.170 --> 01:43:38.930
What emerged was the Magnus Intercursus,

01:43:38.930 --> 01:43:42.470
a treaty which reopened trade between the two countries,

01:43:42.470 --> 01:43:45.747
but heavily favored England as it removed the taxation

01:43:45.747 --> 01:43:48.290
of English goods going into Europe,

01:43:48.290 --> 01:43:51.050
making the island rich in the process.

01:43:51.050 --> 01:43:52.910
And speaking of pretenders,

01:43:52.910 --> 01:43:56.360
Henry had two major uprisings during his reign.

01:43:56.360 --> 01:43:58.700
The first was the Lambert Simnel,

01:43:58.700 --> 01:44:01.370
a young boy who had been somewhat forced into pretending

01:44:01.370 --> 01:44:04.220
to be one of the young princes in the tower.

01:44:04.220 --> 01:44:05.990
After his army was defeated,

01:44:05.990 --> 01:44:09.500
King Henry showed great mercy in sparing the boy's life,

01:44:09.500 --> 01:44:11.390
giving him a job in his kitchens

01:44:11.390 --> 01:44:13.640
for the remainder of his existence.

01:44:13.640 --> 01:44:17.270
The next was Perkin Warbeck, a more serious threat

01:44:17.270 --> 01:44:19.640
as he gained support from Margaret of Burgundy

01:44:19.640 --> 01:44:22.760
and gathered an invasion force to invade the island.

01:44:22.760 --> 01:44:26.390
Warbeck too was defeated, but unlike Lambert Simnel,

01:44:26.390 --> 01:44:29.060
he did not escape a gruesome death.

01:44:29.060 --> 01:44:31.730
He was hung alongside his supporters.

01:44:31.730 --> 01:44:34.160
In all, King Henry VII's reign

01:44:34.160 --> 01:44:37.550
was a remarkably peaceful and prosperous time.

01:44:37.550 --> 01:44:40.400
He was a fantastic and able administrator

01:44:40.400 --> 01:44:44.240
and ruled for a long 24 years where the crown's influence

01:44:44.240 --> 01:44:47.180
and control grew alongside her treasury.

01:44:47.180 --> 01:44:50.960
The realm welcomed the stability King Henry brought,

01:44:50.960 --> 01:44:52.100
and his legitimacy

01:44:52.100 --> 01:44:55.220
was never seriously questioned or challenged.

01:44:55.220 --> 01:44:57.500
But the later years of his reign were marked

01:44:57.500 --> 01:44:59.150
by personal tragedy.

01:44:59.150 --> 01:45:00.980
He lost his eldest son, Arthur,

01:45:00.980 --> 01:45:03.410
to the English sweating sickness,

01:45:03.410 --> 01:45:05.900
and was reportedly stricken with grief.

01:45:05.900 --> 01:45:07.940
The normally stoic and reserved king

01:45:07.940 --> 01:45:11.090
could apparently be heard sobbing at the loss of his son.

01:45:11.090 --> 01:45:14.150
A year later, he lost his wife, Queen Elizabeth,

01:45:14.150 --> 01:45:16.820
and reportedly locked himself away for weeks,

01:45:16.820 --> 01:45:18.290
speaking to no one.

01:45:18.290 --> 01:45:19.940
Many of his courtiers note

01:45:19.940 --> 01:45:22.250
that King Henry never truly recovered

01:45:22.250 --> 01:45:23.540
after the death of his wife.

01:45:23.540 --> 01:45:26.720
He died on the 21st of April, 1509,

01:45:26.720 --> 01:45:30.383
and was succeeded by his son, Henry, Duke of York.

01:45:32.089 --> 01:45:35.030
(gentle piano music)

01:45:35.030 --> 01:45:37.100
There is a strong argument to be made

01:45:37.100 --> 01:45:41.540
that there is no English king more famous than Henry VIII,

01:45:41.540 --> 01:45:43.670
an ironic sentiment when you consider

01:45:43.670 --> 01:45:46.310
he was never actually meant to be king.

01:45:46.310 --> 01:45:49.970
King Henry VII's eldest son was Arthur, Prince of Wales.

01:45:49.970 --> 01:45:54.290
Born in 1486, he spent his life training in the royal courts

01:45:54.290 --> 01:45:57.680
and being groomed to take over from his father before him.

01:45:57.680 --> 01:45:59.570
His younger brother, Henry, meanwhile,

01:45:59.570 --> 01:46:02.510
was raised as a prince with little responsibility.

01:46:02.510 --> 01:46:04.760
Hunting, drinking, and competing,

01:46:04.760 --> 01:46:07.610
these were the pursuits Henry occupied himself with

01:46:07.610 --> 01:46:10.160
during his childhood, and he was more than happy

01:46:10.160 --> 01:46:12.110
to watch his brother take the throne.

01:46:12.110 --> 01:46:14.900
At just 15 years old, Arthur was married

01:46:14.900 --> 01:46:16.430
to Catherine of Aragon,

01:46:16.430 --> 01:46:19.730
daughter of the powerful Catholic monarchy in Spain,

01:46:19.730 --> 01:46:21.770
uniting the two kingdoms as one.

01:46:21.770 --> 01:46:25.220
However, just six months after his marriage to Catherine,

01:46:25.220 --> 01:46:26.660
the newlyweds came down

01:46:26.660 --> 01:46:29.510
with a bad case of sweating sickness.

01:46:29.510 --> 01:46:33.110
Catherine survived, while Arthur unfortunately perished,

01:46:33.110 --> 01:46:36.170
leaving the throne to fall to his younger brother Henry.

01:46:36.170 --> 01:46:38.720
History has not been kind to Henry VIII,

01:46:38.720 --> 01:46:42.890
and the Tudor king is often remembered for two main things,

01:46:42.890 --> 01:46:46.880
his six wives and his break from the Catholic church.

01:46:46.880 --> 01:46:49.190
He is often portrayed as large,

01:46:49.190 --> 01:46:53.540
bordering on obese, rude, mad, and wholly uncultured,

01:46:53.540 --> 01:46:56.660
a stark contrast to how Henry was actually perceived

01:46:56.660 --> 01:46:58.220
during his life.

01:46:58.220 --> 01:47:01.100
He was a natural athlete, a talented musician,

01:47:01.100 --> 01:47:02.570
religious, and well-learned,

01:47:02.570 --> 01:47:04.700
traits which made the young King Henry

01:47:04.700 --> 01:47:06.590
extremely popular in court

01:47:06.590 --> 01:47:08.570
and to the other rulers of Europe.

01:47:08.570 --> 01:47:11.060
But while Henry may have impressed in court,

01:47:11.060 --> 01:47:13.999
he was not an able statesman by any means.

01:47:13.999 --> 01:47:16.730
He had zero interest in administration

01:47:16.730 --> 01:47:19.850
and was considerably less frugal than his father,

01:47:19.850 --> 01:47:21.950
which unsurprisingly resulted

01:47:21.950 --> 01:47:24.140
in the vastly filled treasuries

01:47:24.140 --> 01:47:27.080
being depleted of gold by the end of his reign.

01:47:27.080 --> 01:47:29.330
Henry had a council who listened to him

01:47:29.330 --> 01:47:31.190
due to his willingness to kill.

01:47:31.190 --> 01:47:33.140
The council fulfilled their duties.

01:47:33.140 --> 01:47:36.650
Sir Thomas More, a member of the council, served Henry.

01:47:36.650 --> 01:47:39.320
Though the two became very close friends.

01:47:39.320 --> 01:47:41.990
Seeking to unload the burden of administration,

01:47:41.990 --> 01:47:45.350
King Henry put Cardinal Wolsey in charge of England.

01:47:45.350 --> 01:47:47.600
The son of a Suffolk wool merchant,

01:47:47.600 --> 01:47:49.760
Wolsey was a shrewd diplomat

01:47:49.760 --> 01:47:51.830
and was able to keep England afloat,

01:47:51.830 --> 01:47:54.830
despite the king's best efforts to bankrupt her.

01:47:54.830 --> 01:47:57.290
Wolsey's rise through the ranks of the clergy

01:47:57.290 --> 01:48:00.500
was unparalleled, from bishop of London

01:48:00.500 --> 01:48:02.090
to archbishop of York,

01:48:02.090 --> 01:48:04.820
and then cardinal and lord chancellor of England,

01:48:04.820 --> 01:48:07.640
to finally papal legate himself.

01:48:07.640 --> 01:48:10.640
Wolsey was one of the most successful new men

01:48:10.640 --> 01:48:12.080
of his generation.

01:48:12.080 --> 01:48:15.710
There were even serious considerations to make Wolsey pope.

01:48:15.710 --> 01:48:17.990
Scholars believe that part of the reason Wolsey

01:48:17.990 --> 01:48:20.090
was eventually passed on for pope

01:48:20.090 --> 01:48:22.160
was because of the role England was playing

01:48:22.160 --> 01:48:23.570
during the Reformation.

01:48:23.570 --> 01:48:27.140
Europe as a whole was undergoing major religious upheaval,

01:48:27.140 --> 01:48:30.320
where many religious scholars and academic thinkers

01:48:30.320 --> 01:48:34.160
were challenging the established ideas of the church.

01:48:34.160 --> 01:48:36.230
It was called the Reformation,

01:48:36.230 --> 01:48:39.350
and many of these reformers called England their home.

01:48:39.350 --> 01:48:42.110
They believed the church had become corrupt.

01:48:42.110 --> 01:48:43.550
But it's important to note,

01:48:43.550 --> 01:48:45.800
King Henry's break from the Catholic church

01:48:45.800 --> 01:48:48.860
had nothing to do with his support for the Reformation.

01:48:48.860 --> 01:48:51.230
Henry was in fact a religious conservative,

01:48:51.230 --> 01:48:54.410
and his break from the Catholic church was wholly selfish

01:48:54.410 --> 01:48:56.660
and for personal gain only.

01:48:56.660 --> 01:48:59.090
You see, after the death of his brother,

01:48:59.090 --> 01:49:02.210
Henry had received special dispensation from the pope

01:49:02.210 --> 01:49:04.130
to marry his brother's widow,

01:49:04.130 --> 01:49:05.840
thanks to the fact that their marriage

01:49:05.840 --> 01:49:07.640
had never been consummated.

01:49:07.640 --> 01:49:10.820
For a long time, the pair were happily married,

01:49:10.820 --> 01:49:15.290
but as the years wore on, a problem soon became evident.

01:49:15.290 --> 01:49:18.200
Henry desperately wanted a male heir,

01:49:18.200 --> 01:49:22.070
and after 24 years of marriage to Catherine of Aragon,

01:49:22.070 --> 01:49:24.740
they had produced only one child, Mary.

01:49:24.740 --> 01:49:27.140
This led the king's eyes to wander,

01:49:27.140 --> 01:49:29.390
and they quickly landed on Anne Boleyn,

01:49:29.390 --> 01:49:31.310
one of the queen's ladies in waiting.

01:49:31.310 --> 01:49:34.010
Anne Boleyn refused Henry's advances

01:49:34.010 --> 01:49:35.990
and insisted that if he wanted her,

01:49:35.990 --> 01:49:37.530
he would need to marry her.

01:49:37.530 --> 01:49:41.390
Henry returned to his expert chancellor, Cardinal Wolsey.

01:49:41.390 --> 01:49:44.900
Wolsey had the unenviable task of asking the pope

01:49:44.900 --> 01:49:47.900
if he would null the king's marriage to Catherine.

01:49:47.900 --> 01:49:49.370
The Pope denied it.

01:49:49.370 --> 01:49:52.580
Henry was furious, and looking for someone to blame,

01:49:52.580 --> 01:49:56.720
he fired Wolsey from his post and accused him of treason.

01:49:56.720 --> 01:49:59.810
Wolsey was saved from a long and humiliating trial

01:49:59.810 --> 01:50:02.540
as he died shortly after his deposition.

01:50:02.540 --> 01:50:05.813
Henry soon found himself in a race against time.

01:50:05.813 --> 01:50:07.340
Anne had fallen pregnant,

01:50:07.340 --> 01:50:10.010
and the king was certain she was carrying a boy.

01:50:10.010 --> 01:50:12.140
As he was still married to Catherine,

01:50:12.140 --> 01:50:15.440
any child born from another woman would be illegitimate

01:50:15.440 --> 01:50:17.960
and unable to succeed him as heir.

01:50:17.960 --> 01:50:20.780
Knowing the pope was unsympathetic to his cause,

01:50:20.780 --> 01:50:22.040
he turned to parliament,

01:50:22.040 --> 01:50:24.920
forcing them to declare his first marriage void.

01:50:24.920 --> 01:50:26.630
He married Anne in secret,

01:50:26.630 --> 01:50:29.120
and their child was born soon after.

01:50:29.120 --> 01:50:32.240
To Henry's dismay, however, it was a girl,

01:50:32.240 --> 01:50:34.550
the future Elizabeth I.

01:50:34.550 --> 01:50:37.610
Henry's actions greatly angered not just the clergy,

01:50:37.610 --> 01:50:41.300
but the Spanish Kingdom of Aragon, sparking a conflict

01:50:41.300 --> 01:50:43.880
that would come to have serious consequences

01:50:43.880 --> 01:50:46.220
on England in the coming decades.

01:50:46.220 --> 01:50:48.740
As his relationship with the pope had soured,

01:50:48.740 --> 01:50:51.890
Henry decided to take matters into his own hands.

01:50:51.890 --> 01:50:55.760
In 1534, the Acts of Supremacy was passed,

01:50:55.760 --> 01:51:00.170
making Henry, not the pope, head of the Church of England.

01:51:00.170 --> 01:51:02.390
But how was Henry able to pull this off?

01:51:02.390 --> 01:51:04.490
Rome had been the head of the English church

01:51:04.490 --> 01:51:07.820
since the time of the great Anglo-Saxon kingdoms,

01:51:07.820 --> 01:51:10.550
put simply, the Reformation.

01:51:10.550 --> 01:51:13.760
The church had incurred a tremendous amount of bad feeling

01:51:13.760 --> 01:51:16.790
from everyone in England with church officials being seen

01:51:16.790 --> 01:51:20.540
as wealthy, corrupt, and removed from the ordinary man.

01:51:20.540 --> 01:51:23.090
With Henry now at the head of the Church of England,

01:51:23.090 --> 01:51:24.980
he was free to do as he pleased.

01:51:24.980 --> 01:51:27.200
Those who disagreed would be killed.

01:51:27.200 --> 01:51:29.030
Henry asserted the greatest power

01:51:29.030 --> 01:51:31.040
when he had Thomas More beheaded

01:51:31.040 --> 01:51:33.650
for refusing to take the oath of succession.

01:51:33.650 --> 01:51:37.310
It didn't matter who you were, Henry would punish.

01:51:37.310 --> 01:51:39.800
Henry VIII deeply regretted the killing.

01:51:39.800 --> 01:51:41.900
It was his one life regret.

01:51:41.900 --> 01:51:44.120
After Anne Boleyn failed to provide Henry

01:51:44.120 --> 01:51:46.010
with the male heir he wanted,

01:51:46.010 --> 01:51:48.890
Henry believed she was having an affair with her brother.

01:51:48.890 --> 01:51:52.580
He had both of them charged with treason and beheaded.

01:51:52.580 --> 01:51:54.770
He married Jane Seymour next,

01:51:54.770 --> 01:51:57.440
a woman of considerably lower education

01:51:57.440 --> 01:51:59.300
than his previous two marriages,

01:51:59.300 --> 01:52:01.730
but someone he was deeply fond of.

01:52:01.730 --> 01:52:05.750
She was successful in giving Henry a male heir, Edward,

01:52:05.750 --> 01:52:08.870
but the boy was sickly and there were serious doubts

01:52:08.870 --> 01:52:11.330
about his ability to make it into adulthood.

01:52:11.330 --> 01:52:13.190
So Henry kept trying.

01:52:13.190 --> 01:52:16.010
Jane Seymour died of postnatal complications

01:52:16.010 --> 01:52:18.050
a few weeks after the birth of Edward,

01:52:18.050 --> 01:52:20.780
and the heartbroken king mourned her loss heavily.

01:52:20.780 --> 01:52:25.550
In 1540, however, he was persuaded to marry Anne of Cleves,

01:52:25.550 --> 01:52:28.670
but Anne wasn't exactly what you'd call a looker,

01:52:28.670 --> 01:52:30.770
and their bond lasted only a year

01:52:30.770 --> 01:52:33.260
before Henry had that marriage annulled too.

01:52:33.260 --> 01:52:36.950
That same year he married the 19-year-old Catherine Howard,

01:52:36.950 --> 01:52:38.930
cousin of the late Anne Boleyn.

01:52:38.930 --> 01:52:41.060
She too was beheaded.

01:52:41.060 --> 01:52:43.220
His final wife, Catherine Parr,

01:52:43.220 --> 01:52:47.180
had the luxury of being widowed by the 55-year-old Henry

01:52:47.180 --> 01:52:49.570
who died in 1547.

01:52:49.570 --> 01:52:53.210
He was buried at St. George's Chapel at Windsor Castle,

01:52:53.210 --> 01:52:56.510
beside the remains of his third wife, Jane Seymour.

01:52:56.510 --> 01:52:58.250
His reign had been described

01:52:58.250 --> 01:53:01.520
as one of the most important in English history.

01:53:01.520 --> 01:53:03.800
Henry VIII died believing he had achieved

01:53:03.800 --> 01:53:05.360
what he'd wanted all along,

01:53:05.360 --> 01:53:07.670
a male heir on the English throne.

01:53:07.670 --> 01:53:09.440
But as we'll soon find out,

01:53:09.440 --> 01:53:12.500
his actions were about to plunge England

01:53:12.500 --> 01:53:15.410
into a period of instability and destruction

01:53:15.410 --> 01:53:17.720
that would lead to the death of all,

01:53:17.720 --> 01:53:19.793
but one of his children.

01:53:21.309 --> 01:53:24.080
(suspenseful music)

01:53:24.080 --> 01:53:27.560
Crowned on the 20th of February, 1547,

01:53:27.560 --> 01:53:30.200
Edward was just nine when he came to the throne,

01:53:30.200 --> 01:53:33.500
and thus saw his kingdom ruled by a regency council

01:53:33.500 --> 01:53:35.960
led by his uncle Edward Seymour.

01:53:35.960 --> 01:53:38.390
The youngest of Henry's three children,

01:53:38.390 --> 01:53:40.310
Edward was the first English king

01:53:40.310 --> 01:53:43.490
raised completely Protestant, and his reign was marked

01:53:43.490 --> 01:53:46.520
by major economic and religious upheaval.

01:53:46.520 --> 01:53:49.940
The former was very much a gift from his father, Henry VIII,

01:53:49.940 --> 01:53:52.940
who spent and squandered the vast wealth of the crown

01:53:52.940 --> 01:53:56.120
through excessive flamboyance and mismanagement.

01:53:56.120 --> 01:53:59.420
Things were not helped by a costly and ineffective war

01:53:59.420 --> 01:54:03.080
Edward VI waged against Scotland, which ended in peace

01:54:03.080 --> 01:54:05.150
in exchange for the withdrawal of troops

01:54:05.150 --> 01:54:08.180
from Scottish territory and northern France.

01:54:08.180 --> 01:54:12.110
But perhaps most impactful was the immense religious change

01:54:12.110 --> 01:54:14.240
England soon found itself under.

01:54:14.240 --> 01:54:17.090
While Henry had broken away from the Catholic church,

01:54:17.090 --> 01:54:20.090
he still remained fervently Catholic in doctrine,

01:54:20.090 --> 01:54:23.270
upholding its traditions and practices throughout the realm.

01:54:23.270 --> 01:54:26.510
But King Edward meanwhile was raised a total Protestant,

01:54:26.510 --> 01:54:29.600
and under the regency of the Lord Protector Seymour,

01:54:29.600 --> 01:54:33.860
vast and sweeping religious reforms were passed in England.

01:54:33.860 --> 01:54:35.720
Staples of the Catholic church,

01:54:35.720 --> 01:54:39.470
like Mass and clerical celibacy, were abolished,

01:54:39.470 --> 01:54:42.320
and Seymour passed the Acts of Uniformity,

01:54:42.320 --> 01:54:43.970
which forced all people in the realm

01:54:43.970 --> 01:54:45.890
to attend worship on Sunday.

01:54:45.890 --> 01:54:48.778
While a little tyrannical, it did introduce the concept

01:54:48.778 --> 01:54:53.390
of Sunday as a mandatory day off for the English peasantry.

01:54:53.390 --> 01:54:55.940
But while the regents ruled in his place,

01:54:55.940 --> 01:54:58.430
King Edward VI struggled with his health.

01:54:58.430 --> 01:55:02.180
He was feeble, ghostly pale, and constantly sickly.

01:55:02.180 --> 01:55:06.260
In 1553, Edward fell ill and died.

01:55:06.260 --> 01:55:08.570
He was only 15 years old.

01:55:08.570 --> 01:55:11.240
Before his death, he, alongside his council,

01:55:11.240 --> 01:55:13.550
devised a plan for succession.

01:55:13.550 --> 01:55:15.740
Childless, Edward wanted to ensure

01:55:15.740 --> 01:55:17.840
that his kingdom remained Protestant,

01:55:17.840 --> 01:55:20.840
and so passed his crown onto his first cousin

01:55:20.840 --> 01:55:24.710
and granddaughter of Henry VII, Lady Jane Grey.

01:55:24.710 --> 01:55:27.440
This action, however, removed his older sisters,

01:55:27.440 --> 01:55:30.800
Mary and Elizabeth, from the line of succession.

01:55:30.800 --> 01:55:34.040
Mary was a devout Catholic and would no doubt have reversed

01:55:34.040 --> 01:55:36.590
many of Edward's reformist policies.

01:55:36.590 --> 01:55:39.380
As is the case often with royal succession,

01:55:39.380 --> 01:55:41.540
Edward's passing on the 6th of July

01:55:41.540 --> 01:55:43.733
brought chaos to England.

01:55:45.557 --> 01:55:48.290
(dramatic music)

01:55:48.290 --> 01:55:51.110
Lady Jane Grey never had a coronation.

01:55:51.110 --> 01:55:54.290
She struggled to gain support outside the royal courts.

01:55:54.290 --> 01:55:56.540
And after just nine days on the throne,

01:55:56.540 --> 01:56:00.170
she was removed by Mary I, Henry's eldest daughter

01:56:00.170 --> 01:56:03.470
from his first marriage to Catherine of Aragon.

01:56:03.470 --> 01:56:05.660
Amassing an army in East Anglia,

01:56:05.660 --> 01:56:08.510
Mary marched on London and deposed Jane,

01:56:08.510 --> 01:56:10.310
beheading her for treason

01:56:10.310 --> 01:56:12.860
and taking the English throne as her own.

01:56:12.860 --> 01:56:16.040
Excluding the contested reigns of Lady Jane Grey

01:56:16.040 --> 01:56:17.570
and Empress Matilda,

01:56:17.570 --> 01:56:21.560
Queen Mary was the first queen regent of England.

01:56:21.560 --> 01:56:24.560
But while Mary was able to wrestle control of the crown

01:56:24.560 --> 01:56:26.360
back from her Protestant cousin,

01:56:26.360 --> 01:56:29.870
England's foothold on Calais would finally be lost,

01:56:29.870 --> 01:56:32.180
ending centuries of English presence

01:56:32.180 --> 01:56:33.650
on the continent of Europe.

01:56:33.650 --> 01:56:37.280
For now, England was once again just an island.

01:56:37.280 --> 01:56:40.550
Edward's fear that his half sister would try to undo most,

01:56:40.550 --> 01:56:42.950
if not all of his religious reforms,

01:56:42.950 --> 01:56:46.100
was confirmed shortly after she came to power.

01:56:46.100 --> 01:56:49.760
As a devout Catholic, Mary disliked Protestantism,

01:56:49.760 --> 01:56:51.590
seeing it as one of the vehicles

01:56:51.590 --> 01:56:55.580
that led to her mother's humiliation and her own disownment.

01:56:55.580 --> 01:56:58.565
During her reign, Protestants were severely repressed

01:56:58.565 --> 01:57:01.550
and many were burnt at the stake as heretics,

01:57:01.550 --> 01:57:04.790
earning the queen a new name, Bloody Mary.

01:57:04.790 --> 01:57:07.820
But conflict with the Protestants wasn't enough for Mary,

01:57:07.820 --> 01:57:10.730
as she soon became diametrically opposed

01:57:10.730 --> 01:57:12.170
with her own parliament.

01:57:12.170 --> 01:57:15.560
It was parliament who stopped many of Mary's counter reforms

01:57:15.560 --> 01:57:18.440
against Protestantism from becoming law,

01:57:18.440 --> 01:57:20.840
something she was greatly angered by.

01:57:20.840 --> 01:57:23.600
She entered into an extremely unpopular marriage

01:57:23.600 --> 01:57:27.020
with Philip of Spain, himself a devout Catholic,

01:57:27.020 --> 01:57:28.520
but was blocked by parliament

01:57:28.520 --> 01:57:30.860
from making him co-ruler of England,

01:57:30.860 --> 01:57:33.650
essentially barring him from taking over the throne

01:57:33.650 --> 01:57:35.540
should Mary die before him.

01:57:35.540 --> 01:57:37.430
The parent never had any children,

01:57:37.430 --> 01:57:41.870
and in 1558, Queen Mary I fell gravely ill.

01:57:41.870 --> 01:57:44.240
It was obvious that she would soon die.

01:57:44.240 --> 01:57:45.860
As parliament blocked Philip

01:57:45.860 --> 01:57:47.750
from inheriting the English throne,

01:57:47.750 --> 01:57:51.020
the crown was to be passed on to Mary's younger sister

01:57:51.020 --> 01:57:52.970
and the last person on Earth

01:57:52.970 --> 01:57:56.543
who thought she would inherit the English crown, Elizabeth.

01:57:58.444 --> 01:58:01.250
(light music)

01:58:01.250 --> 01:58:04.010
The pendulum swing of religious reformation

01:58:04.010 --> 01:58:06.980
that had gripped England since the reign of Henry VIII

01:58:06.980 --> 01:58:10.820
once again shifted towards the side of Protestantism,

01:58:10.820 --> 01:58:13.460
with the ascension of Elizabeth as ruler.

01:58:13.460 --> 01:58:15.140
She was crowned Queen Elizabeth I

01:58:15.140 --> 01:58:19.190
on the 17th of November, 1558.

01:58:19.190 --> 01:58:21.200
Unlike her siblings before her,

01:58:21.200 --> 01:58:24.500
Elizabeth possessed a keen eye for diplomacy

01:58:24.500 --> 01:58:26.840
and a shrewd political mind.

01:58:26.840 --> 01:58:28.610
She knew that to remain in power,

01:58:28.610 --> 01:58:30.800
she would need both the support of parliament

01:58:30.800 --> 01:58:33.050
and the religious bodies of England.

01:58:33.050 --> 01:58:35.330
Under Queen Elizabeth, the Church of England,

01:58:35.330 --> 01:58:39.950
as we know it today, was officially established in 1563.

01:58:39.950 --> 01:58:43.250
It based its dogma on the Protestant belief system,

01:58:43.250 --> 01:58:45.620
but the liturgy, rights, and organization

01:58:45.620 --> 01:58:48.140
were very much still Catholic in form,

01:58:48.140 --> 01:58:49.490
appeasing both sides

01:58:49.490 --> 01:58:53.390
and somewhat calming the volatile reformation, for now.

01:58:53.390 --> 01:58:56.180
However, religion still posed a great threat

01:58:56.180 --> 01:58:57.200
to the new queen,

01:58:57.200 --> 01:59:00.680
as she soon faced a Catholic uprising from the north,

01:59:00.680 --> 01:59:03.830
led by her cousin, Mary, Queen of Scots.

01:59:03.830 --> 01:59:06.230
As the granddaughter of Henry VII,

01:59:06.230 --> 01:59:08.570
Mary made a claim to the English throne,

01:59:08.570 --> 01:59:10.340
actions which many of the Catholics

01:59:10.340 --> 01:59:13.400
in England wholeheartedly supported.

01:59:13.400 --> 01:59:15.800
Queen Elizabeth felt threatened by Mary

01:59:15.800 --> 01:59:19.520
and her growing power base, but was initially reluctant

01:59:19.520 --> 01:59:21.590
to take direct action against her.

01:59:21.590 --> 01:59:25.070
She settled for imprisoning Mary in the Tower of London,

01:59:25.070 --> 01:59:27.590
but during her imprisonment, it was discovered

01:59:27.590 --> 01:59:29.600
that she was in regular correspondence

01:59:29.600 --> 01:59:31.910
with many of the queen's enemies.

01:59:31.910 --> 01:59:33.650
Elizabeth had no choice.

01:59:33.650 --> 01:59:38.650
Mary, Queen of Scots, was executed for treason in 1587.

01:59:38.810 --> 01:59:41.540
Soon, however, her attention would be turned away

01:59:41.540 --> 01:59:45.740
from domestic matters and onto more international threats.

01:59:45.740 --> 01:59:49.070
England's relationship with Spain had slowly been souring

01:59:49.070 --> 01:59:50.690
since the reign of her father.

01:59:50.690 --> 01:59:53.270
Angered by the treatment of Catherine of Aragon,

01:59:53.270 --> 01:59:54.980
and further angered by the treatment

01:59:54.980 --> 01:59:57.170
of Mary's husband, Philip of Spain,

01:59:57.170 --> 02:00:00.350
relations between the two European superpowers

02:00:00.350 --> 02:00:02.300
was at an all time low.

02:00:02.300 --> 02:00:04.730
Spain was still firmly Catholic.

02:00:04.730 --> 02:00:06.560
Meanwhile, England spearheaded

02:00:06.560 --> 02:00:08.330
the new Protestant reformation

02:00:08.330 --> 02:00:10.910
that was sweeping over Europe, but the catalyst,

02:00:10.910 --> 02:00:14.240
which finally ignited war between the two nations,

02:00:14.240 --> 02:00:15.980
was the new world.

02:00:15.980 --> 02:00:19.790
Discovered by Christopher Columbus in 1492,

02:00:19.790 --> 02:00:22.250
the Spanish crown had been made rich,

02:00:22.250 --> 02:00:25.400
thanks to the influx of new materials and minerals

02:00:25.400 --> 02:00:28.340
from its territories in the new world.

02:00:28.340 --> 02:00:32.240
As England's own empirical ambitions had yet to fully begin,

02:00:32.240 --> 02:00:33.950
they resorted to piracy.

02:00:33.950 --> 02:00:36.740
English sailors would raid Spanish frigates

02:00:36.740 --> 02:00:38.720
traveling across the Atlantic,

02:00:38.720 --> 02:00:41.660
stealing their wealth and bringing it back to England.

02:00:41.660 --> 02:00:44.412
Publicly, Elizabeth denounced those pirates,

02:00:44.412 --> 02:00:46.220
but in private, she supported

02:00:46.220 --> 02:00:48.890
and even praised them for their actions,

02:00:48.890 --> 02:00:52.460
knighting prominent privateers, as they were called,

02:00:52.460 --> 02:00:56.420
like Sir Francis Drake and Sir John Hawkins.

02:00:56.420 --> 02:00:59.570
By 1588, Spain had had enough.

02:00:59.570 --> 02:01:01.460
They amassed a large fleet of ships

02:01:01.460 --> 02:01:03.590
with the intention of invading England.

02:01:03.590 --> 02:01:05.750
Dubbed the Spanish Armada,

02:01:05.750 --> 02:01:08.117
it left Lisbon with over 150 ships

02:01:08.117 --> 02:01:11.077
and 18,000 men at their control.

02:01:11.077 --> 02:01:14.750
At the time, it was the largest fleet ever seen in Europe

02:01:14.750 --> 02:01:17.540
and was widely considered to be invincible.

02:01:17.540 --> 02:01:20.360
It easily outnumbered and outgunned the English fleet,

02:01:20.360 --> 02:01:23.930
and with news of its departure, fear set in at Westminster.

02:01:23.930 --> 02:01:26.600
The armada was cited off the coast of Plymouth,

02:01:26.600 --> 02:01:29.090
where English commander Sir Francis Drake

02:01:29.090 --> 02:01:31.610
was enjoying a calm game of balls.

02:01:31.610 --> 02:01:34.730
Legend has it that Drake insisted on finishing his game

02:01:34.730 --> 02:01:36.770
before meeting his enemy in battle.

02:01:36.770 --> 02:01:39.590
The English ships sailed out to meet the armada,

02:01:39.590 --> 02:01:43.010
and light skirmishes began off the Cornish coast.

02:01:43.010 --> 02:01:45.560
English used its smaller and faster ships

02:01:45.560 --> 02:01:48.770
to outmaneuver the large and bulky Spanish fleet,

02:01:48.770 --> 02:01:51.650
inflicting some early damage on the invading navy.

02:01:51.650 --> 02:01:53.990
Following the armada up into the channel,

02:01:53.990 --> 02:01:56.150
the Spanish commander in charge of the fleet

02:01:56.150 --> 02:01:59.240
was advised to stop and occupy the Isle of Wight,

02:01:59.240 --> 02:02:01.520
but refused and instead continued on

02:02:01.520 --> 02:02:03.110
with his planned rendezvous

02:02:03.110 --> 02:02:06.140
with the Duke of Parma's forces in Flanders.

02:02:06.140 --> 02:02:08.420
They reached Calais largely intact.

02:02:08.420 --> 02:02:11.510
But that night, things were about to change.

02:02:11.510 --> 02:02:14.630
Knowing he could not beat the Spanish in an open battle,

02:02:14.630 --> 02:02:16.070
Drake devised a plan.

02:02:16.070 --> 02:02:18.050
They set entire ships alight

02:02:18.050 --> 02:02:21.290
and sailed them into the Spanish fleet anchored at Calais,

02:02:21.290 --> 02:02:24.560
causing the fleet to scatter and take heavy losses.

02:02:24.560 --> 02:02:26.450
The Spaniard suffered another defeat

02:02:26.450 --> 02:02:28.820
at the hands of the smaller English ships

02:02:28.820 --> 02:02:30.890
at the Battle of Gravelines.

02:02:30.890 --> 02:02:33.620
And as the armada fled up into the North Sea,

02:02:33.620 --> 02:02:36.140
English ships gave chase around the island.

02:02:36.140 --> 02:02:38.960
Now firmly in the North Sea, Drake and his navy

02:02:38.960 --> 02:02:42.320
gave up chasing the Spanish fleet and returned home.

02:02:42.320 --> 02:02:44.360
The ships that remained of the Armada

02:02:44.360 --> 02:02:46.940
now had the long journey back to Lisbon.

02:02:46.940 --> 02:02:49.430
A huge and violent storm erupted

02:02:49.430 --> 02:02:51.710
while the Spanish sailed around Scotland

02:02:51.710 --> 02:02:53.840
and many ships were shipwrecked.

02:02:53.840 --> 02:02:55.790
By the time they returned to Spain,

02:02:55.790 --> 02:02:58.640
the mighty armada was in pieces.

02:02:58.640 --> 02:03:01.670
Drake was a hero, and England was safe.

02:03:01.670 --> 02:03:05.330
The reign of Elizabeth was an incredibly transformative time

02:03:05.330 --> 02:03:06.620
in English history.

02:03:06.620 --> 02:03:09.560
It marked the emergence of England as a global power

02:03:09.560 --> 02:03:11.420
and not just a European one.

02:03:11.420 --> 02:03:13.370
The investment into a royal navy

02:03:13.370 --> 02:03:15.754
led directly to England's colonial ambitions

02:03:15.754 --> 02:03:17.660
in the years that followed.

02:03:17.660 --> 02:03:21.260
A cultural renaissance also took hold of the island.

02:03:21.260 --> 02:03:23.180
Great playwrights like Shakespeare

02:03:23.180 --> 02:03:26.330
and Christopher Marlowe packed theaters in the capital,

02:03:26.330 --> 02:03:28.940
while adventurers like Drake and Walter Rowley

02:03:28.940 --> 02:03:31.940
explored a new world beyond the borders of Europe.

02:03:31.940 --> 02:03:35.480
Her 44 years on the throne was welcomed by all,

02:03:35.480 --> 02:03:38.150
and Queen Elizabeth enjoyed great popularity

02:03:38.150 --> 02:03:39.740
amongst her subjects.

02:03:39.740 --> 02:03:43.310
One of her most defining features was her chastity.

02:03:43.310 --> 02:03:46.280
Elizabeth died a virgin in 1603.

02:03:46.280 --> 02:03:49.250
She never married, never publicly took suitors,

02:03:49.250 --> 02:03:51.680
and as a result, had no heirs.

02:03:51.680 --> 02:03:55.280
She was the last Tudor monarch of England.

02:03:55.280 --> 02:03:57.650
The issue of succession loomed large

02:03:57.650 --> 02:04:00.620
in Elizabeth's later years, but before she died,

02:04:00.620 --> 02:04:01.850
an agreement had been reached

02:04:01.850 --> 02:04:04.400
that the throne would pass on to her cousin,

02:04:04.400 --> 02:04:08.690
James VI of Scotland, son of Mary, Queen of Scots.

02:04:08.690 --> 02:04:11.660
This unified England and Scotland peacefully

02:04:11.660 --> 02:04:14.960
under one banner for the first time in its history

02:04:14.960 --> 02:04:17.750
and laid the foundation for the Kingdom of Great Britain

02:04:17.750 --> 02:04:19.580
that was about to take its place

02:04:19.580 --> 02:04:22.493
as a superpower on the world stage.

02:04:24.174 --> 02:04:26.750
(light music)

02:04:26.750 --> 02:04:31.280
On the 24th of March, 1603, James VI of Scotland

02:04:31.280 --> 02:04:34.490
was crowned James I, King of England.

02:04:34.490 --> 02:04:37.790
It's worth noting that while James was ruler of both England

02:04:37.790 --> 02:04:42.050
and Scotland, the two kingdoms were not a unified entity.

02:04:42.050 --> 02:04:43.880
They still had separate parliaments,

02:04:43.880 --> 02:04:46.758
their own laws, and individual judiciaries.

02:04:46.758 --> 02:04:49.970
King James was just a shared head of state.

02:04:49.970 --> 02:04:52.850
But it was the first step towards the unification

02:04:52.850 --> 02:04:55.220
of the island of Great Britain.

02:04:55.220 --> 02:04:57.380
And King James spent most of his rule

02:04:57.380 --> 02:05:00.740
fighting to unify the two administrative bodies.

02:05:00.740 --> 02:05:04.070
Despite this, however, the reign of the first Stuart king

02:05:04.070 --> 02:05:07.550
would mostly be remembered for its conflict and division.

02:05:07.550 --> 02:05:11.030
Religion still dominated English domestic policy,

02:05:11.030 --> 02:05:13.400
and the king continued to support the Protestants

02:05:13.400 --> 02:05:16.850
and their reformation that firmly took hold in England.

02:05:16.850 --> 02:05:18.467
During the early years of his rule,

02:05:18.467 --> 02:05:21.620
the king had a new version of the Bible commissioned.

02:05:21.620 --> 02:05:25.580
Named the King James Bible, it was an English language Bible

02:05:25.580 --> 02:05:27.470
that soared in popularity

02:05:27.470 --> 02:05:30.650
thanks to its poetic prose and vivid imagery.

02:05:30.650 --> 02:05:32.240
Many historians credited

02:05:32.240 --> 02:05:35.540
for helping to spread the English language across the globe,

02:05:35.540 --> 02:05:38.810
as it quickly became the most printed book ever,

02:05:38.810 --> 02:05:43.100
and still remains a popular version of the Bible today.

02:05:43.100 --> 02:05:47.720
In 1604, he expelled all Catholic priests from the island,

02:05:47.720 --> 02:05:50.690
a move that would spark an explosive reaction

02:05:50.690 --> 02:05:53.600
from the increasingly radical Catholic minority,

02:05:53.600 --> 02:05:56.120
which still called England their home.

02:05:56.120 --> 02:05:59.390
One wet and dark evening in Northamptonshire,

02:05:59.390 --> 02:06:03.710
11 men quietly murmured to one another at a nearby inn.

02:06:03.710 --> 02:06:07.160
Bathed in candlelight and gripped by religious fervor,

02:06:07.160 --> 02:06:09.051
they devised a plan to put an end

02:06:09.051 --> 02:06:12.980
to the Protestant reformation and its supporters.

02:06:12.980 --> 02:06:16.640
They would take 36 barrels of gunpowder into the cellars

02:06:16.640 --> 02:06:19.400
of the newly constructed houses of parliament

02:06:19.400 --> 02:06:22.790
and ignite them on the day the building was to open,

02:06:22.790 --> 02:06:24.470
killing the king and his council

02:06:24.470 --> 02:06:26.780
in a bang of smoke and fire.

02:06:26.780 --> 02:06:29.840
It was to be known as the Gunpowder Plot.

02:06:29.840 --> 02:06:31.640
Over the course of a few weeks,

02:06:31.640 --> 02:06:33.440
they rolled their barrels down,

02:06:33.440 --> 02:06:36.350
avoiding deduction and capture night after night.

02:06:36.350 --> 02:06:39.680
With the grand opening set for the 5th of November

02:06:39.680 --> 02:06:41.870
and the gunpowder ready to blow,

02:06:41.870 --> 02:06:46.870
all the plotters had to do was wait, but their plans failed.

02:06:47.030 --> 02:06:49.640
An anonymous letter betrayed the plotters,

02:06:49.640 --> 02:06:51.680
and on the morning of the grand opening,

02:06:51.680 --> 02:06:56.450
royal guards flooded into the cellars to discover a lone man

02:06:56.450 --> 02:06:59.270
standing amidst the barrels of gunpowder.

02:06:59.270 --> 02:07:02.210
Guy Fawkes was caught and arrested.

02:07:02.210 --> 02:07:05.120
He was brutally tortured for several days,

02:07:05.120 --> 02:07:06.657
finally giving away the identities

02:07:06.657 --> 02:07:10.640
of the other conspirators after three days on the rack.

02:07:10.640 --> 02:07:12.950
The gunpowder plotters were rounded up,

02:07:12.950 --> 02:07:14.870
captured, and executed.

02:07:14.870 --> 02:07:18.590
All around London, people lit bonfires in celebration

02:07:18.590 --> 02:07:21.770
of the foiled attack on parliament and the king.

02:07:21.770 --> 02:07:25.160
This tradition still exists in England today.

02:07:25.160 --> 02:07:26.690
The plotters had hoped their attack

02:07:26.690 --> 02:07:29.030
would stop the reformation in its tracks,

02:07:29.030 --> 02:07:31.913
but in fact, it had the opposite effect.

02:07:33.080 --> 02:07:36.200
King James had once promised not to persecute Catholics,

02:07:36.200 --> 02:07:37.970
as long as they be quiet

02:07:37.970 --> 02:07:40.700
and give but an outward obedience to the law.

02:07:40.700 --> 02:07:43.400
After the failed Gunpowder Plot, however,

02:07:43.400 --> 02:07:46.868
he passed a wave of anti-Catholic legislation,

02:07:46.868 --> 02:07:48.440
and many in parliament

02:07:48.440 --> 02:07:51.830
who had remained decidedly neutral on the reformation,

02:07:51.830 --> 02:07:54.920
now firmly supported the Protestant cause.

02:07:54.920 --> 02:07:57.500
But for all the religious strife in the realm,

02:07:57.500 --> 02:08:01.190
King James's biggest threat actually came from within.

02:08:01.190 --> 02:08:04.040
Parliament had been growing increasingly powerful,

02:08:04.040 --> 02:08:06.440
and at the start of the 1600s,

02:08:06.440 --> 02:08:09.710
their influence in the kingdom was at an all time high.

02:08:09.710 --> 02:08:14.120
In 1614, he commented that he was surprised his ancestors

02:08:14.120 --> 02:08:16.640
should have permitted such an institution

02:08:16.640 --> 02:08:18.470
to come into existence.

02:08:18.470 --> 02:08:22.010
It is sedation in subjects to dispute what a king may do

02:08:22.010 --> 02:08:23.600
in the height of his power.

02:08:23.600 --> 02:08:25.220
Like many before him,

02:08:25.220 --> 02:08:29.120
King James believed in the absolute power of the monarchy,

02:08:29.120 --> 02:08:32.900
and as a result, resented parliament's ability to challenge

02:08:32.900 --> 02:08:34.460
and contest his rule.

02:08:34.460 --> 02:08:36.710
But while they may have had their differences,

02:08:36.710 --> 02:08:39.320
both ruling bodies were able to compromise

02:08:39.320 --> 02:08:40.820
and maintain the peace.

02:08:40.820 --> 02:08:45.260
As a result, the reign of King James I was widely considered

02:08:45.260 --> 02:08:49.430
to be a peaceful and prosperous time in England.

02:08:49.430 --> 02:08:51.980
The English crown established its first colony

02:08:51.980 --> 02:08:54.710
in the new world, Jamestown in Virginia,

02:08:54.710 --> 02:08:56.630
so named after King James

02:08:56.630 --> 02:08:59.060
and the virgin Queen Elizabeth before him.

02:08:59.060 --> 02:09:02.300
Meanwhile, the great literary tradition of English writers

02:09:02.300 --> 02:09:05.390
continued to flourish as England became a center

02:09:05.390 --> 02:09:07.850
for culture and art in Europe.

02:09:07.850 --> 02:09:11.030
By the end of his life, King James suffered from ill health

02:09:11.030 --> 02:09:13.670
brought on by a lifestyle of excesses.

02:09:13.670 --> 02:09:17.060
He would eventually die during a strong bout of dysentery

02:09:17.060 --> 02:09:20.390
on the 27th of March, 1625.

02:09:20.390 --> 02:09:21.872
At his funeral, it was remarked

02:09:21.872 --> 02:09:25.370
that the king died as he lived, in peace.

02:09:25.370 --> 02:09:28.250
But cracks in the kingdom had started to show.

02:09:28.250 --> 02:09:30.828
Too long had England labored under the strains

02:09:30.828 --> 02:09:34.400
of parliamentary conflict and religious upheaval.

02:09:34.400 --> 02:09:37.670
The heir to the English throne, Charles I,

02:09:37.670 --> 02:09:40.310
was about to inherit a realm that was on the verge

02:09:40.310 --> 02:09:42.173
of tearing itself apart.

02:09:43.877 --> 02:09:46.640
(light music)

02:09:46.640 --> 02:09:50.180
Crowned on the 27th of March, 1625,

02:09:50.180 --> 02:09:54.590
Charles I became king of England, Scotland, and Ireland

02:09:54.590 --> 02:09:57.620
in front of a large crowd at Westminster Abbey.

02:09:57.620 --> 02:09:59.540
He shared in his father's ideas

02:09:59.540 --> 02:10:01.910
of a monarch's divine right to rule,

02:10:01.910 --> 02:10:05.570
and as such, was determined to limit the power of parliament

02:10:05.570 --> 02:10:09.320
and govern over England unchecked and unquestioned.

02:10:09.320 --> 02:10:12.290
Their first showdown came in 1627

02:10:12.290 --> 02:10:14.810
when King Charles attempted to levy taxes

02:10:14.810 --> 02:10:16.580
without parliamentary backing.

02:10:16.580 --> 02:10:19.190
Parliament responded with the petition of rights

02:10:19.190 --> 02:10:20.150
a year later.

02:10:20.150 --> 02:10:23.570
Its basic premise was that no taxes of any kind

02:10:23.570 --> 02:10:26.450
could be allowed without the permission of parliament.

02:10:26.450 --> 02:10:28.940
For Charles, this was the final straw.

02:10:28.940 --> 02:10:30.140
He dissolved parliament

02:10:30.140 --> 02:10:33.170
and ruled without it for the next 11 years,

02:10:33.170 --> 02:10:35.291
levying a number of dubious taxes

02:10:35.291 --> 02:10:38.570
and passing new laws without parliamentary backing,

02:10:38.570 --> 02:10:42.770
actions which made the English king extremely unpopular.

02:10:42.770 --> 02:10:46.040
During this time, England saw an unprecedented level

02:10:46.040 --> 02:10:47.990
of immigration from the island.

02:10:47.990 --> 02:10:52.370
It is estimated that up to 60,000 people left England,

02:10:52.370 --> 02:10:55.100
with half of them going to the New American colonies

02:10:55.100 --> 02:10:56.540
across the Atlantic.

02:10:56.540 --> 02:10:58.233
It wasn't only because of the unjust

02:10:58.233 --> 02:11:01.310
and steep taxation levied by King Charles,

02:11:01.310 --> 02:11:04.343
but because they sought religious freedom in the new world.

02:11:05.690 --> 02:11:08.780
The Calvinist movement had become increasingly popular

02:11:08.780 --> 02:11:11.090
in the kingdom, especially amongst the middle

02:11:11.090 --> 02:11:14.900
and lower classes, and given rise to Puritanism.

02:11:14.900 --> 02:11:17.450
Puritans believed that the new Church of England

02:11:17.450 --> 02:11:20.720
wasn't Protestant enough in its practices,

02:11:20.720 --> 02:11:23.330
and thought it needed to further separate itself

02:11:23.330 --> 02:11:24.920
from Catholic doctrine,

02:11:24.920 --> 02:11:27.890
which still permeated some aspects of its worship.

02:11:27.890 --> 02:11:30.560
Because of the increasing amount of Protestant offshoots

02:11:30.560 --> 02:11:33.050
that were springing up, Archbishop Laud

02:11:33.050 --> 02:11:36.410
attempted to impose uniformity on the English church,

02:11:36.410 --> 02:11:40.430
opposing the Puritan ideal of a stripped back ceremony

02:11:40.430 --> 02:11:43.730
in favor of a traditional ceremonial splendor,

02:11:43.730 --> 02:11:46.280
similar to that of the Roman Catholics.

02:11:46.280 --> 02:11:48.615
As a result, a vast majority of the people

02:11:48.615 --> 02:11:52.040
who left for the colonies were Puritans

02:11:52.040 --> 02:11:55.010
who wish to practice religion the way they saw fit,

02:11:55.010 --> 02:11:57.740
but the impact of King Charles' taxes

02:11:57.740 --> 02:11:59.960
should not be understated.

02:11:59.960 --> 02:12:03.410
He attempted to levy ship money, a form of taxation

02:12:03.410 --> 02:12:06.020
that previously only applied to port cities,

02:12:06.020 --> 02:12:08.510
but now applied to the entire country,

02:12:08.510 --> 02:12:11.300
leading to a sharp decline in his popularity

02:12:11.300 --> 02:12:14.060
and firm opposition to the royal regime.

02:12:14.060 --> 02:12:17.270
Angry at the lack of support and desperate for money,

02:12:17.270 --> 02:12:20.180
King Charles had no choice but to call parliament.

02:12:20.180 --> 02:12:22.940
The Short Parliament, as it came to be known,

02:12:22.940 --> 02:12:24.890
sat for just three weeks.

02:12:24.890 --> 02:12:27.770
It came to an abrupt end after parliament refused

02:12:27.770 --> 02:12:30.650
to vote on any new taxes until the king had listened

02:12:30.650 --> 02:12:32.930
to their long list of grievances.

02:12:32.930 --> 02:12:36.530
After a rebellion broke out in Scotland just months later,

02:12:36.530 --> 02:12:39.380
Charles was once again forced to call parliament.

02:12:39.380 --> 02:12:42.590
This time parliament would sit for 20 years,

02:12:42.590 --> 02:12:45.740
earning itself the nickname the Long Parliament.

02:12:45.740 --> 02:12:46.880
It was apparent to all

02:12:46.880 --> 02:12:49.940
that King Charles' power was growing weaker by the day,

02:12:49.940 --> 02:12:52.100
and parliament seized on the opportunity

02:12:52.100 --> 02:12:54.650
to make increasingly larger demands,

02:12:54.650 --> 02:12:56.900
all of which the king refused.

02:12:56.900 --> 02:12:58.880
The fractured intense relationship

02:12:58.880 --> 02:13:00.560
between the king and his parliament

02:13:00.560 --> 02:13:03.885
that had been festering since the reign of King James I

02:13:03.885 --> 02:13:05.480
finally caved in.

02:13:05.480 --> 02:13:08.030
Fighting broke out in 1642,

02:13:08.030 --> 02:13:10.730
marking the beginning of the English Civil War.

02:13:10.730 --> 02:13:13.010
It was a conflict that was largely split up

02:13:13.010 --> 02:13:14.750
along class lines.

02:13:14.750 --> 02:13:17.990
Parliamentary troops or Roundheads, as they were known,

02:13:17.990 --> 02:13:21.230
were largely made up of the Protestant middle class.

02:13:21.230 --> 02:13:23.990
Meanwhile, the king's army or the Cavaliers

02:13:23.990 --> 02:13:27.920
were mainly supported by the nobility, clergy and peasantry.

02:13:27.920 --> 02:13:31.160
The war began as a series of indecisive skirmishes

02:13:31.160 --> 02:13:32.450
across the region.

02:13:32.450 --> 02:13:33.770
It was during this time

02:13:33.770 --> 02:13:36.500
that a parliamentary general from East Anglia

02:13:36.500 --> 02:13:39.920
began to make a name for himself in the Roundhead army.

02:13:39.920 --> 02:13:42.230
Oliver Cromwell rose to prominence

02:13:42.230 --> 02:13:45.650
by organizing the irregular parliamentary troops

02:13:45.650 --> 02:13:49.760
and transforming them into a disciplined new model army

02:13:49.760 --> 02:13:51.740
capable of taking on the king.

02:13:51.740 --> 02:13:54.740
But while conflict raged for the fate of the kingdom,

02:13:54.740 --> 02:13:58.400
life for most during the Civil War went on as usual,

02:13:58.400 --> 02:14:01.760
fewer involved and even fewer knew about the fighting.

02:14:01.760 --> 02:14:05.840
In 1644, a farmer at Marston Moor was told to leave

02:14:05.840 --> 02:14:08.630
because the armies of parliament and the armies of the king

02:14:08.630 --> 02:14:10.670
were preparing to fight on his land.

02:14:10.670 --> 02:14:12.950
He responded by saying, "What?

02:14:12.950 --> 02:14:14.930
Has them two fallen out then?"

02:14:14.930 --> 02:14:17.390
The farmer was probably equally unaware

02:14:17.390 --> 02:14:19.910
that the farmland he tilled at Marston Moor

02:14:19.910 --> 02:14:22.910
was to be a turning point in the war.

02:14:22.910 --> 02:14:25.430
King Charles' army was decisively beaten

02:14:25.430 --> 02:14:27.110
by Cromwell and his men,

02:14:27.110 --> 02:14:30.590
earning parliament the first major victory of the conflict

02:14:30.590 --> 02:14:34.070
and gave them direct control over the north of England.

02:14:34.070 --> 02:14:37.460
A year later, the king and his army was once again defeated

02:14:37.460 --> 02:14:39.080
at the Battle of Naseby,

02:14:39.080 --> 02:14:41.900
losing control of the south of England as well.

02:14:41.900 --> 02:14:44.600
The English civil war was over.

02:14:44.600 --> 02:14:45.860
Parliament had won.

02:14:45.860 --> 02:14:49.310
Marching back into London, they sought peace with the king.

02:14:49.310 --> 02:14:51.110
During the conflict, however,

02:14:51.110 --> 02:14:54.830
the parliamentary cause became increasingly radicalized

02:14:54.830 --> 02:14:57.350
and extreme in their Protestant beliefs.

02:14:57.350 --> 02:14:59.510
Archbishop Laud who had pushed back

02:14:59.510 --> 02:15:04.280
many of the Calvinist reforms was executed in 1645,

02:15:04.280 --> 02:15:05.660
and many within parliament

02:15:05.660 --> 02:15:07.760
called for the execution of the king

02:15:07.760 --> 02:15:10.040
as the only way to prevent the nation

02:15:10.040 --> 02:15:11.650
falling into anarchy again.

02:15:11.650 --> 02:15:16.460
In 1649, King Charles was brought to trial in Westminster.

02:15:16.460 --> 02:15:17.960
The king was unyielding

02:15:17.960 --> 02:15:21.170
and stubbornly stuck to his absolutist beliefs,

02:15:21.170 --> 02:15:24.770
refusing every one of parliament's calls for reform.

02:15:24.770 --> 02:15:27.230
The radical core had had enough.

02:15:27.230 --> 02:15:29.900
Charged with treason by a parliament whose authority

02:15:29.900 --> 02:15:31.670
he refused to acknowledge,

02:15:31.670 --> 02:15:34.819
King Charles I was executed in Whitehall

02:15:34.819 --> 02:15:38.690
on the 30th of January, 1649.

02:15:38.690 --> 02:15:41.870
For the first time since the Roman Republic,

02:15:41.870 --> 02:15:44.120
England was ruled in its entirety

02:15:44.120 --> 02:15:46.850
by a council of representative officials

02:15:46.850 --> 02:15:48.980
and not a divine ruler.

02:15:48.980 --> 02:15:51.653
England had become a commonwealth.

02:15:53.636 --> 02:15:56.510
(dramatic music)

02:15:56.510 --> 02:15:59.864
The king's execution was actually delayed by several hours

02:15:59.864 --> 02:16:03.290
so that the House of Commons could pass an emergency bill

02:16:03.290 --> 02:16:05.000
that declared itself the source

02:16:05.000 --> 02:16:07.430
of all just power in the realm.

02:16:07.430 --> 02:16:10.700
The reality of the situation was very different.

02:16:10.700 --> 02:16:13.850
Almost all power was in the hands of one man,

02:16:13.850 --> 02:16:15.170
Oliver Cromwell.

02:16:15.170 --> 02:16:18.710
He'd proven himself a highly capable military leader

02:16:18.710 --> 02:16:21.740
and retained control of the parliamentary army,

02:16:21.740 --> 02:16:23.303
even after the war had ended.

02:16:24.200 --> 02:16:26.570
King Charles's son, Charles II,

02:16:26.570 --> 02:16:29.450
landed in Scotland shortly after his father's death

02:16:29.450 --> 02:16:31.850
and attempted to invade England through the north.

02:16:31.850 --> 02:16:35.660
Cromwell defeated his army at Worcester in 1650,

02:16:35.660 --> 02:16:38.330
and Charles was forced to flee to France.

02:16:38.330 --> 02:16:41.120
Back in London, parliament was struggling to agree

02:16:41.120 --> 02:16:43.040
on how the realm should be governed.

02:16:43.040 --> 02:16:46.220
Cromwell, growing tired of the unending debates,

02:16:46.220 --> 02:16:48.470
dissolved the Rump Parliament

02:16:48.470 --> 02:16:50.780
with the use of his armed forces.

02:16:50.780 --> 02:16:54.290
In 1653, he established the Protectorate,

02:16:54.290 --> 02:16:57.560
an executive council that would directly rule over England

02:16:57.560 --> 02:16:59.540
just like the king had before.

02:16:59.540 --> 02:17:03.050
You can probably guess who he installed as its leader.

02:17:03.050 --> 02:17:04.790
A king in all but name,

02:17:04.790 --> 02:17:08.750
Cromwell ruthlessly enforced a set of rigid and strict laws

02:17:08.750 --> 02:17:12.380
that followed the Puritan ideal unwaveringly.

02:17:12.380 --> 02:17:14.360
Church attendance was compulsory.

02:17:14.360 --> 02:17:16.910
Horse racing and cockfighting were banned.

02:17:16.910 --> 02:17:19.520
Gambling dens and brothels closed down.

02:17:19.520 --> 02:17:22.760
And Cromwell even canceled Christmas.

02:17:22.760 --> 02:17:25.100
It wasn't long before the lord protector

02:17:25.100 --> 02:17:28.400
had become as autocratic as the king he'd overthrown.

02:17:28.400 --> 02:17:30.854
He called parliament when he wanted to raise taxes

02:17:30.854 --> 02:17:32.840
and dismissed it when they argued.

02:17:32.840 --> 02:17:36.440
In all, it was a time of great repression and prudence.

02:17:36.440 --> 02:17:38.540
Pursuits of pleasure were banned,

02:17:38.540 --> 02:17:40.760
and many in the realm longed for the days

02:17:40.760 --> 02:17:42.470
when kings ruled England.

02:17:42.470 --> 02:17:46.460
Cromwell eventually died on the 3rd of September, 1658,

02:17:46.460 --> 02:17:48.590
and was buried at Westminster Abbey,

02:17:48.590 --> 02:17:50.294
a luxury previously only afforded

02:17:50.294 --> 02:17:52.550
to kings and queens of England.

02:17:52.550 --> 02:17:55.490
There were attempts to have his son, Richard Cromwell,

02:17:55.490 --> 02:17:57.740
take over the post of lord protector,

02:17:57.740 --> 02:18:01.250
but Richard was a less impactful character than his father,

02:18:01.250 --> 02:18:05.000
and as such, he was ousted shortly after taking the post.

02:18:05.000 --> 02:18:07.400
The Commonwealth had become so unpopular

02:18:07.400 --> 02:18:09.980
during Cromwell's rule that after his death,

02:18:09.980 --> 02:18:13.340
the people called for the king to be reinstated.

02:18:13.340 --> 02:18:15.920
Charles II came back from exile

02:18:15.920 --> 02:18:20.920
and was recrowned king of England on the 29th of May, 1661.

02:18:21.170 --> 02:18:23.720
The body of Oliver Cromwell was exhumed

02:18:23.720 --> 02:18:25.520
from its grave at Westminster

02:18:25.520 --> 02:18:28.160
and hung at Tyburn for all to see.

02:18:28.160 --> 02:18:30.710
When he began to rot, his head was cut off

02:18:30.710 --> 02:18:33.860
and put on public display outside Westminster Hall

02:18:33.860 --> 02:18:36.230
for the next 20 years.

02:18:36.230 --> 02:18:38.077
A statue of Cromwell still stands

02:18:38.077 --> 02:18:40.940
at the foot of the Houses of Parliament today.

02:18:40.940 --> 02:18:43.280
The Commonwealth and its Protectorate

02:18:43.280 --> 02:18:46.580
had a profound impact on English society.

02:18:46.580 --> 02:18:50.330
Puritanism became inexorably linked with military rule,

02:18:50.330 --> 02:18:53.030
and from this point onwards, the more Puritan aspects

02:18:53.030 --> 02:18:56.570
of the reformation were staunchly opposed by parliament,

02:18:56.570 --> 02:18:58.220
as the fervor of religion

02:18:58.220 --> 02:19:01.130
began to take a backseat in domestic rule.

02:19:01.130 --> 02:19:02.690
It also strengthened the bond

02:19:02.690 --> 02:19:04.400
between the kingdom and its king.

02:19:04.400 --> 02:19:05.690
In the next centuries,

02:19:05.690 --> 02:19:08.780
while Europe burned in the crucible of revolution,

02:19:08.780 --> 02:19:12.710
England remained a staunch supporter of dynastic rule,

02:19:12.710 --> 02:19:14.303
but more on that later.

02:19:15.168 --> 02:19:17.668
(light music)

02:19:18.920 --> 02:19:21.500
Considerably less hardheaded than his father,

02:19:21.500 --> 02:19:25.264
King Charles II oversaw the restoration of the crown

02:19:25.264 --> 02:19:28.940
and the reintroduction of the royal family in England.

02:19:28.940 --> 02:19:31.310
The new king agreed to many of the proposals

02:19:31.310 --> 02:19:34.160
his predecessor had fought so hard against,

02:19:34.160 --> 02:19:35.900
and the relationship between king

02:19:35.900 --> 02:19:38.720
and parliament improved considerably.

02:19:38.720 --> 02:19:40.550
King Charles II then said

02:19:40.550 --> 02:19:43.160
about reverting many of the strict Puritan laws

02:19:43.160 --> 02:19:46.197
that Cromwell had passed during his protectorship.

02:19:46.197 --> 02:19:48.050
Alehouses were reopened,

02:19:48.050 --> 02:19:50.390
theaters were allowed to put on shows again,

02:19:50.390 --> 02:19:53.630
and sports and dance were revived throughout the region.

02:19:53.630 --> 02:19:55.438
But for all the splendor and merry

02:19:55.438 --> 02:20:00.050
that King Charles II oversaw, fresh challenges awaited

02:20:00.050 --> 02:20:03.560
as the kingdom settled back into its familiar rhythms.

02:20:03.560 --> 02:20:06.290
The English navy was at an all time low,

02:20:06.290 --> 02:20:09.410
having just lost the second Anglo Dutch war

02:20:09.410 --> 02:20:12.020
that saw the Netherlands pertain their position

02:20:12.020 --> 02:20:15.680
as the dominant European traitor on the high seas.

02:20:15.680 --> 02:20:18.620
Back at home, the Great Plague had struck London,

02:20:18.620 --> 02:20:21.560
killing an estimated 70,000 people

02:20:21.560 --> 02:20:25.310
and decimating the already dwindling English population.

02:20:25.310 --> 02:20:27.980
The following year, the Great Fire of London

02:20:27.980 --> 02:20:29.330
burned through the capital,

02:20:29.330 --> 02:20:33.350
leaving as much as 450 acres of London real estate

02:20:33.350 --> 02:20:34.850
in ash and soot.

02:20:34.850 --> 02:20:36.890
While the fire killed many

02:20:36.890 --> 02:20:40.340
and destroyed the livelihoods of thousands of Londoners,

02:20:40.340 --> 02:20:43.250
it did bring about the end of the Great Plague,

02:20:43.250 --> 02:20:46.640
as all the infected rats burned in the inferno.

02:20:46.640 --> 02:20:48.830
Moreover, it gave the king a chance

02:20:48.830 --> 02:20:52.820
to rebuild parts of the old rundown and ancient city.

02:20:52.820 --> 02:20:55.820
Houses were rebuilt with high quality materials,

02:20:55.820 --> 02:20:58.630
civil planning was introduced, widening streets

02:20:58.630 --> 02:21:01.700
and making the capital feel less cramped.

02:21:01.700 --> 02:21:05.510
The old St Paul's Cathedral also needed to be rebuilt,

02:21:05.510 --> 02:21:09.110
giving us the stunning architectural masterpiece

02:21:09.110 --> 02:21:10.760
we still have today.

02:21:10.760 --> 02:21:12.320
Huge changes in government

02:21:12.320 --> 02:21:14.240
were also beginning to take shape.

02:21:14.240 --> 02:21:17.540
During the reign of King Charles II, there was a move

02:21:17.540 --> 02:21:21.440
to the cabinet style of government England still uses today.

02:21:21.440 --> 02:21:23.720
Political parties were formed

02:21:23.720 --> 02:21:27.230
that became the forerunners to the Tories and Whigs.

02:21:27.230 --> 02:21:30.170
England was modernizing at a rapid rate,

02:21:30.170 --> 02:21:31.487
spurred on by the new king

02:21:31.487 --> 02:21:33.680
and the restoration of the monarchy.

02:21:33.680 --> 02:21:36.350
It was considered to be a model nation,

02:21:36.350 --> 02:21:37.970
and despite its flaws,

02:21:37.970 --> 02:21:40.400
it truly was leading the way in Europe

02:21:40.400 --> 02:21:42.770
in terms of freedom and quality of life.

02:21:42.770 --> 02:21:44.660
But for all modernization,

02:21:44.660 --> 02:21:48.350
religion still plagued domestic policy in the kingdom.

02:21:48.350 --> 02:21:50.780
There was an apparent plot to kill the king

02:21:50.780 --> 02:21:54.050
and establish Catholicism in England once again.

02:21:54.050 --> 02:21:57.350
Known as the Popish Plot of 1678,

02:21:57.350 --> 02:21:59.480
it highlighted how Catholics in the realm

02:21:59.480 --> 02:22:03.560
still severely opposed the reformation, its ideals,

02:22:03.560 --> 02:22:06.380
and the king's perceived role in all this.

02:22:06.380 --> 02:22:10.250
As a result of the plot, anti-Catholic sentiments soared

02:22:10.250 --> 02:22:12.320
and Catholics were banned from parliament

02:22:12.320 --> 02:22:14.960
for the first time in the nation's history.

02:22:14.960 --> 02:22:16.220
Despite this though,

02:22:16.220 --> 02:22:18.740
King Charles was considerably more popular

02:22:18.740 --> 02:22:20.300
than his father before him

02:22:20.300 --> 02:22:23.120
and was considered something of a modern man.

02:22:23.120 --> 02:22:27.470
He was affable, friendly, and reportedly very easygoing.

02:22:27.470 --> 02:22:29.189
His court quickly developed a reputation

02:22:29.189 --> 02:22:33.680
for being morally lax, and the king was often criticized

02:22:33.680 --> 02:22:38.060
for being overly reserved, especially in political matters.

02:22:38.060 --> 02:22:40.250
His marriage to Catherine of Braganza

02:22:40.250 --> 02:22:43.310
saw the pair produce no surviving heirs,

02:22:43.310 --> 02:22:46.790
but the king did recognize 12 illegitimate children

02:22:46.790 --> 02:22:48.710
to various mistresses.

02:22:48.710 --> 02:22:51.530
As a result, when King Charles II died

02:22:51.530 --> 02:22:54.260
on the 6th of February, 1684,

02:22:54.260 --> 02:22:57.547
the throne had to be passed on to his brother, James.

02:22:58.424 --> 02:23:00.924
(light music)

02:23:02.390 --> 02:23:04.820
James was crowned James II of England

02:23:04.820 --> 02:23:08.620
on the same day of his brother's passing in 1684.

02:23:08.620 --> 02:23:10.550
He was a staunch Catholic,

02:23:10.550 --> 02:23:13.250
and despite the growing anti-Catholic sentiment

02:23:13.250 --> 02:23:15.560
that defined England during this time,

02:23:15.560 --> 02:23:17.270
he was accepted as king.

02:23:17.270 --> 02:23:19.310
But while parliament may have been accepting

02:23:19.310 --> 02:23:21.740
of his personal Catholic persuasion,

02:23:21.740 --> 02:23:25.700
they were far less tolerant of any supporting legislation.

02:23:25.700 --> 02:23:27.459
King James tried unsuccessfully

02:23:27.459 --> 02:23:31.160
to enact a number of pro-Catholic policies in the realm.

02:23:31.160 --> 02:23:33.440
This quickly turned the two political parties

02:23:33.440 --> 02:23:36.343
that had formed, the Whigs and Tories, against him,

02:23:36.343 --> 02:23:40.395
and the king grew increasingly more isolated by the day.

02:23:40.395 --> 02:23:44.450
In 1685, one of Charles's illegitimate sons,

02:23:44.450 --> 02:23:47.030
the Duke of Monmouth, landed in Somerset

02:23:47.030 --> 02:23:49.520
and launched a rebellion against his uncle,

02:23:49.520 --> 02:23:52.910
supported by local farmers and laborers in the region.

02:23:52.910 --> 02:23:56.240
The Pitchfork Rebellion was a short-lived affair

02:23:56.240 --> 02:23:58.670
that ended with the battle of Sedgemoor,

02:23:58.670 --> 02:24:01.190
the last battle on English soil,

02:24:01.190 --> 02:24:04.100
and culminated in the bloodiest sizes,

02:24:04.100 --> 02:24:06.110
a series of brutal trials

02:24:06.110 --> 02:24:09.200
that punished all those who had supported the rebellion.

02:24:09.200 --> 02:24:11.810
Led by the infamous Judge Jeffreys,

02:24:11.810 --> 02:24:14.510
hundreds of men were condemned to their death

02:24:14.510 --> 02:24:17.690
and the king's popularity in the realm plummeted.

02:24:17.690 --> 02:24:21.260
To make matters worse, King James had recently had a son

02:24:21.260 --> 02:24:24.410
and shored up his line of succession with a Catholic heir.

02:24:24.410 --> 02:24:26.600
Parliament feared a new Catholic line

02:24:26.600 --> 02:24:30.860
of succession in England and acted quickly to stop this.

02:24:30.860 --> 02:24:33.380
They invited the firmly protestant William

02:24:33.380 --> 02:24:36.170
and Mary of Orange from modern day Holland

02:24:36.170 --> 02:24:39.710
to take over the English throne from King James II.

02:24:39.710 --> 02:24:40.850
Amassing an army,

02:24:40.850 --> 02:24:44.930
William led the glorious revolution in 1688,

02:24:44.930 --> 02:24:49.460
landing Brixham and deposing King James II unopposed.

02:24:49.460 --> 02:24:51.170
The old king fled to France

02:24:51.170 --> 02:24:53.900
where he was welcomed by Louis XIV

02:24:53.900 --> 02:24:55.760
and given a small court of his own

02:24:55.760 --> 02:24:57.710
where he could live out the rest of his days

02:24:57.710 --> 02:24:59.363
in quiet and comfort.

02:25:00.975 --> 02:25:03.410
(gentle music)

02:25:03.410 --> 02:25:06.020
Now, it's important to note that William of Orange

02:25:06.020 --> 02:25:07.790
and his wife Mary of England

02:25:07.790 --> 02:25:10.910
were by no means usurpers of the English throne.

02:25:10.910 --> 02:25:14.180
Mary was actually King James's eldest daughter,

02:25:14.180 --> 02:25:17.180
while William was a descendant of Charles I.

02:25:17.180 --> 02:25:19.010
This legally meant William and Mary

02:25:19.010 --> 02:25:23.120
had as much claim to the throne as, say, James himself.

02:25:23.120 --> 02:25:24.620
But bloodlines aside,

02:25:24.620 --> 02:25:27.770
what really made the pair such an attractive prospect

02:25:27.770 --> 02:25:30.620
was their firm belief in Protestantism.

02:25:30.620 --> 02:25:32.990
William of Orange was widely considered

02:25:32.990 --> 02:25:36.440
a champion of the faith, having led multiple wars

02:25:36.440 --> 02:25:39.364
against the powerful Catholic King Louis XIV

02:25:39.364 --> 02:25:40.760
on the continent.

02:25:40.760 --> 02:25:42.350
Together with his wife Mary,

02:25:42.350 --> 02:25:45.680
they ruled over England together as co-regents,

02:25:45.680 --> 02:25:48.470
but in reality, King William spent a majority

02:25:48.470 --> 02:25:51.590
of his time in Europe fighting the Nine Years' War.

02:25:51.590 --> 02:25:53.600
This left Queen Mary II

02:25:53.600 --> 02:25:56.810
to rule over the realm alone in his absence.

02:25:56.810 --> 02:25:59.600
She quickly proved to be an exemplary regent,

02:25:59.600 --> 02:26:01.790
ruling with a firmness and speed,

02:26:01.790 --> 02:26:03.290
all of which made her popular

02:26:03.290 --> 02:26:05.270
with her parliament and people.

02:26:05.270 --> 02:26:08.600
For the first time since the reign of Queen Elizabeth,

02:26:08.600 --> 02:26:11.450
the two governing bodies that ruled over England

02:26:11.450 --> 02:26:15.710
enjoyed a period of considerable peace and cooperation.

02:26:15.710 --> 02:26:17.720
Parliament was able to pass new bills

02:26:17.720 --> 02:26:20.600
and levy taxes with little royal pushback,

02:26:20.600 --> 02:26:23.930
and in 1689, they passed the Bill of Rights,

02:26:23.930 --> 02:26:26.450
a landmark moment in English history

02:26:26.450 --> 02:26:29.540
that forever altered the power of the crown.

02:26:29.540 --> 02:26:31.580
It essentially banned all Catholics

02:26:31.580 --> 02:26:35.210
from being crown king or queen of England again,

02:26:35.210 --> 02:26:36.800
and also barred the regent

02:26:36.800 --> 02:26:39.380
from interfering with political matters.

02:26:39.380 --> 02:26:41.300
Neither ruler opposed the new bill,

02:26:41.300 --> 02:26:45.920
and the power of the English monarch was diminished forever.

02:26:45.920 --> 02:26:49.250
Queen Mary died of smallpox in 1694,

02:26:49.250 --> 02:26:52.460
leaving King William alone to rule the English kingdom.

02:26:52.460 --> 02:26:54.200
Shortly after she passed,

02:26:54.200 --> 02:26:57.800
the king was notified of a Jacobite uprising in Scotland

02:26:57.800 --> 02:27:00.800
and he led an army north to confront the rebels.

02:27:00.800 --> 02:27:04.790
The Jacobites were a group loyal to the deposed James II

02:27:04.790 --> 02:27:07.100
and wanted to assassinate King William

02:27:07.100 --> 02:27:09.890
and restore James to the English throne.

02:27:09.890 --> 02:27:13.490
You see, after the glorious revolution, parliament argued

02:27:13.490 --> 02:27:16.970
that King James had forfeited the English throne by fleeing,

02:27:16.970 --> 02:27:18.980
leaving room for William to take it,

02:27:18.980 --> 02:27:21.980
not by force, but by invitation.

02:27:21.980 --> 02:27:23.990
This set a precedent of contract

02:27:23.990 --> 02:27:26.930
between the king and their people, where any breach,

02:27:26.930 --> 02:27:30.170
in this case, Kings James II fleeing the capital,

02:27:30.170 --> 02:27:33.080
could result in the legal deposition of the king

02:27:33.080 --> 02:27:34.910
at the hands of the people.

02:27:34.910 --> 02:27:37.370
Jacobites staunchly opposed this,

02:27:37.370 --> 02:27:40.970
believing that the king was chosen by God as a divine ruler

02:27:40.970 --> 02:27:42.830
and could not be removed,

02:27:42.830 --> 02:27:46.070
therefore making the post 1668 regime

02:27:46.070 --> 02:27:48.350
of King William illegitimate.

02:27:48.350 --> 02:27:51.110
The king swiftly crushed the Jacobite rebels,

02:27:51.110 --> 02:27:53.690
but their cause had not been defeated,

02:27:53.690 --> 02:27:55.850
and they would continue to threaten the crown

02:27:55.850 --> 02:27:57.590
for decades to come.

02:27:57.590 --> 02:27:59.270
But for now, King William

02:27:59.270 --> 02:28:02.060
and the House of Stuarts were secure.

02:28:02.060 --> 02:28:05.120
Having had no children and with a death of his nephew,

02:28:05.120 --> 02:28:08.480
Prince William, Duke of Gloucester, in 1700,

02:28:08.480 --> 02:28:10.820
the issue of succession soon took over

02:28:10.820 --> 02:28:12.980
as the main threat to Stuart rule.

02:28:12.980 --> 02:28:16.160
Not wanting to give the Jacobites any room to maneuver,

02:28:16.160 --> 02:28:17.810
he decided to name Anne,

02:28:17.810 --> 02:28:20.690
Queen Mary's sister and daughter of James II,

02:28:20.690 --> 02:28:23.180
as the successor to the English throne.

02:28:23.180 --> 02:28:25.820
On the 8th of March, 1702,

02:28:25.820 --> 02:28:27.980
King William joined his wife in death

02:28:27.980 --> 02:28:29.780
after contracting pneumonia,

02:28:29.780 --> 02:28:32.060
while he recovered from a broken collarbone

02:28:32.060 --> 02:28:34.850
he'd sustained falling off his horse.

02:28:34.850 --> 02:28:37.550
His reign had been incredibly stable,

02:28:37.550 --> 02:28:39.980
and he was a popular figure in the realm,

02:28:39.980 --> 02:28:42.320
both with parliament and the people.

02:28:42.320 --> 02:28:45.320
The stability he ushered was a welcome change

02:28:45.320 --> 02:28:48.590
as the iron grip of religious tensions appeared

02:28:48.590 --> 02:28:50.120
to have relaxed somewhat

02:28:50.120 --> 02:28:52.670
and was crowned shortly after his death

02:28:52.670 --> 02:28:55.892
and inherited a peaceful, prosperous kingdom.

02:28:55.892 --> 02:28:58.725
(uplifting music)

02:28:59.840 --> 02:29:02.630
Queen Anne was no stranger to the island

02:29:02.630 --> 02:29:04.550
and had already been a notable figure

02:29:04.550 --> 02:29:06.050
during the reign of her sister

02:29:06.050 --> 02:29:08.060
and brother-in-law before her.

02:29:08.060 --> 02:29:11.420
When she came to power herself in 1702,

02:29:11.420 --> 02:29:13.280
she had long established herself

02:29:13.280 --> 02:29:17.000
within the English upper class and enjoyed popular support

02:29:17.000 --> 02:29:20.240
from powerful nobles and politicians alike.

02:29:20.240 --> 02:29:21.860
For the first part of her reign,

02:29:21.860 --> 02:29:24.230
Queen Anne was under the influence of Sarah,

02:29:24.230 --> 02:29:28.070
Duchess of Marlborough, and her husband, John Churchill.

02:29:28.070 --> 02:29:29.630
Eventually, though, Queen Anne

02:29:29.630 --> 02:29:31.670
and the duchess fell out with one another,

02:29:31.670 --> 02:29:34.550
but not before the Churchills rose to prominence

02:29:34.550 --> 02:29:36.320
and power in the kingdom.

02:29:36.320 --> 02:29:38.420
John Churchill established himself

02:29:38.420 --> 02:29:41.480
as a premier naval captain who earned a claim

02:29:41.480 --> 02:29:44.150
for his role in the Spanish War of Succession.

02:29:44.150 --> 02:29:47.150
The Churchills would continue to play a large role

02:29:47.150 --> 02:29:50.210
in English history for the coming generations,

02:29:50.210 --> 02:29:54.410
all culminating in their ancestor, Sir Winston Churchill,

02:29:54.410 --> 02:29:57.590
leading England through the Second World War.

02:29:57.590 --> 02:29:59.690
When we look back at the reign of Queen Anne,

02:29:59.690 --> 02:30:02.240
the most enduring and notable part of it

02:30:02.240 --> 02:30:03.980
is without a doubt the formation

02:30:03.980 --> 02:30:06.620
of the United Kingdom of Great Britain.

02:30:06.620 --> 02:30:09.140
While Ireland was subordinate to England

02:30:09.140 --> 02:30:11.000
and Wales had long been made a part

02:30:11.000 --> 02:30:12.470
of the Kingdom of England,

02:30:12.470 --> 02:30:15.290
Scotland was still its own sovereign state.

02:30:15.290 --> 02:30:17.300
Queen Anne sought to change that,

02:30:17.300 --> 02:30:20.240
expressing her desires to unite the two kingdoms

02:30:20.240 --> 02:30:24.230
as early as her coronation speech at Westminster Abbey.

02:30:24.230 --> 02:30:28.730
In 1707, she got her wish with the Act of the Union.

02:30:28.730 --> 02:30:31.880
The Kingdom of Scotland and the Kingdom of England unified

02:30:31.880 --> 02:30:35.330
to form one sovereign state, Great Britain.

02:30:35.330 --> 02:30:38.030
A new flag was adopted to symbolize the unity

02:30:38.030 --> 02:30:41.360
of the two realms, giving birth to the Union Jack.

02:30:41.360 --> 02:30:43.880
Now, unlike her Catholic father, James II,

02:30:43.880 --> 02:30:46.640
Anne had been raised Anglican,

02:30:46.640 --> 02:30:50.240
and as such, supported policies and policy makers

02:30:50.240 --> 02:30:52.700
who shared in her religious views.

02:30:52.700 --> 02:30:56.240
She famously favored the Anglican majority Tory party

02:30:56.240 --> 02:30:59.120
in government, but faced increasing opposition

02:30:59.120 --> 02:31:01.130
from the Whigs who had grown in power

02:31:01.130 --> 02:31:03.470
since the War of the Spanish Succession.

02:31:03.470 --> 02:31:05.750
Things came to a head in 1710

02:31:05.750 --> 02:31:08.930
when she dismissed many Whig politicians from parliament

02:31:08.930 --> 02:31:10.700
for their hawkish behavior

02:31:10.700 --> 02:31:13.670
and continued insistence on an English presence

02:31:13.670 --> 02:31:18.110
in a European war, but the conflict had its upsides.

02:31:18.110 --> 02:31:20.420
The English navy had been revitalized

02:31:20.420 --> 02:31:22.940
and rebuilt since the early Stuart days,

02:31:22.940 --> 02:31:26.090
earning itself a fierce reputation on the high seas

02:31:26.090 --> 02:31:29.883
as one of the most formidable navies in the world.

02:31:29.883 --> 02:31:33.770
A powerful navy also helped bolster colonial expansion,

02:31:33.770 --> 02:31:36.950
as territories in the Americas were quickly developing

02:31:36.950 --> 02:31:39.890
into profitable and important territories

02:31:39.890 --> 02:31:43.220
thanks to the tobacco farms and growing slave trade.

02:31:43.220 --> 02:31:45.290
But while the kingdom flourished,

02:31:45.290 --> 02:31:47.990
Queen Anne privately suffered.

02:31:47.990 --> 02:31:50.780
She lost her husband, Prince George of Denmark,

02:31:50.780 --> 02:31:52.640
only a decade into her reign,

02:31:52.640 --> 02:31:54.170
and towards the end of her life,

02:31:54.170 --> 02:31:57.170
she suffered from severe ill health.

02:31:57.170 --> 02:31:59.630
She gained a lot of weight and had a stroke

02:31:59.630 --> 02:32:01.730
that left her without the ability to speak

02:32:01.730 --> 02:32:03.830
towards the latter half of her life.

02:32:03.830 --> 02:32:06.080
Not long after that, Queen Anne died

02:32:06.080 --> 02:32:09.560
on the morning of the 1st of August, 1714.

02:32:09.560 --> 02:32:11.840
Her doctors thought that her death was a release

02:32:11.840 --> 02:32:14.540
from a life of ill health and tragedy.

02:32:14.540 --> 02:32:19.391
Despite 17 pregnancies, none survived, and as such,

02:32:19.391 --> 02:32:23.330
Queen Anne had no one to succeed her on the throne.

02:32:23.330 --> 02:32:25.760
Because of the ban on Catholic monarchs,

02:32:25.760 --> 02:32:28.790
Anne needed to find a suitable Protestant successor.

02:32:28.790 --> 02:32:30.410
It was decided that her cousin,

02:32:30.410 --> 02:32:32.780
George I of the House of Hanover,

02:32:32.780 --> 02:32:34.670
would take over the British crown.

02:32:34.670 --> 02:32:38.123
Queen Anne was the last Stuart ruler of England.

02:32:39.860 --> 02:32:42.920
(light music)

02:32:42.920 --> 02:32:45.380
For the first time since William the Conqueror

02:32:45.380 --> 02:32:47.870
almost 700 years ago,

02:32:47.870 --> 02:32:51.350
England would again have a truly foreign king

02:32:51.350 --> 02:32:52.760
sitting on its throne.

02:32:52.760 --> 02:32:55.880
But while the realm welcomed their new Protestant ruler

02:32:55.880 --> 02:32:57.440
who had served with distinction

02:32:57.440 --> 02:32:59.690
during the Spanish War of Succession,

02:32:59.690 --> 02:33:01.820
there was just one glaring issue.

02:33:01.820 --> 02:33:05.300
King George I was outrageously unsuited

02:33:05.300 --> 02:33:07.670
to rule over the Kingdom of Great Britain.

02:33:07.670 --> 02:33:09.500
He didn't speak a word of English.

02:33:09.500 --> 02:33:11.990
He was pedantic, decidedly slow

02:33:11.990 --> 02:33:13.550
when it came to decision making,

02:33:13.550 --> 02:33:16.730
and showed a great disinterest in ruling over the kingdom.

02:33:16.730 --> 02:33:18.905
As a result, he passed over the control

02:33:18.905 --> 02:33:20.510
and authority of the realm

02:33:20.510 --> 02:33:23.720
to a small group of trusted politicians.

02:33:23.720 --> 02:33:25.850
This was a role that would later be known

02:33:25.850 --> 02:33:29.070
as the prime minister and officially gave birth

02:33:29.070 --> 02:33:32.840
to the cabinet system still used in England today.

02:33:32.840 --> 02:33:36.620
He was crowned on the 20th of October, 1714,

02:33:36.620 --> 02:33:38.060
and before he'd even had time

02:33:38.060 --> 02:33:39.980
to learn his councilors names,

02:33:39.980 --> 02:33:43.850
he was quickly forced to deal with an old threat up north.

02:33:43.850 --> 02:33:46.760
Jacobites had once again landed in Scotland

02:33:46.760 --> 02:33:48.440
seeking to overthrow the king

02:33:48.440 --> 02:33:51.620
and install James Stuart, son of James II,

02:33:51.620 --> 02:33:53.420
as the king of Great Britain.

02:33:53.420 --> 02:33:55.340
Like King William before him,

02:33:55.340 --> 02:33:58.970
the new King George easily quashed the rebel army,

02:33:58.970 --> 02:34:02.240
and James Stuart, later called the Old Pretender,

02:34:02.240 --> 02:34:05.240
fled to France, just like his father had.

02:34:05.240 --> 02:34:07.820
Meanwhile, back in Westminster, Churchill,

02:34:07.820 --> 02:34:11.090
the Duke of Marlborough, had now returned from Spain

02:34:11.090 --> 02:34:13.820
and came to the king to cash in his checks.

02:34:13.820 --> 02:34:17.000
The War of Spanish Succession had been fought on credit,

02:34:17.000 --> 02:34:19.040
with the idea that once it was over,

02:34:19.040 --> 02:34:21.350
the English crown would repay Marlborough

02:34:21.350 --> 02:34:25.610
for his men and material, but there was just one issue.

02:34:25.610 --> 02:34:27.380
The crown was in serious debt,

02:34:27.380 --> 02:34:30.800
and in theory, couldn't pay Churchill what he was owed.

02:34:30.800 --> 02:34:33.170
King George was himself a big spender,

02:34:33.170 --> 02:34:35.600
and famously had a number of mistresses

02:34:35.600 --> 02:34:38.000
who abused the court's finances,

02:34:38.000 --> 02:34:42.110
racking up huge bills on luxury goods and fine dining.

02:34:42.110 --> 02:34:45.380
So King George I and his financial advisors

02:34:45.380 --> 02:34:46.700
came up with a plan.

02:34:46.700 --> 02:34:50.420
They created the South Sea Company, a shell company,

02:34:50.420 --> 02:34:52.970
little more than paper on some clerk's desk,

02:34:52.970 --> 02:34:56.960
that would assume the 31 million pound national debt

02:34:56.960 --> 02:35:00.890
and turn it into company stock to be sold off to investors.

02:35:00.890 --> 02:35:04.100
This would in theory allow the crown to recoup their money

02:35:04.100 --> 02:35:07.250
and repay Churchill without bankrupting itself,

02:35:07.250 --> 02:35:10.130
but the stock was grossly overinflated

02:35:10.130 --> 02:35:12.110
and inevitably it crashed,

02:35:12.110 --> 02:35:16.160
bankrupting investors and the government all at once.

02:35:16.160 --> 02:35:19.040
Westminster was in disarray.

02:35:19.040 --> 02:35:21.590
Lord Stanhope, who was personally innocent

02:35:21.590 --> 02:35:24.980
of any wrongdoing, apparently collapsed and died

02:35:24.980 --> 02:35:27.110
after a stressful debate on the matter

02:35:27.110 --> 02:35:28.820
in the House of Lords.

02:35:28.820 --> 02:35:29.990
It was during this time

02:35:29.990 --> 02:35:32.930
that Robert Walpole rose to prominence.

02:35:32.930 --> 02:35:35.210
His expert management of the crisis

02:35:35.210 --> 02:35:36.980
and rescheduling of the debts

02:35:36.980 --> 02:35:40.670
allowed the kingdom to return to some financial stability

02:35:40.670 --> 02:35:43.550
and saved King George from disgrace.

02:35:43.550 --> 02:35:45.830
For his actions, he was promoted

02:35:45.830 --> 02:35:50.000
and became England's first defacto prime minister.

02:35:50.000 --> 02:35:51.800
In the aftermath of the crisis,

02:35:51.800 --> 02:35:54.320
the Bank of England took over in managing the crown

02:35:54.320 --> 02:35:56.987
and government funds, a move which eventually led

02:35:56.987 --> 02:36:00.320
to England's economy becoming the best managed

02:36:00.320 --> 02:36:02.720
in the world over the next century.

02:36:02.720 --> 02:36:06.470
However, King George, who was already an unpopular figure,

02:36:06.470 --> 02:36:08.690
had become borderline despised

02:36:08.690 --> 02:36:11.510
as a result of the South Sea fiasco.

02:36:11.510 --> 02:36:14.780
And with the establishment of the office of Prime Minister,

02:36:14.780 --> 02:36:18.650
royal power was once again undermined forever.

02:36:18.650 --> 02:36:20.810
King George I died from a stroke

02:36:20.810 --> 02:36:24.770
while visiting his native Hanover in June 1727.

02:36:24.770 --> 02:36:27.140
He is the most recent English king

02:36:27.140 --> 02:36:29.210
to be buried outside of Great Britain.

02:36:29.210 --> 02:36:32.783
His son, George II, was to take over the throne.

02:36:34.309 --> 02:36:36.110
(foreboding music)

02:36:36.110 --> 02:36:38.360
George followed in his father's footsteps

02:36:38.360 --> 02:36:41.170
as a firmly German English king.

02:36:41.170 --> 02:36:44.390
He is the most recent king born outside of England

02:36:44.390 --> 02:36:46.130
and chose to spend the majority of his time

02:36:46.130 --> 02:36:48.440
as ruler abroad in Hanover,

02:36:48.440 --> 02:36:51.410
where he exercised considerably more control

02:36:51.410 --> 02:36:53.000
over the running of the realm.

02:36:53.000 --> 02:36:56.330
You see, almost all of the domestic running of Great Britain

02:36:56.330 --> 02:36:58.610
now fell into the hands of parliament

02:36:58.610 --> 02:37:00.440
and the new prime minister,

02:37:00.440 --> 02:37:02.810
and King George II grew frustrated

02:37:02.810 --> 02:37:05.840
at the lack of influence he had as a royal.

02:37:05.840 --> 02:37:09.080
He was able to exercise some control over matters

02:37:09.080 --> 02:37:11.900
of international policy and warfare,

02:37:11.900 --> 02:37:14.690
but those decisions were few and far between.

02:37:14.690 --> 02:37:18.560
One of these moments was the third Jacobite uprising.

02:37:18.560 --> 02:37:22.190
Led by the Young Pretender, Bonnie Prince Charles,

02:37:22.190 --> 02:37:25.010
another son of the former James II,

02:37:25.010 --> 02:37:27.890
the Jacobite rebels amassed support in Scotland

02:37:27.890 --> 02:37:30.350
and marched South in English territory,

02:37:30.350 --> 02:37:33.170
hoping to depose the Hanoverian monarchy.

02:37:33.170 --> 02:37:36.320
Charles Stuart had hoped that upon his arrival in England,

02:37:36.320 --> 02:37:38.660
he would be flooded with popular support

02:37:38.660 --> 02:37:42.800
and easily overpower the unpopular Hanoverian king,

02:37:42.800 --> 02:37:44.480
but he was wrong.

02:37:44.480 --> 02:37:47.630
While his army was able to get as far south as Derby,

02:37:47.630 --> 02:37:50.251
they were plagued by indecisive leadership

02:37:50.251 --> 02:37:53.360
and failed to gather any support in the realm.

02:37:53.360 --> 02:37:55.490
Fearing a retaliation from the king,

02:37:55.490 --> 02:37:58.010
Charles Stuart retreated back to Scotland

02:37:58.010 --> 02:38:00.950
where he prepared to face King George's troops.

02:38:00.950 --> 02:38:05.570
At the Battle of Culloden in 1745, the final Jacobite stand

02:38:05.570 --> 02:38:08.750
would be slaughtered by William, Duke of Cumberland,

02:38:08.750 --> 02:38:10.910
on behalf of the British crown.

02:38:10.910 --> 02:38:12.740
The fighting was brutal,

02:38:12.740 --> 02:38:15.980
and William gave his men orders to spare no one,

02:38:15.980 --> 02:38:17.750
not even the wounded.

02:38:17.750 --> 02:38:21.200
Charles escaped the slaughter, making his way back to France

02:38:21.200 --> 02:38:24.320
where he lived out the last of his days a drunkard.

02:38:24.320 --> 02:38:27.050
The Scottish nobles who had supported the Jacobites

02:38:27.050 --> 02:38:30.440
were mercilessly rounded up and executed.

02:38:30.440 --> 02:38:33.937
It was so brutal that Cumberland earned himself the nickname

02:38:33.937 --> 02:38:38.210
Butcher Cumberland for his actions north of the border.

02:38:38.210 --> 02:38:40.010
But the revolt had been quashed,

02:38:40.010 --> 02:38:44.330
and finally the Jacobite threat had been silenced forever.

02:38:44.330 --> 02:38:46.400
The uprisings give us a unique look

02:38:46.400 --> 02:38:49.700
into how life during King George's reign was perceived.

02:38:49.700 --> 02:38:52.100
Life was good, placid, and peaceful,

02:38:52.100 --> 02:38:55.220
and it was clear that there was no genuine animosity

02:38:55.220 --> 02:38:58.578
for the king as exhibited by the lack of popular support

02:38:58.578 --> 02:39:00.560
the uprisings garnered.

02:39:00.560 --> 02:39:03.050
While the king was by no means popular,

02:39:03.050 --> 02:39:05.510
there was little incentive to depose him.

02:39:05.510 --> 02:39:07.070
The everyday running of the realm

02:39:07.070 --> 02:39:09.650
was firmly in the hands of parliament,

02:39:09.650 --> 02:39:12.680
and a new king was not likely to change that,

02:39:12.680 --> 02:39:16.010
and this domestic comfort was very much a side effect

02:39:16.010 --> 02:39:19.010
of Britain's growing international successes.

02:39:19.010 --> 02:39:20.900
The East India Trading Company

02:39:20.900 --> 02:39:23.870
that had been set up almost 100 years before

02:39:23.870 --> 02:39:27.200
defeated a combined army of French and Indian troops

02:39:27.200 --> 02:39:28.940
on the Indian subcontinent,

02:39:28.940 --> 02:39:32.780
earning themselves a total monopoly in the region.

02:39:32.780 --> 02:39:35.360
Elsewhere, the Seven Years' War was raging,

02:39:35.360 --> 02:39:38.510
with fighting taking place as far away as the new world

02:39:38.510 --> 02:39:41.240
and the first truly global conflict.

02:39:41.240 --> 02:39:44.420
Britain was ultimately victorious against the French,

02:39:44.420 --> 02:39:47.750
gaining new territories in Canada, Florida, Granada,

02:39:47.750 --> 02:39:50.510
Senegal, and east of the Mississippi.

02:39:50.510 --> 02:39:52.460
Great Britain was beginning to emerge

02:39:52.460 --> 02:39:55.430
as the most dominant force, not just in Europe,

02:39:55.430 --> 02:39:57.650
but on the entire planet.

02:39:57.650 --> 02:40:01.040
King George II lived to be 77 years old,

02:40:01.040 --> 02:40:03.770
then the oldest ruler in the nation's history,

02:40:03.770 --> 02:40:05.330
but by the end of his life,

02:40:05.330 --> 02:40:08.330
he was completely deaf and blind in one eye,

02:40:08.330 --> 02:40:12.260
and as a result, spent much of his time bedbound and unwell.

02:40:12.260 --> 02:40:15.830
He died on the 25th of October, 1760

02:40:15.830 --> 02:40:18.350
after collapsing near his closed stool,

02:40:18.350 --> 02:40:21.080
a precursor to the modern toilet.

02:40:21.080 --> 02:40:23.780
Because his eldest son, Frederick, Prince of Wales,

02:40:23.780 --> 02:40:26.510
had died suddenly in 1751,

02:40:26.510 --> 02:40:30.440
succession was passed onto Frederick's son, George III.

02:40:30.440 --> 02:40:33.830
Despite England enjoying a period of remarkable growth

02:40:33.830 --> 02:40:36.241
and expansion abroad, opening new museums

02:40:36.241 --> 02:40:39.140
and extinguishing long standing threats,

02:40:39.140 --> 02:40:41.930
King George was remembered by his contemporaries

02:40:41.930 --> 02:40:45.800
as a buffoon ruled by wives and ministers.

02:40:45.800 --> 02:40:48.140
He was considered an inept ruler,

02:40:48.140 --> 02:40:51.410
and subsequent memoirs all painted an image of a king

02:40:51.410 --> 02:40:53.990
engorged on pleasure and drink.

02:40:53.990 --> 02:40:56.210
But had they known who was to come next,

02:40:56.210 --> 02:40:57.740
the buffoon and his wife

02:40:57.740 --> 02:41:00.948
might not have been treated so harshly after all.

02:41:00.948 --> 02:41:03.781
(uplifting music)

02:41:04.760 --> 02:41:07.850
There was no way to know that the reign of King George III

02:41:07.850 --> 02:41:10.010
was to be one of the most tumultuous

02:41:10.010 --> 02:41:12.260
and eventful in English history.

02:41:12.260 --> 02:41:15.260
Domestically, internationally, and personally,

02:41:15.260 --> 02:41:18.830
George III faced pressure and conflict at every turn.

02:41:18.830 --> 02:41:22.520
Crowned on the 22nd of September, 1761,

02:41:22.520 --> 02:41:25.100
King George III differed from his grandfather

02:41:25.100 --> 02:41:26.990
and great-grandfather in the sense

02:41:26.990 --> 02:41:29.840
that he was more English than they ever were.

02:41:29.840 --> 02:41:32.270
He was born on the island, spoke the language,

02:41:32.270 --> 02:41:33.710
and spent his formative years

02:41:33.710 --> 02:41:35.390
learning in the British Kingdom.

02:41:35.390 --> 02:41:38.330
Those who hoped this would make him a more capable regent

02:41:38.330 --> 02:41:40.760
were quickly brought back to reality.

02:41:40.760 --> 02:41:43.520
King George III would frequently become afflicted

02:41:43.520 --> 02:41:46.190
with bouts of debilitating madness,

02:41:46.190 --> 02:41:47.959
rendering him incapable of ruling

02:41:47.959 --> 02:41:51.020
and sending Westminster into disarray.

02:41:51.020 --> 02:41:54.380
This earned the king the nickname Mad King George,

02:41:54.380 --> 02:41:56.270
and there were many attempts by parliament

02:41:56.270 --> 02:41:59.060
to install his son, the Prince of Wales, to the throne,

02:41:59.060 --> 02:42:00.590
but every time they tried,

02:42:00.590 --> 02:42:03.980
King George would regain his senses and resume his rule

02:42:03.980 --> 02:42:06.740
before any permanent decisions had been made.

02:42:06.740 --> 02:42:10.010
His early rule was defined mainly by conflict,

02:42:10.010 --> 02:42:12.020
both at home and abroad.

02:42:12.020 --> 02:42:13.970
The American War of Independence

02:42:13.970 --> 02:42:17.180
was won by the colonists in 1783,

02:42:17.180 --> 02:42:20.690
severing the Americas from the British control forever

02:42:20.690 --> 02:42:23.630
and giving birth to the United States of America

02:42:23.630 --> 02:42:25.490
as an independent nation.

02:42:25.490 --> 02:42:27.920
Closer to home, King George was forced to deal

02:42:27.920 --> 02:42:30.590
with the Gordon Riots of 1780,

02:42:30.590 --> 02:42:32.458
where a mob of protestors rioted

02:42:32.458 --> 02:42:35.570
against the specter of Catholic emancipation

02:42:35.570 --> 02:42:37.490
and left the city looted and burnt

02:42:37.490 --> 02:42:39.590
after three days of violence.

02:42:39.590 --> 02:42:44.150
Before that, in 1799, the United Irishmen rebelled

02:42:44.150 --> 02:42:45.950
on behalf of the Irish people

02:42:45.950 --> 02:42:49.070
and demanded Irish autonomy from Great Britain.

02:42:49.070 --> 02:42:51.530
They were easily defeated at Vinegar Hill,

02:42:51.530 --> 02:42:54.860
and two years later, Ireland was officially unified

02:42:54.860 --> 02:42:56.630
into the Kingdom of Great Britain,

02:42:56.630 --> 02:43:00.380
forming the United Kingdom that still stands today.

02:43:00.380 --> 02:43:04.010
But framing all this was the Napoleonic Wars.

02:43:04.010 --> 02:43:06.920
A Corsican in general with a skill for warfare

02:43:06.920 --> 02:43:10.760
and lofty ambitions had quickly come to dominate Europe,

02:43:10.760 --> 02:43:14.510
plunging the continent into a state of perpetual warfare.

02:43:14.510 --> 02:43:15.980
Fighting was sporadic,

02:43:15.980 --> 02:43:18.020
and a number of coalitions were formed

02:43:18.020 --> 02:43:20.720
to try and defeat the pint size general.

02:43:20.720 --> 02:43:23.810
British naval victories in the Nile and at Trafalgar

02:43:23.810 --> 02:43:25.820
earned the United Kingdom a reputation

02:43:25.820 --> 02:43:28.190
as the fiercest navy in the world,

02:43:28.190 --> 02:43:31.700
while the land war in Spain decisively pushed Napoleon

02:43:31.700 --> 02:43:33.680
out of the Iberian Peninsula.

02:43:33.680 --> 02:43:36.380
Britain was eventually victorious at Waterloo,

02:43:36.380 --> 02:43:40.280
marking the end of the Napoleonic Wars in 1815.

02:43:40.280 --> 02:43:42.620
Historians often cite this as the moment

02:43:42.620 --> 02:43:46.040
Britain became the most dominant power in the world.

02:43:46.040 --> 02:43:50.540
Under George III, the early industrial revolution also began

02:43:50.540 --> 02:43:53.900
as steam engines were introduced to the British workforce.

02:43:53.900 --> 02:43:56.870
Protests against these new machines were common

02:43:56.870 --> 02:43:59.420
and culminated in the Luddite protest

02:43:59.420 --> 02:44:01.700
where farm workers broke into factories

02:44:01.700 --> 02:44:03.380
and smashed up the machinery

02:44:03.380 --> 02:44:05.660
for taking their jobs away from them.

02:44:05.660 --> 02:44:07.880
The rapid changes in the workforce

02:44:07.880 --> 02:44:11.870
alongside the economic disaster that was the Napoleonic Wars

02:44:11.870 --> 02:44:15.590
meant that social unrest in Britain was at an all time high.

02:44:15.590 --> 02:44:20.090
Mass unemployment, depression, and civil unrest ran rampant,

02:44:20.090 --> 02:44:24.020
and the king's response was to ruthlessly quash dissent,

02:44:24.020 --> 02:44:25.610
usually by force.

02:44:25.610 --> 02:44:27.830
And keep in mind, during all this,

02:44:27.830 --> 02:44:29.570
King George would often descend

02:44:29.570 --> 02:44:32.180
into crippling bouts of madness,

02:44:32.180 --> 02:44:34.070
leaving the realm without its figurehead

02:44:34.070 --> 02:44:35.470
for months at a time.

02:44:35.470 --> 02:44:38.510
In 1810, parliament had had enough.

02:44:38.510 --> 02:44:40.910
It was clear that George could no longer rule,

02:44:40.910 --> 02:44:43.700
and it was decided that his son, George IV,

02:44:43.700 --> 02:44:46.190
would take over his regent in his place.

02:44:46.190 --> 02:44:48.380
King George lived for another 10 years

02:44:48.380 --> 02:44:50.360
while his son ruled in his place.

02:44:50.360 --> 02:44:54.845
When he died age 81 in 1820, he was the longest reigning

02:44:54.845 --> 02:44:58.430
and longest living British monarch in history.

02:44:58.430 --> 02:44:59.360
To this day,

02:44:59.360 --> 02:45:02.813
he's still the oldest reigning male king of England.

02:45:04.692 --> 02:45:07.850
(foreboding music)

02:45:07.850 --> 02:45:09.350
George, Prince of Wales,

02:45:09.350 --> 02:45:12.560
or Prinny, as he was known to those closest to him,

02:45:12.560 --> 02:45:16.520
had already been ruling over Britain as regent since 1810,

02:45:16.520 --> 02:45:19.250
but after the death of his father in 1820,

02:45:19.250 --> 02:45:22.250
he ascended to the throne as King George IV.

02:45:22.250 --> 02:45:24.140
Following in his father's footstep,

02:45:24.140 --> 02:45:27.910
King George IV was known as an impulsive, extravagant,

02:45:27.910 --> 02:45:32.150
and morally dubious man who enjoyed the finer things in life

02:45:32.150 --> 02:45:35.890
and behaved in a way that was all together unkingly.

02:45:35.890 --> 02:45:37.790
He had the brightened pavilion built

02:45:37.790 --> 02:45:41.450
as an homage to East Asia right here on the English coast.

02:45:41.450 --> 02:45:45.200
Its gaudy and lavish design was polarizing at the time,

02:45:45.200 --> 02:45:47.690
but it has since become a national treasure.

02:45:47.690 --> 02:45:51.470
He remodeled Buckingham Palace and rebuilt Windsor Castle

02:45:51.470 --> 02:45:54.950
to reflect the splendor and power of the English crown.

02:45:54.950 --> 02:45:57.140
On a personal level, King George was known

02:45:57.140 --> 02:45:59.390
for being something of a ladies man.

02:45:59.390 --> 02:46:02.810
Now, while having multiple mistresses wasn't uncommon,

02:46:02.810 --> 02:46:04.610
it was his behavior with them

02:46:04.610 --> 02:46:07.340
that earned him the scorn of his cabinet.

02:46:07.340 --> 02:46:09.770
One, a lady, Mrs. Fitzherbert,

02:46:09.770 --> 02:46:12.200
was said to have married the king in secret,

02:46:12.200 --> 02:46:14.240
and a tunnel from Brighton Pavilion

02:46:14.240 --> 02:46:16.700
leads directly into her home nearby.

02:46:16.700 --> 02:46:19.700
As a prince, King George earned himself a reputation

02:46:19.700 --> 02:46:22.520
as an extremely charming and cultured man.

02:46:22.520 --> 02:46:26.120
He is often remembered as the first gentleman of England,

02:46:26.120 --> 02:46:28.550
but faced an increasingly hostile public

02:46:28.550 --> 02:46:30.620
after his ascension to the throne.

02:46:30.620 --> 02:46:33.830
Crowned on the 19th of July, 1821,

02:46:33.830 --> 02:46:36.230
there was drama on the day of his coronation

02:46:36.230 --> 02:46:38.540
as the new king attempted to have his wife,

02:46:38.540 --> 02:46:41.420
Caroline of Brunswick, barred from the ceremony.

02:46:41.420 --> 02:46:43.070
He then petitioned parliament

02:46:43.070 --> 02:46:45.110
for help in getting a divorce.

02:46:45.110 --> 02:46:48.080
Under British law, a divorce could only be granted

02:46:48.080 --> 02:46:49.670
on the grounds of adultery.

02:46:49.670 --> 02:46:51.080
Since neither King George

02:46:51.080 --> 02:46:54.560
or Caroline would admit to that, the king got creative.

02:46:54.560 --> 02:46:57.740
He tried to pass the Bill of Pains and Penalties,

02:46:57.740 --> 02:47:01.460
essentially a public trial that accused his wife of adultery

02:47:01.460 --> 02:47:04.400
and planned to use parliament as his judge and jury

02:47:04.400 --> 02:47:07.250
to get a divorce and deny Caroline her right

02:47:07.250 --> 02:47:08.540
as queen of England.

02:47:08.540 --> 02:47:11.180
The debate was heavily reported in the press,

02:47:11.180 --> 02:47:13.850
and public opposition to the bill was high.

02:47:13.850 --> 02:47:16.640
It eventually passed, but only just,

02:47:16.640 --> 02:47:19.340
and as public unrest towards the bill grew,

02:47:19.340 --> 02:47:21.770
the government decided to withdraw the bill

02:47:21.770 --> 02:47:25.010
in an effort to save the reputation of the royal crown,

02:47:25.010 --> 02:47:27.140
but the damage had been done.

02:47:27.140 --> 02:47:29.000
The court of King George IV

02:47:29.000 --> 02:47:32.570
developed a reputation for extravagance and scandal.

02:47:32.570 --> 02:47:36.290
George was himself an impulsive and unreliable statesman

02:47:36.290 --> 02:47:38.480
who frequently behaved selfishly

02:47:38.480 --> 02:47:41.120
and drew the ire of many in his cabinet.

02:47:41.120 --> 02:47:43.430
The king's power continued to diminish,

02:47:43.430 --> 02:47:47.000
and George was forced to accept Catholic emancipation,

02:47:47.000 --> 02:47:50.420
a reversal of many of the anti-Catholic legislation

02:47:50.420 --> 02:47:53.270
that had been passed since the reign of Henry VIII,

02:47:53.270 --> 02:47:55.790
despite being staunchly opposed to it.

02:47:55.790 --> 02:47:58.310
Catholics were once again given the right to vote,

02:47:58.310 --> 02:48:01.370
hold public office, and sit in parliament.

02:48:01.370 --> 02:48:04.370
It was also during the reign of King George IV

02:48:04.370 --> 02:48:07.100
that the first regular police force in London

02:48:07.100 --> 02:48:09.290
was established by Robert Peel,

02:48:09.290 --> 02:48:11.750
but a life of overindulgence and grandeur

02:48:11.750 --> 02:48:13.400
had its toll on the king.

02:48:13.400 --> 02:48:15.350
By the time he ascended to the throne,

02:48:15.350 --> 02:48:17.150
he had gained so much weight

02:48:17.150 --> 02:48:19.310
that he was the subject of much ridicule

02:48:19.310 --> 02:48:21.200
during public appearances.

02:48:21.200 --> 02:48:25.940
He reached a whopping 17 stone, or 108 kilograms,

02:48:25.940 --> 02:48:27.830
and after a decade on the throne,

02:48:27.830 --> 02:48:30.350
his lifestyle had caught up to him.

02:48:30.350 --> 02:48:34.790
King George IV died on the 26th of June, 1830,

02:48:34.790 --> 02:48:37.580
surrounded by servants and cabinet members.

02:48:37.580 --> 02:48:41.127
A senior aide to the king privately confided in his diary,

02:48:41.127 --> 02:48:44.030
"A more contemptible, cowardly, selfish,

02:48:44.030 --> 02:48:46.700
unfeeling dog does not exist.

02:48:46.700 --> 02:48:50.330
There have been good and wise kings, but not many of them,

02:48:50.330 --> 02:48:53.450
and this I believe to be one of the worst."

02:48:53.450 --> 02:48:56.930
As his only legitimate child had died a few years prior,

02:48:56.930 --> 02:48:58.160
the throne was to be given

02:48:58.160 --> 02:49:00.890
to his younger brother, William Henry.

02:49:00.890 --> 02:49:03.390
(light music)

02:49:05.360 --> 02:49:07.310
Nicknamed the Sailor King,

02:49:07.310 --> 02:49:09.950
William had spent the majority of his life at sea

02:49:09.950 --> 02:49:11.600
as part of the Royal Navy.

02:49:11.600 --> 02:49:15.320
He had been made lord high admiral in 1827

02:49:15.320 --> 02:49:16.940
and inherited his brother's throne

02:49:16.940 --> 02:49:19.820
at the sprightly age of 64.

02:49:19.820 --> 02:49:22.880
Crowned on the 8th of September, 1831,

02:49:22.880 --> 02:49:25.220
King William's comparatively shored reign

02:49:25.220 --> 02:49:28.910
was nonetheless highly transformative to British society.

02:49:28.910 --> 02:49:31.520
The poor laws were updated and streamlined,

02:49:31.520 --> 02:49:33.950
centralizing their administrative function

02:49:33.950 --> 02:49:36.710
and establishing workhouses across the country.

02:49:36.710 --> 02:49:39.080
Many of these reforms set as a precedent

02:49:39.080 --> 02:49:43.160
for the modern welfare system still used in Britain today.

02:49:43.160 --> 02:49:44.600
Meanwhile, child labor,

02:49:44.600 --> 02:49:46.430
which had been allowed to run rampant

02:49:46.430 --> 02:49:49.820
and unchecked since the start of the Industrial Revolution,

02:49:49.820 --> 02:49:54.380
was officially banned, thanks to the Factory Act of 1833.

02:49:54.380 --> 02:49:56.690
King William also oversaw the passing

02:49:56.690 --> 02:49:59.660
of the Slave Abolition Act that same year,

02:49:59.660 --> 02:50:03.800
banning slavery in all its forms across the British Empire.

02:50:03.800 --> 02:50:05.060
It's worth noting, however,

02:50:05.060 --> 02:50:07.670
that the king was staunch anti-abolition

02:50:07.670 --> 02:50:10.850
and campaigned against the passing of the bill.

02:50:10.850 --> 02:50:14.120
Despite this, the new king was far less involved in politics

02:50:14.120 --> 02:50:16.160
than his brother and father before him.

02:50:16.160 --> 02:50:18.560
The crown's political influence had diminished

02:50:18.560 --> 02:50:20.300
past the point of no return.

02:50:20.300 --> 02:50:23.390
And after his failure to remove the Melbourne ministry,

02:50:23.390 --> 02:50:26.270
he resigned himself to matters away from politics

02:50:26.270 --> 02:50:27.920
for the remainder of his reign.

02:50:27.920 --> 02:50:31.520
He would be the last king to select a prime minister

02:50:31.520 --> 02:50:33.620
against the wishes of parliament.

02:50:33.620 --> 02:50:36.560
But away from the chatter and dealings of Westminster,

02:50:36.560 --> 02:50:38.090
King William's personal life

02:50:38.090 --> 02:50:40.340
was much more under his control.

02:50:40.340 --> 02:50:42.500
He was in a 20 year long partnership

02:50:42.500 --> 02:50:45.320
with Irish actress, Dorothea Bland,

02:50:45.320 --> 02:50:49.220
with whom he had 10 children, five boys and five girls.

02:50:49.220 --> 02:50:51.890
The pair appeared to have enjoyed each other's company

02:50:51.890 --> 02:50:54.080
as evident by their extended courtship

02:50:54.080 --> 02:50:56.060
and drama-free years together.

02:50:56.060 --> 02:50:58.400
William's father, King George III,

02:50:58.400 --> 02:51:00.710
was supportive of his son's relationship

02:51:00.710 --> 02:51:04.430
and bestowed onto William the title of Ranger of Bushy Park,

02:51:04.430 --> 02:51:06.398
a role which included a large residence

02:51:06.398 --> 02:51:09.920
known as Bushy House on the outskirts of London.

02:51:09.920 --> 02:51:12.920
But Dorothea Bland would never be queen

02:51:12.920 --> 02:51:15.380
as the pair split in 1811.

02:51:15.380 --> 02:51:18.140
Bland was given custody of the five girls

02:51:18.140 --> 02:51:20.510
and paid a monthly sum for their upkeep

02:51:20.510 --> 02:51:24.140
under the condition that she never returned to the stage.

02:51:24.140 --> 02:51:26.390
She, however, did return to acting,

02:51:26.390 --> 02:51:28.760
hoping to earn some extra money to pay off a debt

02:51:28.760 --> 02:51:31.010
one of her daughter's husbands had incurred.

02:51:31.010 --> 02:51:32.660
When news reached William,

02:51:32.660 --> 02:51:35.120
he stopped paying her monthly allowance,

02:51:35.120 --> 02:51:38.330
and she eventually fled to France to avoid the debtors

02:51:38.330 --> 02:51:40.010
who she'd failed to pay off.

02:51:40.010 --> 02:51:43.190
She died impoverished in 1816.

02:51:43.190 --> 02:51:46.370
Just a few years later, William searched for a proper wife

02:51:46.370 --> 02:51:49.670
concluded with his marriage to Adelaide of Saxe-Meiningen.

02:51:49.670 --> 02:51:53.210
She was of royal stock in her prime childbearing years,

02:51:53.210 --> 02:51:54.980
and it's reported that she and William

02:51:54.980 --> 02:51:57.560
became extremely fond of one another.

02:51:57.560 --> 02:51:59.870
This luck continued well into kingship,

02:51:59.870 --> 02:52:02.990
as William proved himself to be an expert diplomat,

02:52:02.990 --> 02:52:05.543
especially on the international stage.

02:52:06.500 --> 02:52:08.270
He oversaw the initial phases

02:52:08.270 --> 02:52:10.730
of the construction of the Suez Canal

02:52:10.730 --> 02:52:12.950
and stressed the importance of its ability

02:52:12.950 --> 02:52:17.060
to garner good relations between the British crown in Egypt.

02:52:17.060 --> 02:52:20.360
He also helped repair Britain's relationship with America,

02:52:20.360 --> 02:52:23.990
which had suffered immensely under King George III.

02:52:23.990 --> 02:52:26.510
At a dinner party with the American ambassador,

02:52:26.510 --> 02:52:28.700
King William loudly proclaimed his regret

02:52:28.700 --> 02:52:32.210
for not being born a free independent American.

02:52:32.210 --> 02:52:34.430
So much did he respect that nation

02:52:34.430 --> 02:52:36.830
which had given birth to George Washington,

02:52:36.830 --> 02:52:39.680
the greatest man that ever lived.

02:52:39.680 --> 02:52:43.190
Anglo American relations steadily improved under his rule,

02:52:43.190 --> 02:52:46.520
and the two nations are still close to this day.

02:52:46.520 --> 02:52:49.340
But for all his charm and diplomatic tact,

02:52:49.340 --> 02:52:52.070
he and Adelaide had no surviving children,

02:52:52.070 --> 02:52:54.440
and as such, King William was presented

02:52:54.440 --> 02:52:57.860
with a succession crisis towards the end of his life.

02:52:57.860 --> 02:53:00.470
The king was extremely fond of his niece,

02:53:00.470 --> 02:53:03.590
Princess Alexandrina Victoria of Kent,

02:53:03.590 --> 02:53:07.220
and named her as his heir during his final birthday banquet.

02:53:07.220 --> 02:53:09.770
By this time, the king was gravely ill,

02:53:09.770 --> 02:53:12.740
but wanted to survive to see his niece turn 18,

02:53:12.740 --> 02:53:15.710
ensuring that the crown was passed directly to her

02:53:15.710 --> 02:53:17.930
and not placed under a regency council

02:53:17.930 --> 02:53:20.570
as was custom for under eighteens.

02:53:20.570 --> 02:53:23.780
His last year alive was a torturous one.

02:53:23.780 --> 02:53:26.750
Princess Adelaide reportedly stayed by his side,

02:53:26.750 --> 02:53:30.560
refusing to go to bed for 10 days as his health worsened.

02:53:30.560 --> 02:53:33.290
King William IV died in the early hours

02:53:33.290 --> 02:53:36.170
of the 20th of June, 1837.

02:53:36.170 --> 02:53:40.493
He was the last Hanoverian king to rule over England.

02:53:42.017 --> 02:53:44.930
(light music)

02:53:44.930 --> 02:53:48.200
At just 18 years old, Victoria found herself

02:53:48.200 --> 02:53:52.520
at the head of the greatest empire the world had ever seen.

02:53:52.520 --> 02:53:54.530
As it was against Hanoverian law

02:53:54.530 --> 02:53:56.720
for a woman to rule over the province,

02:53:56.720 --> 02:53:58.610
the new queen was stripped of a role

02:53:58.610 --> 02:54:00.680
as ruler of the Kingdom of Hanover.

02:54:00.680 --> 02:54:03.318
However, by now, Britain had emerged

02:54:03.318 --> 02:54:06.920
as the most dominant superpower on the planet.

02:54:06.920 --> 02:54:10.460
Under her rule, the empire would reach its territorial peak,

02:54:10.460 --> 02:54:15.050
controlling 35.5 million square kilometers.

02:54:15.050 --> 02:54:16.880
It was and still stands

02:54:16.880 --> 02:54:21.170
as the largest empire ever seen in human history.

02:54:21.170 --> 02:54:23.701
On the 28th of June, 1838,

02:54:23.701 --> 02:54:26.840
400,000 people traveled to the capital

02:54:26.840 --> 02:54:29.690
to see Victoria ascend to the British throne.

02:54:29.690 --> 02:54:31.310
She became the first monarch

02:54:31.310 --> 02:54:34.310
to take up permanent residence at Buckingham Palace,

02:54:34.310 --> 02:54:36.107
which has since become the administrative

02:54:36.107 --> 02:54:38.150
and a residential headquarters

02:54:38.150 --> 02:54:40.280
for the royal family in England.

02:54:40.280 --> 02:54:42.740
But the cheer and pomp soon faded,

02:54:42.740 --> 02:54:44.690
and the start of her reign was fraught

02:54:44.690 --> 02:54:47.540
with social tension and conflict in the realm.

02:54:47.540 --> 02:54:50.690
There had been a widespread demand for electoral reform

02:54:50.690 --> 02:54:54.740
and calls for universal male suffrage ran across the kingdom

02:54:54.740 --> 02:54:58.190
as ordinary men demanded the right to vote.

02:54:58.190 --> 02:55:00.860
There were also calls to abolish the Corn Law,

02:55:00.860 --> 02:55:02.659
which heavily taxed imported grains

02:55:02.659 --> 02:55:05.060
and barley that came into the island.

02:55:05.060 --> 02:55:09.440
In 1846, the Corn Laws were repealed and free trade won out,

02:55:09.440 --> 02:55:11.720
greatly improving the standard of living,

02:55:11.720 --> 02:55:16.190
and contributing to a Victorian era boom in population.

02:55:16.190 --> 02:55:17.660
Unlike her uncle William,

02:55:17.660 --> 02:55:20.630
Queen Victoria sought to involve herself in politics

02:55:20.630 --> 02:55:23.030
far more than she really should have.

02:55:23.030 --> 02:55:25.760
Because of the laws that prohibited the English monarch

02:55:25.760 --> 02:55:29.570
from meddling in political matters, she had to get creative.

02:55:29.570 --> 02:55:32.360
The queen attempted to influence government outcome

02:55:32.360 --> 02:55:35.120
and ministerial policy through private meetings

02:55:35.120 --> 02:55:36.830
and backroom dealings,

02:55:36.830 --> 02:55:39.380
something she quickly developed a talent for.

02:55:39.380 --> 02:55:42.440
As an astute diplomat, she knew how to conduct herself

02:55:42.440 --> 02:55:45.530
in the murky political world of Victorian England,

02:55:45.530 --> 02:55:47.641
and as such, was far more successful

02:55:47.641 --> 02:55:50.540
in influencing the decision-making processes

02:55:50.540 --> 02:55:52.700
of parliament and her lords.

02:55:52.700 --> 02:55:55.447
However, she publicly maintained her image as a busy

02:55:55.447 --> 02:55:58.550
and charitable monarch who directly involved herself

02:55:58.550 --> 02:56:01.340
in a number of public works projects.

02:56:01.340 --> 02:56:03.110
Under her husband's patronage,

02:56:03.110 --> 02:56:07.160
the first World Fair was held in London in 1851.

02:56:07.160 --> 02:56:09.920
Prince Albert directly oversaw the construction

02:56:09.920 --> 02:56:12.830
of the Crystal Palace, which stood in Sydenham

02:56:12.830 --> 02:56:15.320
until it burned down, and welcomed exhibits

02:56:15.320 --> 02:56:19.490
from all over the empire in a show of unity and strength.

02:56:19.490 --> 02:56:22.430
But while the World Fair may have bolstered these ideas

02:56:22.430 --> 02:56:23.870
of togetherness at home,

02:56:23.870 --> 02:56:26.720
the reality of things was very different.

02:56:26.720 --> 02:56:30.140
In 1857, the Crimean War broke out

02:56:30.140 --> 02:56:32.540
as a result of growing tensions on the continent

02:56:32.540 --> 02:56:37.100
between emerging superpowers and old empires in the east.

02:56:37.100 --> 02:56:40.100
Britain chose to fight for the Ottomans against Russia,

02:56:40.100 --> 02:56:42.950
wanting to maintain the balance of power in Europe

02:56:42.950 --> 02:56:44.930
and limit Russian expansion.

02:56:44.930 --> 02:56:47.600
Despite the war's unpopularity at home,

02:56:47.600 --> 02:56:50.870
Britain and her allies were eventually victorious,

02:56:50.870 --> 02:56:53.000
and Europe was once again stable,

02:56:53.000 --> 02:56:55.520
but before any celebrations could be had,

02:56:55.520 --> 02:56:58.862
the Indian mutiny called the army's attention once more

02:56:58.862 --> 02:57:00.590
and resulted in the British

02:57:00.590 --> 02:57:03.230
taking complete administrative control

02:57:03.230 --> 02:57:05.690
over the sub-continent of India.

02:57:05.690 --> 02:57:07.850
As a result, Queen Victoria

02:57:07.850 --> 02:57:11.570
officially became Victoria, Empress of India.

02:57:11.570 --> 02:57:13.220
Previously, the Indian government

02:57:13.220 --> 02:57:16.220
had worked alongside the British East India Company

02:57:16.220 --> 02:57:18.200
in the day-to-day ruling of the region.

02:57:18.200 --> 02:57:20.810
However, after the mutineers were put down

02:57:20.810 --> 02:57:22.490
and the rebellion quashed,

02:57:22.490 --> 02:57:25.250
the British government ousted both the Indians

02:57:25.250 --> 02:57:26.960
and the East India Company

02:57:26.960 --> 02:57:29.150
from their administrative positions

02:57:29.150 --> 02:57:31.340
and took control for themselves.

02:57:31.340 --> 02:57:34.040
During a proclamation to the Indian people,

02:57:34.040 --> 02:57:37.250
the queen promised her new subjects rights and freedoms

02:57:37.250 --> 02:57:39.260
equal to that of the British public.

02:57:39.260 --> 02:57:41.810
These rights were not always maintained,

02:57:41.810 --> 02:57:45.110
and her proclamation was referred to many times

02:57:45.110 --> 02:57:48.620
during the long fight for Indian independence.

02:57:48.620 --> 02:57:50.510
Back in London, Queen Victoria

02:57:50.510 --> 02:57:53.330
and Prince Albert had been steadily reproducing,

02:57:53.330 --> 02:57:56.120
giving birth to a total of nine children,

02:57:56.120 --> 02:57:59.330
all of whom married into European royal families.

02:57:59.330 --> 02:58:00.740
This earned the queen the nickname

02:58:00.740 --> 02:58:03.200
the Grandmother of Europe.

02:58:03.200 --> 02:58:07.010
The death of Albert in 1860 devastated Victoria,

02:58:07.010 --> 02:58:09.470
who fell into a prolonged period of mourning.

02:58:09.470 --> 02:58:11.570
The previously active monarch

02:58:11.570 --> 02:58:13.370
was seldom seen by her cabinet,

02:58:13.370 --> 02:58:16.880
and for a time disappeared completely from the public stage.

02:58:16.880 --> 02:58:19.880
In her absence, British republicanism grew,

02:58:19.880 --> 02:58:22.010
and there were real murmurs in the capital

02:58:22.010 --> 02:58:26.000
of a potential revolution against the royal institutions,

02:58:26.000 --> 02:58:27.860
but these amounted to nothing.

02:58:27.860 --> 02:58:29.840
She would've eventually compose herself

02:58:29.840 --> 02:58:33.410
and resume a life in the public eye, but continued to mourn,

02:58:33.410 --> 02:58:35.990
wearing black until the day she died.

02:58:35.990 --> 02:58:39.410
The queen ruled for 40 more years without her prince,

02:58:39.410 --> 02:58:41.750
and in that time, her kingdom erupted

02:58:41.750 --> 02:58:45.770
as a center of industry, art, and science in the world.

02:58:45.770 --> 02:58:49.370
Factories dominated the landscape from London to Glasgow,

02:58:49.370 --> 02:58:51.830
as new cities tripled in size.

02:58:51.830 --> 02:58:54.140
Places like Birmingham and Manchester,

02:58:54.140 --> 02:58:57.380
which had before only been minor villages and settlements,

02:58:57.380 --> 02:59:01.850
were now the second and third largest cities in the country.

02:59:01.850 --> 02:59:04.880
Great writers produced some of their finest works.

02:59:04.880 --> 02:59:06.830
Bram Stoker wrote "Dracula,"

02:59:06.830 --> 02:59:09.590
Sir Arthur Conan Doyle wrote "Sherlock Holmes,"

02:59:09.590 --> 02:59:12.590
and Charles Dickens published some of the greatest works

02:59:12.590 --> 02:59:13.814
of literary fiction

02:59:13.814 --> 02:59:16.970
in the English language since Shakespeare.

02:59:16.970 --> 02:59:18.920
Advancements in science and medicine

02:59:18.920 --> 02:59:21.650
also progressed massively under her rule.

02:59:21.650 --> 02:59:24.650
Darwin published his theories on the evolution of man,

02:59:24.650 --> 02:59:27.260
Alexander Graham Bell invented the telephone,

02:59:27.260 --> 02:59:30.920
and germ theory became the leading idea that pushes medicine

02:59:30.920 --> 02:59:33.950
and the prevention of disease forwards.

02:59:33.950 --> 02:59:37.040
After King George III, Queen Victoria stands

02:59:37.040 --> 02:59:40.610
as the second longest reigning monarch in British history.

02:59:40.610 --> 02:59:42.560
Her golden and diamond jubilees

02:59:42.560 --> 02:59:44.900
were a time of great celebration,

02:59:44.900 --> 02:59:48.590
and her 63 year reign remains an iconic chapter

02:59:48.590 --> 02:59:52.700
in British history, referred to as the Victorian era.

02:59:52.700 --> 02:59:55.640
In 1901 while on a trip to Osborne house

02:59:55.640 --> 02:59:56.690
in the Isle of Wight,

02:59:56.690 --> 03:00:00.890
Queen Victoria died from a stroke at 81 years of age.

03:00:00.890 --> 03:00:03.350
Her death marked the end of the House of Hanover

03:00:03.350 --> 03:00:05.660
and its rule on the British Isles.

03:00:05.660 --> 03:00:08.570
With the throne now passed onto her son, Edward,

03:00:08.570 --> 03:00:11.270
Britain had to leave its ancient queen behind

03:00:11.270 --> 03:00:14.540
as it ran headfirst into the modern age.

03:00:14.540 --> 03:00:16.670
Perhaps if it knew what that meant,

03:00:16.670 --> 03:00:19.223
it might not have done so as willingly.

03:00:20.581 --> 03:00:23.600
(dramatic music)

03:00:23.600 --> 03:00:26.720
As the first of the modern monarchs of Britain,

03:00:26.720 --> 03:00:29.750
King Edward VII exemplified many of the tropes

03:00:29.750 --> 03:00:32.810
and ideas we associate with the royal family today.

03:00:32.810 --> 03:00:34.850
Throughout his time as the prince of Wales

03:00:34.850 --> 03:00:37.280
and later as king, he traveled extensively

03:00:37.280 --> 03:00:39.500
throughout the country and the world,

03:00:39.500 --> 03:00:42.110
performing traditional ceremonies to the public

03:00:42.110 --> 03:00:45.530
and acting as a figurehead to institutions and charities.

03:00:45.530 --> 03:00:47.600
King Edward oversaw the crown shift

03:00:47.600 --> 03:00:50.150
to being a vehicle for public philanthropy

03:00:50.150 --> 03:00:53.690
as he opened new bridges, schools, and hospitals

03:00:53.690 --> 03:00:56.720
in an effort to modernize the role of the royal family.

03:00:56.720 --> 03:00:58.750
Since monarchical influence in politics

03:00:58.750 --> 03:01:01.400
was now legally prohibited,

03:01:01.400 --> 03:01:03.920
King Edward took a leaf out of his mother's book

03:01:03.920 --> 03:01:06.770
and took to the shadows to impose his will.

03:01:06.770 --> 03:01:10.520
He reinvented royal diplomacy, fostering good relations

03:01:10.520 --> 03:01:12.860
with many of the powerful elite in Europe,

03:01:12.860 --> 03:01:16.790
most notably the French, for whom he was called Peacemaker,

03:01:16.790 --> 03:01:20.240
but he was not always successful in these endeavors.

03:01:20.240 --> 03:01:23.870
He married Alexandra of Denmark in 1863,

03:01:23.870 --> 03:01:26.060
and together they had six children.

03:01:26.060 --> 03:01:27.530
Like in the reign of his mother,

03:01:27.530 --> 03:01:31.340
King Edward ruled over an island that was rapidly changing.

03:01:31.340 --> 03:01:33.830
Scientific and technological advancements

03:01:33.830 --> 03:01:36.410
doubled year on year as man took flight.

03:01:36.410 --> 03:01:38.870
Wireless signals were sent across the Atlantic,

03:01:38.870 --> 03:01:41.060
and the South Pole was reached by humans

03:01:41.060 --> 03:01:43.670
for the first time in human history.

03:01:43.670 --> 03:01:47.000
But for all its developments in science and culture,

03:01:47.000 --> 03:01:49.490
the Edwardian era is best remembered

03:01:49.490 --> 03:01:51.710
for the rise of socialism.

03:01:51.710 --> 03:01:54.440
All across the world, the working classes

03:01:54.440 --> 03:01:57.410
had benefited from increased education and literacy,

03:01:57.410 --> 03:02:00.260
and as such, at the start of the century,

03:02:00.260 --> 03:02:04.490
a huge number of poor British subjects had become educated

03:02:04.490 --> 03:02:07.910
and increasingly vocal about their rights as humans.

03:02:07.910 --> 03:02:11.750
Murmurs of independence rang throughout Britain's colonies,

03:02:11.750 --> 03:02:13.310
and strong attempts were made

03:02:13.310 --> 03:02:15.920
to erode the longstanding class divides

03:02:15.920 --> 03:02:17.510
that had kept hold in England

03:02:17.510 --> 03:02:21.620
since the reign of King Egbert, all those years before.

03:02:21.620 --> 03:02:24.080
At the time of his death in 1910,

03:02:24.080 --> 03:02:27.548
King Edward VII faced a constitutional crisis

03:02:27.548 --> 03:02:31.190
spurred on by socialism and its ideals.

03:02:31.190 --> 03:02:33.020
A year prior, the Liberal Party

03:02:33.020 --> 03:02:36.260
had enacted the People's Budget, an unprecedented set

03:02:36.260 --> 03:02:38.603
of new taxes against the richest in the realm

03:02:38.603 --> 03:02:39.590
that was intended

03:02:39.590 --> 03:02:42.797
to help fund social housing projects across Britain.

03:02:42.797 --> 03:02:44.140
The House of Commons passed it,

03:02:44.140 --> 03:02:46.790
but when it came to the House of Lords,

03:02:46.790 --> 03:02:50.600
an unelected council who sit for life, it was vetoed.

03:02:50.600 --> 03:02:52.940
Technically speaking, the House of Lords

03:02:52.940 --> 03:02:55.220
had every right to do this.

03:02:55.220 --> 03:02:57.620
But there had been a longstanding honor code

03:02:57.620 --> 03:02:59.390
between the two branches of government

03:02:59.390 --> 03:03:01.640
that essentially said the House of Lords

03:03:01.640 --> 03:03:04.250
was not supposed to amend money bills,

03:03:04.250 --> 03:03:07.280
as only the House of Commons had the power to decide

03:03:07.280 --> 03:03:09.230
on the monarch's resources.

03:03:09.230 --> 03:03:11.780
Their block of the bill, while not illegal,

03:03:11.780 --> 03:03:14.461
was in bad spirit, and further emphasized

03:03:14.461 --> 03:03:17.300
the growing social divide in the kingdom.

03:03:17.300 --> 03:03:20.150
Many in parliament believed their system of government

03:03:20.150 --> 03:03:21.830
needed to be reformed.

03:03:21.830 --> 03:03:25.070
It was under this unrest that King Edward VII died

03:03:25.070 --> 03:03:27.618
on the 6th of May, 1910.

03:03:27.618 --> 03:03:30.080
He left the throne to his son, George,

03:03:30.080 --> 03:03:33.170
who was to inherit not just a fractured kingdom,

03:03:33.170 --> 03:03:37.343
but a planet on the verge of tearing itself apart.

03:03:38.205 --> 03:03:41.510
(light music)

03:03:41.510 --> 03:03:44.091
But before he was accosted by arms, races,

03:03:44.091 --> 03:03:48.170
and constitutional crises, George was a young man

03:03:48.170 --> 03:03:50.630
who was not always meant to be king.

03:03:50.630 --> 03:03:52.370
The second son of King Edward,

03:03:52.370 --> 03:03:55.040
he spent his youth serving abroad in the Royal Navy,

03:03:55.040 --> 03:03:58.580
enjoying his freedom and a reveling in the life of a prince.

03:03:58.580 --> 03:04:01.040
However, fate had other plans for him,

03:04:01.040 --> 03:04:03.860
and after his brother and the heir to the British throne,

03:04:03.860 --> 03:04:08.240
Prince Albert, died unexpectedly in 1892,

03:04:08.240 --> 03:04:10.580
George was hurriedly recalled to Britain

03:04:10.580 --> 03:04:12.500
to begin a life of preparation

03:04:12.500 --> 03:04:16.190
and education to eventually ascend to the British throne.

03:04:16.190 --> 03:04:18.110
He married his brother's fiance,

03:04:18.110 --> 03:04:20.450
Princess Victoria, Mary of Teck,

03:04:20.450 --> 03:04:22.790
and together the pair had six children.

03:04:22.790 --> 03:04:25.400
In 1910 with a passing of his father,

03:04:25.400 --> 03:04:28.940
George was crowned king emperor of the United Kingdom

03:04:28.940 --> 03:04:33.170
on the 22nd of June to joyous celebrations in the capital.

03:04:33.170 --> 03:04:34.790
The constitutional crisis

03:04:34.790 --> 03:04:37.040
that had defined the end of his father's reign

03:04:37.040 --> 03:04:41.030
was quickly dealt with thanks to the Parliament Act of 1911,

03:04:41.030 --> 03:04:42.620
which saw the House of Commons

03:04:42.620 --> 03:04:46.640
establish legal supremacy over the House of Lords.

03:04:46.640 --> 03:04:48.828
England itself was experiencing a period

03:04:48.828 --> 03:04:51.920
of civil unrest and social upheaval.

03:04:51.920 --> 03:04:55.190
The socialist ideals that had been gaining popularity

03:04:55.190 --> 03:04:57.440
now had Europe in a vice grip.

03:04:57.440 --> 03:05:00.410
Irish politicians began calling for home rule

03:05:00.410 --> 03:05:02.630
and separation from the British Kingdom,

03:05:02.630 --> 03:05:05.780
while socialist politicians grew in numbers, power,

03:05:05.780 --> 03:05:08.090
and ambition within the House of Commons.

03:05:08.090 --> 03:05:11.390
But all this turmoil was about to take a back seat

03:05:11.390 --> 03:05:14.120
as Europe erupted into warfare.

03:05:14.120 --> 03:05:16.910
The First World War had begun.

03:05:16.910 --> 03:05:19.490
On the 4th of August, 1914,

03:05:19.490 --> 03:05:21.680
four years after his coronation,

03:05:21.680 --> 03:05:25.190
King George V declared war on Germany.

03:05:25.190 --> 03:05:28.557
On the day of the declaration, the king wrote in his diary,

03:05:28.557 --> 03:05:32.840
"I held a council at 10:45 to declare war with Germany.

03:05:32.840 --> 03:05:37.040
It is a terrible catastrophe, but it is not our fault.

03:05:37.040 --> 03:05:40.310
Please to God, it may soon be over."

03:05:40.310 --> 03:05:43.910
It was not, and the war raged for four years,

03:05:43.910 --> 03:05:45.770
as England and her allies battled

03:05:45.770 --> 03:05:47.720
against the central powers.

03:05:47.720 --> 03:05:49.970
It was a conflict that would claim the lives

03:05:49.970 --> 03:05:52.640
of around 40 million people

03:05:52.640 --> 03:05:55.310
with fighting happening all over the world.

03:05:55.310 --> 03:05:58.820
The new machines which had taken society into the modern age

03:05:58.820 --> 03:06:02.060
now brought death on an industrial scale,

03:06:02.060 --> 03:06:05.480
and the war had a profound impact on the British psyche,

03:06:05.480 --> 03:06:09.410
inflicting scars that to this day have yet to heal.

03:06:09.410 --> 03:06:11.570
Even the king could not escape this.

03:06:11.570 --> 03:06:14.150
To him, the war was personal.

03:06:14.150 --> 03:06:17.540
The Russian czar and the German kaiser were his cousins

03:06:17.540 --> 03:06:21.143
as they shared ancestry to Queen Victoria and Prince Albert.

03:06:21.980 --> 03:06:23.600
The men had grown up together,

03:06:23.600 --> 03:06:26.870
spending summers at Buckingham Palace playing make believe

03:06:26.870 --> 03:06:30.110
and fighting in homemade trenches in the palace gardens.

03:06:30.110 --> 03:06:33.680
Now, their countries played out these childhood fantasies

03:06:33.680 --> 03:06:35.900
with unforgiving brutality.

03:06:35.900 --> 03:06:37.976
Consequently, the English King George

03:06:37.976 --> 03:06:42.320
still carried a German surname, Saxe-Coburg and Gotha.

03:06:42.320 --> 03:06:44.990
As anti-German sentiment skyrocketed,

03:06:44.990 --> 03:06:47.810
the king drew ire for his perceived connections

03:06:47.810 --> 03:06:49.040
to their new enemy.

03:06:49.040 --> 03:06:51.410
Famous English writer, HG Wells,

03:06:51.410 --> 03:06:54.678
wrote about Britain's alien and uninspiring court

03:06:54.678 --> 03:06:56.450
in reference to the king.

03:06:56.450 --> 03:06:58.227
George responded to the author,

03:06:58.227 --> 03:07:02.540
"I may be uninspiring, but I'll be damned if I'm alien."

03:07:02.540 --> 03:07:04.790
To appease British nationalists,

03:07:04.790 --> 03:07:07.430
King George V changed his surname

03:07:07.430 --> 03:07:09.830
from the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha

03:07:09.830 --> 03:07:14.660
to the House of Windsor on the 17th of July, 1917.

03:07:14.660 --> 03:07:17.630
That same year, the Russians who had allied with Britain

03:07:17.630 --> 03:07:19.940
during the conflict had capitulated,

03:07:19.940 --> 03:07:23.930
and Russia was overcome with fervor of revolution.

03:07:23.930 --> 03:07:25.670
The downtrodden Russian people

03:07:25.670 --> 03:07:27.650
overthrew the czar and his family,

03:07:27.650 --> 03:07:31.010
imprisoning him and establishing the Soviet Union.

03:07:31.010 --> 03:07:33.890
Not only was the czar King George's cousin,

03:07:33.890 --> 03:07:37.370
but the two were dear friends, and George made plans

03:07:37.370 --> 03:07:39.770
to rescue his cousin from the revolutionaries

03:07:39.770 --> 03:07:41.720
that had arrested him and his family.

03:07:41.720 --> 03:07:44.960
But that same fervor that had led to revolution in Russia

03:07:44.960 --> 03:07:47.510
was beginning to bubble in Britain.

03:07:47.510 --> 03:07:49.310
Compounding social issues

03:07:49.310 --> 03:07:52.580
had decreased the quality of life in the country so much

03:07:52.580 --> 03:07:55.190
that there was a genuine fear of revolution

03:07:55.190 --> 03:07:58.220
similar to that of the Russian communists.

03:07:58.220 --> 03:08:00.770
King George worried that bringing the Romanovs

03:08:00.770 --> 03:08:03.193
who represented all the gaudy excesses

03:08:03.193 --> 03:08:06.890
and societal disconnect between a king and his people

03:08:06.890 --> 03:08:08.840
would look bad on the British crown.

03:08:08.840 --> 03:08:10.550
Czar Nicholas and his family

03:08:10.550 --> 03:08:13.220
were gunned down by the revolutionaries,

03:08:13.220 --> 03:08:15.980
and Russia would never have a king again.

03:08:15.980 --> 03:08:20.150
By 1918, the war was over, the armistice was signed,

03:08:20.150 --> 03:08:22.760
and Germany sent their kaiser into exile.

03:08:22.760 --> 03:08:26.930
Of the great European monarchies, only a few now stood.

03:08:26.930 --> 03:08:28.850
King George was alone.

03:08:28.850 --> 03:08:31.460
The later half of George's reign was dominated

03:08:31.460 --> 03:08:35.180
by the growing threat of socialism and its offshoots.

03:08:35.180 --> 03:08:37.630
Fascism, republicanism, communism,

03:08:37.630 --> 03:08:41.180
these political ideologies grew in popularity

03:08:41.180 --> 03:08:43.760
and promised the working classes of the world

03:08:43.760 --> 03:08:46.730
a chance at retribution and equality.

03:08:46.730 --> 03:08:49.610
The world had seen what communists were capable of

03:08:49.610 --> 03:08:51.320
during the Russian Revolution,

03:08:51.320 --> 03:08:54.110
and anti-communist sentiment perforated

03:08:54.110 --> 03:08:56.690
throughout the British upper class.

03:08:56.690 --> 03:08:58.250
The socialist labor movement

03:08:58.250 --> 03:09:00.950
had gained massive popularity in parliament,

03:09:00.950 --> 03:09:03.800
but instead of an all-out revolt like in Russia,

03:09:03.800 --> 03:09:06.080
they sought to work alongside the king

03:09:06.080 --> 03:09:09.170
to introduce more democratic measures to the island.

03:09:09.170 --> 03:09:11.210
The king submitted to their demands,

03:09:11.210 --> 03:09:14.210
and together they revamped the role of the British monarchy,

03:09:14.210 --> 03:09:17.750
bringing it closer to the public and the working class.

03:09:17.750 --> 03:09:21.800
In 1926, King George became a central figure

03:09:21.800 --> 03:09:25.190
in the push for self-governance in the British dominions.

03:09:25.190 --> 03:09:29.030
In 1931, the statute of Westminster gave territories

03:09:29.030 --> 03:09:31.629
like Australia and Canada greater autonomy

03:09:31.629 --> 03:09:33.260
and self-governance,

03:09:33.260 --> 03:09:36.530
while still keeping them firmly under the British crown.

03:09:36.530 --> 03:09:39.680
The king also oversaw Britain's financial recovery

03:09:39.680 --> 03:09:43.100
after the 1929 stock market crash.

03:09:43.100 --> 03:09:45.890
He encouraged the formation of a national government

03:09:45.890 --> 03:09:48.230
and agreed to reduce the civil list,

03:09:48.230 --> 03:09:50.330
essentially lowering the number of people

03:09:50.330 --> 03:09:51.800
on the government's payroll.

03:09:51.800 --> 03:09:54.260
All of this helped in stabilizing the economy,

03:09:54.260 --> 03:09:56.997
and as a result, Britain was able to maintain peace

03:09:56.997 --> 03:09:59.180
and a basic standard of living

03:09:59.180 --> 03:10:00.885
during a time when the entire world

03:10:00.885 --> 03:10:03.920
was reeling from economic hardship.

03:10:03.920 --> 03:10:06.710
He was deeply suspicious of the Nazi party,

03:10:06.710 --> 03:10:08.900
which had been rising in power in Germany

03:10:08.900 --> 03:10:10.910
following the First World War.

03:10:10.910 --> 03:10:15.320
In 1934, he told the German ambassador Leopold von Hoesch

03:10:15.320 --> 03:10:18.530
that should Germany continue on its current trajectory,

03:10:18.530 --> 03:10:20.810
there would be a war in Europe once again

03:10:20.810 --> 03:10:22.780
in the next 10 years.

03:10:22.780 --> 03:10:25.820
He was wrong, but only just.

03:10:25.820 --> 03:10:29.330
In 1935, a year before his death,

03:10:29.330 --> 03:10:31.730
George celebrated his silver jubilee

03:10:31.730 --> 03:10:33.860
to cheering crowds in the capital.

03:10:33.860 --> 03:10:36.470
He was a popular and well loved king.

03:10:36.470 --> 03:10:38.810
The people respected him for his hard work

03:10:38.810 --> 03:10:40.550
and commitment to the empire,

03:10:40.550 --> 03:10:43.700
as well as his charity and care to the British public.

03:10:43.700 --> 03:10:46.737
As crowds waved him on, he reportedly said,

03:10:46.737 --> 03:10:48.590
"I cannot understand it.

03:10:48.590 --> 03:10:52.190
After all, I'm only a very ordinary sort of fellow."

03:10:52.190 --> 03:10:54.980
His relationship with his eldest son, Edward,

03:10:54.980 --> 03:10:57.350
deteriorated towards the end of his life,

03:10:57.350 --> 03:10:59.330
as he grew increasingly disappointed

03:10:59.330 --> 03:11:01.580
at Edward's inability to settle down

03:11:01.580 --> 03:11:04.130
and his continued affairs with married women.

03:11:04.130 --> 03:11:08.000
In contrast, he was deeply close to his second son Albert

03:11:08.000 --> 03:11:10.100
and became a dotting grandfather

03:11:10.100 --> 03:11:12.710
to Albert's daughter, Prince Elizabeth,

03:11:12.710 --> 03:11:15.800
who referred to him as Grandpa England.

03:11:15.800 --> 03:11:19.707
In 1935, he said this of his eldest son, Edward.

03:11:19.707 --> 03:11:22.082
"After I am dead, the boy will ruin himself

03:11:22.082 --> 03:11:24.380
within 12 months.

03:11:24.380 --> 03:11:27.410
I pray to God he does not marry and have children,

03:11:27.410 --> 03:11:29.630
and that nothing stands in the way of Bertie

03:11:29.630 --> 03:11:31.520
and Lilibet and the throne."

03:11:31.520 --> 03:11:35.450
On the evening of the 15th of January, 1936,

03:11:35.450 --> 03:11:38.840
King George took to his bedroom complaining of a cold.

03:11:38.840 --> 03:11:40.430
He never reemerged.

03:11:40.430 --> 03:11:43.940
Five days later when it was clear the king was going to die,

03:11:43.940 --> 03:11:46.730
his physician administered a mild sedative,

03:11:46.730 --> 03:11:49.700
intending to peacefully end the king's life.

03:11:49.700 --> 03:11:52.580
He argued that he wanted to preserve the monarch's dignity

03:11:52.580 --> 03:11:55.520
and spare him and his family any more suffering.

03:11:55.520 --> 03:11:59.630
It was decided that he would be killed by 11:55 PM

03:11:59.630 --> 03:12:02.950
to ensure that the news broke in time for the morning papers

03:12:02.950 --> 03:12:06.980
and not the less inappropriate evening journals.

03:12:06.980 --> 03:12:09.560
Against the king's personal wishes,

03:12:09.560 --> 03:12:12.830
the British crown was passed on to his eldest son,

03:12:12.830 --> 03:12:15.629
Edward, Prince of Wales.

03:12:15.629 --> 03:12:19.250
(uplifting music)

03:12:19.250 --> 03:12:21.890
As the second monarch of the House of Windsor,

03:12:21.890 --> 03:12:23.210
there were many in the kingdom

03:12:23.210 --> 03:12:26.540
who hoped that the crown would prove a stabilizing influence

03:12:26.540 --> 03:12:28.820
on the eccentric Prince Edward.

03:12:28.820 --> 03:12:30.080
It did not.

03:12:30.080 --> 03:12:32.030
The new king showed great impatience

03:12:32.030 --> 03:12:35.360
at following royal protocol and caused major concern

03:12:35.360 --> 03:12:38.240
amongst the political factions of Westminster

03:12:38.240 --> 03:12:40.040
for his complete disregard

03:12:40.040 --> 03:12:43.040
for established constitutional conventions.

03:12:43.040 --> 03:12:45.950
He caused a serious constitutional crisis

03:12:45.950 --> 03:12:47.690
only a month into his rule

03:12:47.690 --> 03:12:50.450
after he proposed to marry Wallis Simpson,

03:12:50.450 --> 03:12:53.840
an American woman who had divorced twice already.

03:12:53.840 --> 03:12:56.930
The British prime minister himself opposed the marriage,

03:12:56.930 --> 03:12:58.850
arguing that a twice divorced woman

03:12:58.850 --> 03:13:01.610
with two living husbands was not a politically

03:13:01.610 --> 03:13:05.750
or socially acceptable person to have as queen consort.

03:13:05.750 --> 03:13:07.730
Furthermore, his proposed marriage

03:13:07.730 --> 03:13:09.230
would jeopardize his position

03:13:09.230 --> 03:13:11.030
as the head of the Church of England,

03:13:11.030 --> 03:13:13.580
which forbade marrying a divorcee

03:13:13.580 --> 03:13:15.800
if their ex-partner was still alive.

03:13:15.800 --> 03:13:17.840
It became clear that if king went through

03:13:17.840 --> 03:13:20.297
with the marriage to Wallis, the prime minister

03:13:20.297 --> 03:13:23.420
and his cabinet would retire and protest.

03:13:23.420 --> 03:13:26.270
This was serious, as it would ruin his status

03:13:26.270 --> 03:13:28.640
as a politically neutral monarch

03:13:28.640 --> 03:13:30.950
and could potentially draw opposition

03:13:30.950 --> 03:13:32.570
calling for the total removal

03:13:32.570 --> 03:13:35.030
of the royal institution as a whole.

03:13:35.030 --> 03:13:38.450
King Edward would have to choose between love or duty.

03:13:38.450 --> 03:13:39.920
He chose love.

03:13:39.920 --> 03:13:43.310
After only 326 days on the throne,

03:13:43.310 --> 03:13:45.620
King Edward VIII abdicated.

03:13:45.620 --> 03:13:47.840
Unknowingly, he had given his late father

03:13:47.840 --> 03:13:50.150
the very thing he had wished for.

03:13:50.150 --> 03:13:54.298
Prince Albert now would be king of Britain and her empire.

03:13:54.298 --> 03:13:57.048
(ethereal music)

03:13:58.610 --> 03:14:00.350
Upon his secession to the throne,

03:14:00.350 --> 03:14:02.990
Prince Albert chose to adopt regnal name

03:14:02.990 --> 03:14:05.870
and was thereafter known as King George VI.

03:14:05.870 --> 03:14:10.520
He was crowned on the 12th of May, 1937 to much popularity,

03:14:10.520 --> 03:14:11.720
but behind the scenes,

03:14:11.720 --> 03:14:14.660
the smiling king rejected his new position.

03:14:14.660 --> 03:14:16.940
He wrote in his diary that after hearing the news

03:14:16.940 --> 03:14:19.040
of his brother's decision to abdicate,

03:14:19.040 --> 03:14:21.950
he broke down and wept like a child.

03:14:21.950 --> 03:14:25.370
Rumors spread across the country that the new King George

03:14:25.370 --> 03:14:28.460
was physically and mentally unfit to rule.

03:14:28.460 --> 03:14:30.290
This is in some ways true.

03:14:30.290 --> 03:14:32.960
King George had a speech impediment and a stutter,

03:14:32.960 --> 03:14:34.370
not the kind of trade you want

03:14:34.370 --> 03:14:37.430
when you need to portray yourself as a strong figurehead.

03:14:37.430 --> 03:14:39.860
He frequently saw a speech therapist

03:14:39.860 --> 03:14:41.210
who was able to coach the king

03:14:41.210 --> 03:14:42.770
through his public engagements,

03:14:42.770 --> 03:14:45.140
and in all surviving recordings of the king,

03:14:45.140 --> 03:14:49.190
there is almost no noticeable stammer to be heard.

03:14:49.190 --> 03:14:52.820
- The queen and I are very happy

03:14:52.820 --> 03:14:56.600
to be in Scotland once more.

03:14:56.600 --> 03:14:58.430
- [Instructor] During the first years of his reign,

03:14:58.430 --> 03:15:00.530
King George toured in North America

03:15:00.530 --> 03:15:03.320
in an effort to bring the isolated Americans closer

03:15:03.320 --> 03:15:04.700
to the issues in Europe.

03:15:04.700 --> 03:15:07.700
You see, King George, along with the rest of Europe,

03:15:07.700 --> 03:15:09.560
knew that war was imminent.

03:15:09.560 --> 03:15:11.720
He was forced to publicly support

03:15:11.720 --> 03:15:13.970
British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain's

03:15:13.970 --> 03:15:17.300
policy of appeasement, even bringing the prime minister

03:15:17.300 --> 03:15:19.850
onto the balcony of Buckingham Palace

03:15:19.850 --> 03:15:22.310
in an extraordinary show of unity.

03:15:22.310 --> 03:15:24.410
But it was increasingly clear

03:15:24.410 --> 03:15:28.160
that peace in our time wasn't going to last very long.

03:15:28.160 --> 03:15:30.440
The king was well received in the US,

03:15:30.440 --> 03:15:33.410
and he was successful in shoring up American support

03:15:33.410 --> 03:15:35.780
in any upcoming conflicts.

03:15:35.780 --> 03:15:40.780
War broke out in Europe in 1939 after Hitler invaded Poland

03:15:40.820 --> 03:15:44.090
and prompted Britain to respond in the defense of her ally.

03:15:44.090 --> 03:15:45.227
Throughout the conflict,

03:15:45.227 --> 03:15:47.060
the king and queen decided to stay

03:15:47.060 --> 03:15:49.970
at the royal residence of Buckingham Palace

03:15:49.970 --> 03:15:53.420
as a sign of unity and solidarity with the English people,

03:15:53.420 --> 03:15:56.450
a decision that made them wildly popular.

03:15:56.450 --> 03:15:58.550
As London suffered through the blitz,

03:15:58.550 --> 03:16:00.620
the king and queen hunkered down,

03:16:00.620 --> 03:16:02.690
narrowly escaping death themselves

03:16:02.690 --> 03:16:06.680
as two German bombs landed in the palace gardens one night.

03:16:06.680 --> 03:16:09.620
They were subject to British rationing restrictions,

03:16:09.620 --> 03:16:11.150
just like everyone else,

03:16:11.150 --> 03:16:14.330
and were looked at around the world as model rulers

03:16:14.330 --> 03:16:16.700
who shared in their subject's suffering.

03:16:16.700 --> 03:16:20.600
His daughter, Princess Elizabeth, even enlisted in the army,

03:16:20.600 --> 03:16:24.350
mending Jeeps as part of the auxiliary territorial service.

03:16:24.350 --> 03:16:26.480
Unsurprisingly, Neville Chamberlain

03:16:26.480 --> 03:16:28.340
lost the ensuing election

03:16:28.340 --> 03:16:31.280
and Winston Churchill took over as prime minister.

03:16:31.280 --> 03:16:34.550
While King George was initially hesitant of Churchill,

03:16:34.550 --> 03:16:38.360
the two quickly developed the closest personal relationship

03:16:38.360 --> 03:16:40.130
in modern British history

03:16:40.130 --> 03:16:42.890
between a monarch and a prime minister.

03:16:42.890 --> 03:16:45.740
Every Tuesday for four and a half years,

03:16:45.740 --> 03:16:48.200
the two men met to privately eat dinner

03:16:48.200 --> 03:16:51.860
and discuss the war with unparalleled frankness.

03:16:51.860 --> 03:16:53.750
In the meantime, the king and queen

03:16:53.750 --> 03:16:56.360
would regularly make visits to bombed out houses

03:16:56.360 --> 03:16:58.070
and factories around the country,

03:16:58.070 --> 03:16:59.870
boosting morale as they went.

03:16:59.870 --> 03:17:03.260
King George even visited the army in France, Italy,

03:17:03.260 --> 03:17:05.210
North Africa, and Holland,

03:17:05.210 --> 03:17:07.190
and the British king became a symbol

03:17:07.190 --> 03:17:10.160
of national resistance across the globe.

03:17:10.160 --> 03:17:13.430
In 1945, the war was over.

03:17:13.430 --> 03:17:16.970
Guns ceased to fire and bombs stopped being dropped.

03:17:16.970 --> 03:17:18.860
Britain and her allies had won.

03:17:18.860 --> 03:17:20.120
During celebrations,

03:17:20.120 --> 03:17:23.007
crowds gathered outside Buckingham Palace chanting,

03:17:23.007 --> 03:17:24.500
"We want the king."

03:17:24.500 --> 03:17:26.450
King George gave them what they wanted,

03:17:26.450 --> 03:17:29.900
and echoing his actions almost six years ago,

03:17:29.900 --> 03:17:31.940
he brought Prime Minister Churchill

03:17:31.940 --> 03:17:33.980
onto the balcony to join him.

03:17:33.980 --> 03:17:37.040
This time, however, peace would last.

03:17:37.040 --> 03:17:39.440
King George even spoke at the first assembly

03:17:39.440 --> 03:17:40.910
of the United Nations,

03:17:40.910 --> 03:17:42.950
which was held in London a year later.

03:17:42.950 --> 03:17:46.220
But while the war had strengthened his popularity at home,

03:17:46.220 --> 03:17:49.160
it had come at a monumental cost.

03:17:49.160 --> 03:17:51.920
Britain and her empire was in ruins.

03:17:51.920 --> 03:17:54.680
Financially, the fighting had destroyed large portions

03:17:54.680 --> 03:17:56.420
of England and her factories.

03:17:56.420 --> 03:17:58.700
While the Lend-Lease program had put the country

03:17:58.700 --> 03:18:02.150
in unimaginable amounts of debt with the US,

03:18:02.150 --> 03:18:04.250
abroad, the many arms of the empire

03:18:04.250 --> 03:18:05.990
that had fought for the British crown

03:18:05.990 --> 03:18:08.120
now demanded independence.

03:18:08.120 --> 03:18:09.470
There had already been a move

03:18:09.470 --> 03:18:12.620
into recognizing some of Britain's overseas territories

03:18:12.620 --> 03:18:16.730
as independent dominions, like Canada and Australia.

03:18:16.730 --> 03:18:19.220
But after the war, there was a clear shift

03:18:19.220 --> 03:18:21.530
towards recognizing all her territories

03:18:21.530 --> 03:18:23.450
as independent states.

03:18:23.450 --> 03:18:25.520
As colonial sentiment diminished,

03:18:25.520 --> 03:18:28.430
the British Empire was renamed and reorganized

03:18:28.430 --> 03:18:30.800
into the commonwealth of nations.

03:18:30.800 --> 03:18:32.750
Some stayed, while many chose

03:18:32.750 --> 03:18:35.840
to fully separate from the British crown.

03:18:35.840 --> 03:18:38.720
King George was named as head of the New Commonwealth,

03:18:38.720 --> 03:18:42.380
and as such, nations like Canada, Belize, Jamaica,

03:18:42.380 --> 03:18:45.950
Australia, and New Zealand still recognize the king

03:18:45.950 --> 03:18:50.000
as their head of state, but others sought full independence.

03:18:50.000 --> 03:18:51.710
India became a republic,

03:18:51.710 --> 03:18:54.890
while the nations of Bangladesh and Pakistan were formed

03:18:54.890 --> 03:18:57.290
during the British split from the subcontinent.

03:18:57.290 --> 03:18:59.330
Britain and her territory shrink

03:18:59.330 --> 03:19:03.257
and the empire where the sun never set was no more.

03:19:03.257 --> 03:19:06.140
But while the world celebrated peace,

03:19:06.140 --> 03:19:09.230
the king battled with the personal toll of the war.

03:19:09.230 --> 03:19:10.640
He was a heavy smoker

03:19:10.640 --> 03:19:13.370
and subsequently developed lung cancer

03:19:13.370 --> 03:19:16.130
alongside a laundry list of other ailments,

03:19:16.130 --> 03:19:17.660
and the stress of the conflict

03:19:17.660 --> 03:19:20.000
pushed his ill health over the edge.

03:19:20.000 --> 03:19:22.460
His later years saw his daughter, Elizabeth,

03:19:22.460 --> 03:19:24.680
take over in many of the royal duties

03:19:24.680 --> 03:19:26.390
he could no longer attend.

03:19:26.390 --> 03:19:29.990
On the 31st of January, 1953,

03:19:29.990 --> 03:19:32.420
King George made the trip to London airport,

03:19:32.420 --> 03:19:34.940
despite the advice of those closest to him,

03:19:34.940 --> 03:19:36.770
to see off Princess Elizabeth

03:19:36.770 --> 03:19:38.670
and her husband Philip Mountbatten

03:19:38.670 --> 03:19:41.960
as they embarked on a royal tour to Australia.

03:19:41.960 --> 03:19:44.270
It was his last public appearance.

03:19:44.270 --> 03:19:46.850
Six days later, King George VI

03:19:46.850 --> 03:19:51.470
was found dead in bed at Sandringham Castle at 56 years old.

03:19:51.470 --> 03:19:54.770
He was buried at St. George's Chapel at Windsor Castle.

03:19:54.770 --> 03:19:57.140
Upon hearing the news of her father's death,

03:19:57.140 --> 03:19:59.390
Princess Elizabeth returned to England

03:19:59.390 --> 03:20:01.384
and took her place in history.

03:20:01.384 --> 03:20:03.967
(gentle music)

03:20:05.360 --> 03:20:07.995
At 25 years of age, Princess Elizabeth

03:20:07.995 --> 03:20:12.410
ascended to the British throne, becoming Queen Elizabeth II.

03:20:12.410 --> 03:20:15.740
It was the first televised coronation ceremony

03:20:15.740 --> 03:20:17.210
in British history,

03:20:17.210 --> 03:20:21.590
and over 100 million people tuned in worldwide to watch it.

03:20:21.590 --> 03:20:24.650
Prior to this, though, drama had already been brewing

03:20:24.650 --> 03:20:26.060
close to the new queen.

03:20:26.060 --> 03:20:28.160
There was the issue of the royal house,

03:20:28.160 --> 03:20:31.040
which needed to be sorted prior to her ascension.

03:20:31.040 --> 03:20:32.780
It was custom for the royal house

03:20:32.780 --> 03:20:34.640
to take after the husband's name,

03:20:34.640 --> 03:20:36.860
which in this case was House Mountbatten

03:20:36.860 --> 03:20:38.600
after her husband Philip.

03:20:38.600 --> 03:20:41.300
The queen, however, had other ideas.

03:20:41.300 --> 03:20:44.390
She issued a declaration a month before the coronation

03:20:44.390 --> 03:20:47.960
stating that the royal house would go on as is,

03:20:47.960 --> 03:20:50.450
maintaining the name House Windsor.

03:20:50.450 --> 03:20:52.467
Philip complained telling people,

03:20:52.467 --> 03:20:54.560
"I am the only man in the country

03:20:54.560 --> 03:20:57.710
not allowed to give his name to his own children."

03:20:57.710 --> 03:21:00.560
Resentment against his role as royal consort

03:21:00.560 --> 03:21:03.380
would dominate the early years of their marriage,

03:21:03.380 --> 03:21:05.720
but Philip soon grew to be a loyal,

03:21:05.720 --> 03:21:08.720
comforting, and dutiful partner to the queen.

03:21:08.720 --> 03:21:10.910
Immediately after her coronation,

03:21:10.910 --> 03:21:13.850
Elizabeth and her husband embarked on a seven month tour

03:21:13.850 --> 03:21:17.000
of the newly established commonwealth of nations.

03:21:17.000 --> 03:21:19.820
She was the first reigning monarch of Australia

03:21:19.820 --> 03:21:22.400
and New Zealand to visit those nations.

03:21:22.400 --> 03:21:25.820
And it's estimated that half of the Australian population

03:21:25.820 --> 03:21:28.490
came out to see the queen on her state visit.

03:21:28.490 --> 03:21:30.890
Throughout her life, she traveled extensively

03:21:30.890 --> 03:21:32.900
around the world, and by the end,

03:21:32.900 --> 03:21:36.620
she was the most widely traveled head of state in history.

03:21:36.620 --> 03:21:38.270
She was the first British monarch

03:21:38.270 --> 03:21:39.860
to visit a communist country,

03:21:39.860 --> 03:21:42.440
visiting Yugoslavia in the '70s,

03:21:42.440 --> 03:21:45.560
and her visit to the People's Republic of China in the '80s

03:21:45.560 --> 03:21:49.070
was the first state visit by a British monarch to China

03:21:49.070 --> 03:21:52.280
in the two countries millennia long history.

03:21:52.280 --> 03:21:54.290
But once she had returned from her tour

03:21:54.290 --> 03:21:56.660
and was once again back in Westminster,

03:21:56.660 --> 03:21:58.550
the queen saw the political power

03:21:58.550 --> 03:22:01.220
of the monarchy diminish once again.

03:22:01.220 --> 03:22:03.470
You see, the ruling conservative party

03:22:03.470 --> 03:22:06.440
had no formal system for choosing a leader.

03:22:06.440 --> 03:22:10.520
So after the resignation of Anthony Eden as Prime Minister,

03:22:10.520 --> 03:22:12.530
the burden fell to Queen Elizabeth

03:22:12.530 --> 03:22:15.320
to decide who would form the next government.

03:22:15.320 --> 03:22:16.730
She met with a small number

03:22:16.730 --> 03:22:18.980
of council members and politicians

03:22:18.980 --> 03:22:22.700
and appointed their recommended candidate, Harold Macmillan.

03:22:22.700 --> 03:22:25.850
This, alongside the failure of the Suez Crisis,

03:22:25.850 --> 03:22:26.840
would earn the queen

03:22:26.840 --> 03:22:29.840
her first bit of major personal criticism.

03:22:29.840 --> 03:22:33.680
Lord Altrincham accused Elizabeth of being out of touch

03:22:33.680 --> 03:22:36.140
in a magazine which he owned and edited.

03:22:36.140 --> 03:22:39.620
This led to Altrincham being denounced by public figures

03:22:39.620 --> 03:22:41.960
and slapped by a member of the public

03:22:41.960 --> 03:22:44.210
for his comments against the queen.

03:22:44.210 --> 03:22:47.240
Six years later, Macmillan himself retired

03:22:47.240 --> 03:22:49.160
and the queen was once again tasked

03:22:49.160 --> 03:22:50.810
with choosing a replacement.

03:22:50.810 --> 03:22:54.170
She selected Alec Douglas-Home as Prime Minister,

03:22:54.170 --> 03:22:56.720
but again drew criticism from making her decision

03:22:56.720 --> 03:22:59.900
based on a small number of close advisors.

03:22:59.900 --> 03:23:02.810
In 1965, the Conservative Party

03:23:02.810 --> 03:23:06.260
established a formal mechanism for choosing their leader,

03:23:06.260 --> 03:23:09.920
and the queen's direct involvement in politics was gone,

03:23:09.920 --> 03:23:11.960
but a further loss of political power

03:23:11.960 --> 03:23:13.460
was just the beginning.

03:23:13.460 --> 03:23:17.270
The process of decolonization that had begun in earnest

03:23:17.270 --> 03:23:20.600
during her father's reign had sped up in recent years.

03:23:20.600 --> 03:23:23.214
Africa rapidly shed the colonial shackles

03:23:23.214 --> 03:23:25.310
that Britain had imposed on her

03:23:25.310 --> 03:23:28.670
as 20 African nations gained full independence

03:23:28.670 --> 03:23:31.610
throughout the 1960s and '70s.

03:23:31.610 --> 03:23:33.800
As her power overseas weakened,

03:23:33.800 --> 03:23:36.530
Britain sought to join the European Community,

03:23:36.530 --> 03:23:39.080
a precursor to the European Union,

03:23:39.080 --> 03:23:41.810
a goal that achieved in 1973.

03:23:41.810 --> 03:23:43.820
There was great concern during this time

03:23:43.820 --> 03:23:46.460
about the power and influence of the crown,

03:23:46.460 --> 03:23:48.560
especially amongst her dominions.

03:23:48.560 --> 03:23:51.200
Australian Republicanism was on the rise,

03:23:51.200 --> 03:23:53.677
and Canada's prime minister, Pierre Trudeau,

03:23:53.677 --> 03:23:57.650
seemed to wholly disregard the reagent and her importance,

03:23:57.650 --> 03:24:00.830
sliding down the banisters at Buckingham Palace

03:24:00.830 --> 03:24:03.170
and pirouetting behind the queen's back

03:24:03.170 --> 03:24:05.210
during a state visit to London.

03:24:05.210 --> 03:24:07.880
A few years later when Canadian politicians

03:24:07.880 --> 03:24:10.340
were sent to London to discuss the patriation

03:24:10.340 --> 03:24:12.440
of the Canadian constitution,

03:24:12.440 --> 03:24:15.680
they found Queen Elizabeth to be better informed

03:24:15.680 --> 03:24:19.190
than any of the British politicians and bureaucrats.

03:24:19.190 --> 03:24:22.520
Canada would get its independence in 1982,

03:24:22.520 --> 03:24:25.670
but the queen maintained her role as their head of state.

03:24:25.670 --> 03:24:27.410
She suffered great embarrassment

03:24:27.410 --> 03:24:30.800
when the surveyor of the queen's pictures, Anthony Blunt,

03:24:30.800 --> 03:24:34.640
was unmasked as a communist spy, and during the '80s,

03:24:34.640 --> 03:24:36.860
numerous attempts at her life were made,

03:24:36.860 --> 03:24:38.420
none proving successful,

03:24:38.420 --> 03:24:41.360
but each growing in danger and intensity.

03:24:41.360 --> 03:24:44.390
During a Trooping of the Color in 1981,

03:24:44.390 --> 03:24:47.480
six shots were fired at the queen in close range

03:24:47.480 --> 03:24:50.090
as she rode her horse down the mall in London.

03:24:50.090 --> 03:24:53.000
That October, during a state visit to New Zealand,

03:24:53.000 --> 03:24:55.910
a 17-year-old Christopher John Lewis

03:24:55.910 --> 03:24:58.850
fired a shot from a 22 rifle at the queen

03:24:58.850 --> 03:25:00.770
as she stepped out of her vehicle.

03:25:00.770 --> 03:25:04.250
A year later, an intruder broke into Buckingham Palace

03:25:04.250 --> 03:25:06.560
and sat watching the queen sleep.

03:25:06.560 --> 03:25:08.840
When she awoke, the two calmly chatted

03:25:08.840 --> 03:25:11.720
while Elizabeth waited for palace police to arrive.

03:25:11.720 --> 03:25:14.900
In all instances, the queen escaped harm.

03:25:14.900 --> 03:25:17.810
Throughout all this, she had managed to endear herself

03:25:17.810 --> 03:25:20.450
to the public, showing immense poise and grace

03:25:20.450 --> 03:25:23.420
during each and every attempt on her life.

03:25:23.420 --> 03:25:26.210
Royal popularity was relatively high,

03:25:26.210 --> 03:25:29.660
but the 1990s would prove to be a difficult decade

03:25:29.660 --> 03:25:31.340
for not just the queen,

03:25:31.340 --> 03:25:34.310
but the monarchical institution as a whole.

03:25:34.310 --> 03:25:36.680
During a speech to mark her ruby jubilee,

03:25:36.680 --> 03:25:39.470
the queen commented on her annus horribilis,

03:25:39.470 --> 03:25:42.920
or horrible year, in 1992.

03:25:42.920 --> 03:25:44.480
Many of her children had suffered

03:25:44.480 --> 03:25:47.510
highly public breakdowns in their marriages.

03:25:47.510 --> 03:25:50.060
Prince Andrew had separated from his wife Sarah,

03:25:50.060 --> 03:25:52.400
while Princess Anne had officially divorced

03:25:52.400 --> 03:25:54.020
Captain Mark Phillips.

03:25:54.020 --> 03:25:56.630
But the biggest blow to royal popularity

03:25:56.630 --> 03:25:59.480
came with her eldest son, Prince Charles,

03:25:59.480 --> 03:26:02.360
and his now estranged wife Diana.

03:26:02.360 --> 03:26:04.670
On the 7th of June, Diana published

03:26:04.670 --> 03:26:08.360
her tell-all memoir, "Diana: The True Story,"

03:26:08.360 --> 03:26:10.580
revealing all the problems in her marriage

03:26:10.580 --> 03:26:13.460
and the stifling atmosphere of the royal family.

03:26:13.460 --> 03:26:15.380
It went into sorted detail

03:26:15.380 --> 03:26:18.470
about Charles's affair with Camilla Parker Bowles

03:26:18.470 --> 03:26:21.740
and made Diana incredibly popular with the public,

03:26:21.740 --> 03:26:24.740
all while bringing down the reputation of the crown

03:26:24.740 --> 03:26:27.710
and besmirching the heir to the British throne.

03:26:27.710 --> 03:26:30.080
A fire broke out in Buckingham Palace

03:26:30.080 --> 03:26:33.290
in November of that year, and it was under all these events

03:26:33.290 --> 03:26:37.520
and more that the queen remarked, "1992 is not a year

03:26:37.520 --> 03:26:40.790
on which I shall look back with undiluted pleasure.

03:26:40.790 --> 03:26:44.180
In the words of one of my more sympathetic correspondence,

03:26:44.180 --> 03:26:47.420
it has turned out to be an annus horribilis."

03:26:47.420 --> 03:26:49.610
The '90s saw the crown combat the rise

03:26:49.610 --> 03:26:51.170
of tabloid journalism.

03:26:51.170 --> 03:26:54.050
Sensational headlines and growing personal dramas

03:26:54.050 --> 03:26:57.740
made the royal family a frequent front page presence.

03:26:57.740 --> 03:27:00.500
In 1997, Diana, who by now

03:27:00.500 --> 03:27:02.690
had officially separated from Charles,

03:27:02.690 --> 03:27:05.600
died in a high speed car crash in France

03:27:05.600 --> 03:27:07.910
after being followed by paparazzi.

03:27:07.910 --> 03:27:11.180
The queen took her young grandchildren to Balmoral Castle

03:27:11.180 --> 03:27:13.550
so that the young boys could grieve in private

03:27:13.550 --> 03:27:16.160
away from the intense media coverage.

03:27:16.160 --> 03:27:18.290
But the crown silence and seclusion

03:27:18.290 --> 03:27:20.960
led to a wave of public outrage.

03:27:20.960 --> 03:27:22.293
Later, rumors would arise

03:27:22.293 --> 03:27:25.040
that the queen had ordered Diana's death,

03:27:25.040 --> 03:27:27.290
but these claims are unsubstantiated,

03:27:27.290 --> 03:27:30.680
and a toxicology report on the driver showed he was drunk

03:27:30.680 --> 03:27:32.240
at the time of the accident.

03:27:32.240 --> 03:27:33.800
Before the end of the century,

03:27:33.800 --> 03:27:35.690
the queen would play an integral part

03:27:35.690 --> 03:27:38.270
in the devolution of the UK parliament,

03:27:38.270 --> 03:27:42.200
formally opening the new legislatures in Wales and Scotland.

03:27:42.200 --> 03:27:45.380
In 2002, she celebrated her golden jubilee

03:27:45.380 --> 03:27:49.400
to enormous crowds that surprised even the queen herself.

03:27:49.400 --> 03:27:51.950
A decade later, she would see the same crowds

03:27:51.950 --> 03:27:54.230
celebrating her diamond jubilee.

03:27:54.230 --> 03:27:57.950
That summer, the queen opened the 2012 Olympic Games,

03:27:57.950 --> 03:27:59.480
becoming the first head of state

03:27:59.480 --> 03:28:01.760
to open two Olympic ceremonies

03:28:01.760 --> 03:28:05.930
after her role in the 1972 Montreal Olympics.

03:28:05.930 --> 03:28:09.110
But as she crept steadily into old age,

03:28:09.110 --> 03:28:12.950
the well-traveled and beloved queen began to slow down.

03:28:12.950 --> 03:28:16.100
She had a number of surgeries and minor health scares,

03:28:16.100 --> 03:28:18.890
and officially gave up driving on public roads

03:28:18.890 --> 03:28:22.790
after an accident involving her husband in 2019.

03:28:22.790 --> 03:28:26.150
In September, 2015, Queen Elizabeth II

03:28:26.150 --> 03:28:30.050
became the longest reigning monarch in British history,

03:28:30.050 --> 03:28:34.970
overtaking Queen Victoria who had ruled over 150 years ago.

03:28:34.970 --> 03:28:38.180
A few years later, she became the first British monarch

03:28:38.180 --> 03:28:40.520
to celebrate a sapphire jubilee,

03:28:40.520 --> 03:28:43.790
as well as a platinum wedding anniversary to Philip.

03:28:43.790 --> 03:28:46.160
She was present at the marriage of her grandson,

03:28:46.160 --> 03:28:48.080
an eventual heir to the throne,

03:28:48.080 --> 03:28:50.180
Prince William and Kate Middleton,

03:28:50.180 --> 03:28:52.040
as well as the marriage of Prince Harry

03:28:52.040 --> 03:28:53.840
and actress Meghan Markle.

03:28:53.840 --> 03:28:57.650
In 2022, she celebrated her platinum jubilee,

03:28:57.650 --> 03:29:01.070
marking 70 years on the British throne.

03:29:01.070 --> 03:29:04.490
That year, she became the second longest living monarch

03:29:04.490 --> 03:29:08.450
in history behind King Louis XIV of France,

03:29:08.450 --> 03:29:11.150
who had ruled for 72 years.

03:29:11.150 --> 03:29:14.870
By this time, though, the queen was a visibly much frailer

03:29:14.870 --> 03:29:16.910
and soon passed public appearances

03:29:16.910 --> 03:29:19.880
and engagements over to her son Charles.

03:29:19.880 --> 03:29:22.370
On the 8th of September, the queen fell ill

03:29:22.370 --> 03:29:24.620
and her family rushed from all over the globe

03:29:24.620 --> 03:29:26.000
to be by her side.

03:29:26.000 --> 03:29:29.480
She died peacefully at 15:10 British Standard Time

03:29:29.480 --> 03:29:33.770
at Balmoral Castle in 2022, age 96.

03:29:33.770 --> 03:29:37.070
Her reign spanned an immensely transformative period

03:29:37.070 --> 03:29:40.850
of not just royal history, but world history.

03:29:40.850 --> 03:29:43.820
The crown had undoubtedly fallen in power,

03:29:43.820 --> 03:29:45.710
but the queen in her conduct ensured

03:29:45.710 --> 03:29:47.690
that it held onto its prestige.

03:29:47.690 --> 03:29:51.140
She was a well-respected stateswoman, and during her reign,

03:29:51.140 --> 03:29:53.750
her popularity remains steadily positive

03:29:53.750 --> 03:29:56.270
despite moments of tension and drama.

03:29:56.270 --> 03:29:59.270
She made the transition into the technological age

03:29:59.270 --> 03:30:02.960
with all its trappings seamlessly and with grace,

03:30:02.960 --> 03:30:06.590
modernized the role of the monarch for the 21st century,

03:30:06.590 --> 03:30:10.250
and earned the respect of people all over the globe.

03:30:10.250 --> 03:30:11.990
Her death was widely mourned

03:30:11.990 --> 03:30:14.870
and attended by 500 heads of state.

03:30:14.870 --> 03:30:16.550
In her wake, the British throne

03:30:16.550 --> 03:30:18.773
was left to her son, Charles.

03:30:19.780 --> 03:30:22.490
(light music)

03:30:22.490 --> 03:30:25.280
Crowned on the 6th of May, 2023,

03:30:25.280 --> 03:30:28.798
King Charles III is the latest in a long line

03:30:28.798 --> 03:30:30.860
to sit on the British throne.

03:30:30.860 --> 03:30:32.150
He has been an active member

03:30:32.150 --> 03:30:34.190
of the royal family since his youth,

03:30:34.190 --> 03:30:37.790
speaking out in support of climate change, royal reforms,

03:30:37.790 --> 03:30:41.180
and sustainable farming since the 1960s.

03:30:41.180 --> 03:30:45.140
He is high profile, and bitter divorce from Diana Spencer

03:30:45.140 --> 03:30:46.730
made the prince a polarizing

03:30:46.730 --> 03:30:50.300
and at times unpopular figure in the kingdom.

03:30:50.300 --> 03:30:52.940
His subsequent marriage to Camilla Parker Bowles

03:30:52.940 --> 03:30:54.920
a year after the death of Diana

03:30:54.920 --> 03:30:57.500
drew widespread public scrutiny,

03:30:57.500 --> 03:30:59.570
but his reputation held on

03:30:59.570 --> 03:31:01.970
and he has since become an outspoken advocate

03:31:01.970 --> 03:31:05.330
for environmentalism, historical conservation,

03:31:05.330 --> 03:31:08.240
and a reduction in size of the British monarchy.

03:31:08.240 --> 03:31:11.690
While with Diana, he had two sons, Prince William,

03:31:11.690 --> 03:31:14.390
heir to the British throne, and Prince Harry.

03:31:14.390 --> 03:31:17.690
He has maintained a close relationship to both boys.

03:31:17.690 --> 03:31:21.290
However, after the marriage of Harry and Meghan in 2018

03:31:21.290 --> 03:31:23.600
and the subsequent fallout between Harry

03:31:23.600 --> 03:31:25.280
and the royal institution,

03:31:25.280 --> 03:31:28.160
the pair have been increasingly estranged.

03:31:28.160 --> 03:31:31.520
Ascending to the throne at 73 years of age,

03:31:31.520 --> 03:31:34.310
King Charles III became the oldest person

03:31:34.310 --> 03:31:36.050
to be crown king of Britain,

03:31:36.050 --> 03:31:38.840
and his coronation took place at Westminster Abbey,

03:31:38.840 --> 03:31:41.030
as customs still dictates.

03:31:41.030 --> 03:31:42.260
Only time will tell

03:31:42.260 --> 03:31:44.660
how the reign of Charles III will pan out.

03:31:44.660 --> 03:31:48.290
Despite his age, the kingdom is undergoing immense change

03:31:48.290 --> 03:31:50.420
both politically and socially.

03:31:50.420 --> 03:31:54.200
And if his predecessors' long lives or anything to go by,

03:31:54.200 --> 03:31:56.570
Charles should sit for a good while still.

03:31:56.570 --> 03:31:58.550
Britain has now officially separated

03:31:58.550 --> 03:32:00.200
from the European Union,

03:32:00.200 --> 03:32:03.380
migration to the island remains higher than ever before,

03:32:03.380 --> 03:32:04.820
and the country is suffering

03:32:04.820 --> 03:32:08.060
through some of the worst recessions in its history,

03:32:08.060 --> 03:32:11.090
putting untold strain on the national health service

03:32:11.090 --> 03:32:12.860
and welfare systems.

03:32:12.860 --> 03:32:15.470
The Conservative Party have enjoyed over a decade

03:32:15.470 --> 03:32:17.090
of uninterrupted rule,

03:32:17.090 --> 03:32:20.000
and social tension calling for government reform

03:32:20.000 --> 03:32:22.100
grows louder every year.

03:32:22.100 --> 03:32:24.950
This is the kingdom Charles has inherited.

03:32:24.950 --> 03:32:27.920
By comparison, he is a very modern king.

03:32:27.920 --> 03:32:30.050
He understands that the role of the monarchy

03:32:30.050 --> 03:32:34.520
must continue to change, or else, risk being left behind.

03:32:34.520 --> 03:32:38.300
It remains to be seen, will he rise to the challenge,

03:32:38.300 --> 03:32:43.300
or could King Charles III be the last king of Great Britain?

